<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 0221EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     01-12 0824</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,810</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farmers Union Opposes Decoupling Payments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Farmers Union says it will wage a
lobbying battle in Congress against a proposal to let farmers
collect federal subsidies without regard to the kind of crops they
produce.
   NFU president Leland Swenson said Wednesday that the idea, known
as ``decoupling,'' would be ``devastating for farmers and rural
communities, endanger the environment and destabilize the position
of Third World farmers.''
   Swenson said at a news conference that decoupling would be a
``short-term welfare program'' and will be opposed vigorously by NFU
lobbyists.
   The idea of decoupling has been around for years but has not had
great support on Capitol Hill. One of the early decisions by the
incoming Bush administration will be whether to embrace decoupling
as a way of containing government farm costs.
   Under some versions of decoupling, federal payments targeted to
farmers would gradually be reduced over four or five years and
perhaps then be eliminated altogether as producers are weaned from
federal crop subsidies.
   The NFU's main rival, the American Farm Bureau Federation, at one
time supported decoupling but since has backed off to give it a
closer look.
   One of the biggest advocates is the Heritage Foundation, a
Washington-based conservative think tank, which recently issued a
report saying that one of the first jobs of the Bush administration
should be to cut subsidies and ``get farmers off the dole.''
   Decoupling, the Heritage report said, would allow federal
payments to farmers to be based on a flat rate and targeted to those
most in need. As it has been for more than half a century, payments
now are pegged to specific kinds of crops and levels of production _
the larger the farm, the larger the subsidy.
   Under decoupling, farmers would simply be given a cash payment
and then be free to grow or not grow any crop they choose.
   ``Planting decisions would then be based on market signals _
consumer demand for a product _ rather than on what is required by
Washington,'' the Heritage report said.
   Charles Grizzle, who wrote the Heritage report, said in a
telephone interview that decoupling makes sense as a way of getting
crop programs away from government subsidies and into a
market-oriented economic environment.
   ``In my judgment, it's a charade now to think that most of the
production that is linked to subsidy payments is being grown for the
marketplace,'' Grizzle said. ``It's a mindset, almost like a
crutch.''
   Swenson, however, called decoupling proposals a ``cop-out'' and
released a report analyzing a decoupling bill introduced by Sen.
Rudy Boschwitz, R-Minn., in 1985 as the Family Farm Protection and
Full Production Act. Swenson said the bill continues to have some
support in Congress, along with backing from big grain companies
such as Cargill Inc.
   ``It's really a cop-out in addressing the real issue of adopting
and implementing a farm program which enhances the market price for
agricultural commodities,'' Swenson said. ``It implies that the
family farm structure of agriculture is not important.''
   The analysis used figures attributed to the Institute for Trade
and Agriculture of St. Paul, Minn., showing that the Boschwitz bill
would reduce federal price support loans sharply for major crops,
including wheat to $1.60 per bushel from $2.06 this year, and corn
to $1.30 per bushel from the 1989 rate of $1.65.
   ``Lowering of world prices, a result of decoupling, would
aggravate the situation of Third World farmers, who are our best
potential customers for U.S. food exports,'' Swenson said.
   The NFU, he said, will draft its own alternative to decoupling to
``assure consumers an adequate and dependable supply of food'' and
``enhance the market price of agricultural commodities.''
   Although Swenson did not disclose details of what NFU's plan
might include, he said it would ``reduce the budget impact of farm
programs'' and allow for continued expansion of agricultural exports.
   The 1988 drought helped siphon off huge stockpiles of U.S. grain,
boosting market prices for wheat to an average of $3.89 per bushel
last month from $2.70 a year earlier. Corn in December, according to
the Agriculture Department, averaged $2.54 per bushel, compared with
the year-earlier mark of $1.72 per bushel.
   Swenson was asked if the NFU would recommend an increase in
federal price supports to as much as current market prices. He
replied, ``Or higher.''
   The Reagan administration for eight years has been committed to a
market-oriented farm policy, less reliance on federal controls and
freer world trade. Those goals are expected to continue under the
Bush administration.
   But Swenson is not convinced at this time that foreign countries
will go along with current U.S. agricultural trade objectives in the
Bush administration any more than they have in the Reagan years.
   ``There isn't such a thing as a free market,'' Swenson said. ``It
doesn't exist, will not exist, either in this country or any other
major exporting country in the world.''
</TEXT>
