<FIRST>r i PM-Father'sWill     01-12 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Father's Will,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dairy Worker Receives $160,000 From Father He Never Saw</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   STOCKTON-ON-TEES, England (AP) _ Michael Minns received $160,000
from the father he never knew and thought was killed in World War II.
   Minns, 44, said Wednesday that he grew up believing his soldier
father, James Minns, died in the war, and was astonished when
lawyers tracked him down and told him that for 40 years his father
was in a hospital 50 miles away.
   Minns, a dairy worker and father of four, said he then discovered
his father had not had a visitor in the hospital for 38 years.
   ``I'm heartbroken,'' he said. ``It would have meant a lot to meet
him.''
   Minns, offspring of a wartime romance, was born illegitimate. He
was brought up by his aunt, who died when he was 15.
   He said he only learned his father was a war-stress patient at
St. Nicholas Hospital in Gosforth in northeast England after he died
two years ago.
   ``The news was a considerable shock,'' he said. ``I feel bitter
because certain relatives knew about him and kept it to themselves.''
   ``The money isn't important. If it had been 90 million pounds
($160 million) it wouldn't make up for the fact I've been robbed of
my father.''
</TEXT>
