<FIRST>r w PM-DemocraticChairman     01-12 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Democratic Chairman,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brown Wins Labor Backing In DNC Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The AFL-CIO is supporting longtime Democratic
Party activist Ronald H. Brown's bid to be the next party chairman,
giving the Washington attorney labor's influential backing in the
five-man race.
   The AFL-CIO announced the endorsement Wednesday following a
90-minute meeting of president Lane Kirkland and 16 other members of
its national political committee.
   The endorsement was announced in a two-sentence statement that
said Brown was the ``consensus'' choice of those at the meeting.
   It did not list any reason for the endorsement or refer to public
endorsements of another candidate, former Rep. James V. Stanton of
Ohio, by building-trades unions affiliated with AFL-CIO.
   Of the 404 votes on the DNC, 46 are cast by union
representatives. But labor's influence is considered far greater
than those numbers suggest. All five candidates to succeed Paul G.
Kirk Jr. met with AFL-CIO leaders last week in hopes of securing the
endorsement.
   ``This endorsement represents a vote of confidence by the
representatives of the working men and women of this country,''
Brown said in a statement.
   Brown and Richard Weiner, the Michigan state party chairman, are
viewed as the front-runners to replace Kirk. Brown has the support
of many national Democrats, but few if any of them vote. Weiner's
base stems from his role as president of the Assocation of State
Party Chairs.
   The other candidates are former congressmen Jim Jones of Oklahoma
and Michael Barnes of Maryland. All five last week began a series of
joint regional meetings around the country. The DNC will pick a
successor to Kirk next month.
   Brown is a veteran party insider who advised the unsuccessful
presidential campaign of Jesse Jackson.
   Critics of Brown's candidacy argue that his election would
suggest that the party is lining up behind Jackson's liberal stands.
Among such critics is Jones, a moderate who said Wednesday evening
that his ``campaign continues to move forward'' despite the labor
endorsement of Brown.
</TEXT>
