<HEAD>Bush Reported to Pledge Support to Angolan Rebel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angolan rebel leader Jonas Savimbi has
President-elect George Bush's assurance of continued U.S. support
until the Angolan government reaches a settlement with him,
according to a published report today.
   The Washington Post reported that the assurance was contained in
a Jan. 6 letter from Bush.
   The vice president also said the incoming Bush administration
will push other governments to work for an agreement between Angola
and Savimbi's UNITA movement, according to the newspaper.
   In the letter, Bush promised to ``continue all appropriate and
effective assistance to UNITA'' until Savimbi's political goals are
reached.
   That means covert military aid, which has cost about $15 million
annually for the past two years, the newspaper said, quoting an
unidentified Bush aide.
   On Dec. 22, Angola, South Africa and Cuba signed an agreement
providing for the phased withdrawal of Cuban troops from Angola,
along with the independence of Namibia, the neighboring territory
which is administered by South Africa.
   The United States has no formal ties with the government of
Angola, partly because of the presence of the 50,000 Cuban troops.
