<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Brazil-FastTrain     01-12 0124</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Brazil-Fast Train,0125</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brazil Will Have High Speed Train</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brazil will introduce Latin America's
first high speed train, which will connect its two main cities, Rio
de Janeiro and Sao Paulo, about 280 miles apart, in two hours,
authorities say.
   According to initial studies, the train will be able to exceed
132 mph.
   A Transport Ministry source said Wednesday that bidding among
national and foreign companies interested in installing and
operating the line will begin Jan. 28 and construction should start
in about a year.
   The winning company will have the right to operate the high speed
train for a period of from 30 to 50 years and will have complete
control in setting ticket prices, the source said.
</TEXT>
