<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0425 to correct cycle designator</HEAD>
<HEAD>HUD Selects Federal Property That Can Be Used For Homeless</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Housing and Urban
Development's latest list of property identified as suitable for the
homeless includes national parkland, a naval submarine base and a
lock and dam site.
   Those sites are included in a list of 38 pieces of federal
property identified by HUD on Wednesday as suitable for the homeless.
   In announcing the decision, HUD said the new list of 17 buildings
and 21 land sites was being submitted to the General Services
Administration and the Department of Health and Human Services.
   GSA and HHS will oversee a process in which states, local
government units and private non-profit organizations may submit
applications to use the facilities for the homeless.
   Wednesday's action brings to 148 the number of federal properties
_ 65 buildings and 83 land sites _ judged suitable for aiding the
homeless.
   HUD is also reviewing for suitability more than 1,600 unused or
underutilized properties owned by federal landholding agencies. The
department is due to complete this review no later than the end of
February.
   Wednesday's action was taken to meet a deadline set on Dec. 14 by
U.S. District Court Judge Oliver Gasch.
   In Wednesday's announcement, locations containing unused or
underutilized federally owned buildings deemed suitable for homeless
facilities were listed as:
   Clear Air Force Station, Alaska; Hot Springs National Park, Ark.;
Carbondale Mining Technology Center, Carterville, Ill.; GSA Depot,
Watertown, Mass.; Fort Snelling, Minn.; Army Reserve Center,
Springfield, Mo.; Magdalena, N.M.; Tonopah, Nev.; Fire Island
National Seashore, Patchogue, N.Y.; Hammond, Ore.; Aguadilla, Puerto
Rico; GSA Depot, Davisville, R.I.; and Mineral Wells, Texas.
   Locations containing suitable federally owned land were listed as:
   Fort Wainwright annex, Fairbanks, Alaska; Andrews Lock and Dam,
Henry County, Ala.; U.S. Coast Guard Training Center, Petaluma,
Calif.; San Gabriel River Channel, Azusa, Calif.; Denver, Colo.;
Gainesville, Ga.; Andrews Lock and Dam, Early County, Ga.; Kings
Bay, Ga.; Homewood, Ill.; Baton Rouge, La.; Sudbury-Hudson, Mass.;
Andrews Air Force Base, Md.; Camp Butner, N.C.; Gallup Indian
Center, N.M.; Fort Hamilton, Brooklyn, N.Y.; Sandusky, Ohio; Jackson
County, Okla.; Lebanon, Pa.; Amarillo, Texas; and Bardane, W.Va.
   Some locations included more than one piece of property.
