<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Mailings Among Lawmakers' Many Fringe Benefits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress is asking for a record $114 million
for its official mailings in 1990, which is, not coincidentally, an
election year.
   The figure is included in President Reagan's proposed budget but
Congress actually draws up its own spending proposal. It is normal
for Congress to about double its mailing costs in election years,
even though campaign materials cannot be sent with taxpayer money.
   For fiscal 1989, Congress has budgeted $60.9 million, according
to budget documents. In the election year of 1988, however,
congressional mailings cost $113.3 million.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Fed Proposed Tightening Disclosure Requirements</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Reserve Board is asking that
lenders be required to provide home equity loan borrowers with more
information about the cost of such loans.
   Under the rules proposed Wednesday, lenders generally would have
to provide potential borrowers with a written explanation of the
terms and conditions of the loan at the time of loan application and
before any non-refundable fee is collected.
   The disclosures must include a full explanation of how the
interest rate and monthly payments might change and the
circumstances under which immediate repayment of the loan could be
demanded.
   Congress has prohibited lenders from unilaterally changing the
terms of the loan after it has been taken out. The Federal Reserve
rules would allow changes, such as providing a lower monthly payment
over a longer term, provided the borrower agrees to the changes in
writing.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>More MIA Remains Being Returned</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vietnamese government is returning the
suspected remains of 25 Americans killed in the Vietnam War and also
let five U.S. teams of experts in the country for a search mission.
   The announcement Wednesday comes less than a month after Vietnam
transferred the largest single group of remains ever to the United
States since the war's end _ 38 individuals.
   The repatriation of the 25 remains will occur Jan. 23, with an
American cargo plane flying to Hanoi and transporting the remains to
the U.S. Army's Central Identification Laboratory in Honolulu,
Hawaii, the Pentagon said.
   ``The U.S. government appreciates the initiative taken by Vietnam
to repatriate these remains and hopes to continue the increasing
joint cooperation to resolve this long-standing humanitarian
issue,'' the Pentagon said.
</TEXT>
