<FIRST>r i PM-Chemical-Glance     01-12 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chemical-Glance,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Highlights of Final Declaration</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Chemical Conference, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Highlights of the final declaration adopted
Wednesday by the 149 nations participating in the five-day
Conference on the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons.
   The non-binding declaration:
   _ Reaffirms the 1925 Geneva Protocol prohibiting the use of
chemical weapons, but not their production and storage.
   _ Calls for global negotiations in Geneva to comprehensively and
verifiably ban the development, production and storage of chemical
arms.
   _ Encourages all states to quickly resolve their differences
about chemical weapons and to adopt and participate in an agreement.
   _ Asks states to exercise restraint and observe the spirit of the
conference, even though no consensus has been reached on specifics.
   _ Expresses ``concern'' at recent violations of the 1925 protocol.
   _ Urges giving the United Nations secretary-general more power to
investigate chemical weapons use.
   _ Supports humanitarian assistance given to victims of chemical
weapons.
   _ Refers to a 1978 U.N. document calling for general disarmament
without specifically linking the control of nuclear and chemical
weapons, as Arab nations had wanted.
</TEXT>
