<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     01-12 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Dips, Stocks Unchanged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar lost ground against the Japanese yen on
Thursday, while share prices closed unchanged on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange.
   The dollar finished at 126.12 yen, down 0.83 yen from Wednesday's
126.95-yen close. The currency, which opened lower at 125.90 yen
after its overnight decline on overseas markets, moved in a range of
125.90-126.22 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 136.94-point
gainer for a record 31,143.45 close on Wednesday, finished unchanged
from the previous day's close.
   The U.S. currency's lower opening in Tokyo followed concerted
dollar-selling overnight by the U.S. Federal Reserve and several
European central banks on overseas markets, dealers said.
   Central banks in several European countries including West
Germany, Switzerland, Britain and Italy intervened in exchange
markets Wednesday to brake the dollar's recent rise against their
respective currencies.
   The dollar was firmer due to buying by Japanese investors, a
dealer with a major commercial bank said. They see the dollar's
early January rally as indicating the currency will not fall right
away to the low 120-yen range or below, as had been widely expected,
the dealer said.
   As long as investors do not anticipate the dollar's rapid
decline, their strong appetite for the currency will continue, he
added.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, market players were mainly selling
issues to prevent the index from rising further, as well as to
collect profits after the Nikkei's sharp increase since last
Thursday, said a dealer with Nomura Securities, Japan's largest
brokerage.
   Trading normally slows down after a few days of consecutive
gains, he added.
</TEXT>
