<SECOND>PM-Kindergarten Gun,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>5-Year-Old Brought Loaded Gun To School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A kindergarten student brought a loaded automatic
handgun to his school before handing it barrel-first to his teacher,
who was surprised to find it wasn't a toy, authorities said.
   ``Either luck or good fortune was on my side,'' the shaken
teacher, Donald Miller, said through United Federation of Teachers
spokesman Bert Shanas.
   ``I'm just saying a prayer of thanks when I think of what could
have happened to the kids in the cafeteria or myself.''
   The 5-year-old boy, whose name was not released, told school
authorities that ``an unknown man put the gun in his pocket on the
way to school,'' said police spokeswoman Sgt. Diane Kubler.
   Police contacted the boy's mother and were trying to determine
where the gun came from, Board of Education spokesman Frank Sobrino
said.
   The teacher thought the gun was a toy when it was called to his
attention by another child in the cafeteria at a Bronx elementary
school Wednesday morning, Shanas said.
   When Miller asked the boy for it, he handed it over with the
barrel pointed at Miller's stomach, Shanas said. The teacher took it
to the office, where a custodian confirmed it was real, cocked and
loaded.
