<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     01-12 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls Against Yen, Stocks Unchanged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell today against the Japanese yen,
while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's leading index closed unchanged from
the previous day.
   The dollar, which had gained 1.25 yen on Wednesday, fell back by
0.83 yen today, closing at 126.12 yen. It opened today at 125.90
yen, and ranged between 125.90 and 126.22 yen.
   The U.S. currency's sharply lower opening in Tokyo followed
concerted dollar-selling intervention by European and U.S. central
banks on overseas markets overnight, dealers said.
   Central banks in several European countries including West
Germany, Switzerland, Britain and Italy intervened in exchange
markets Wednesday to brake the dollar's recent rise against their
currencies.
   But news of the intervention did not sharply discourage
dollar-buying in Tokyo, as market players expected U.S. monetary
authorities to keep high interest rates, said a dealer with
Mitsubishi Bank, speaking on condition of anonymity. Higher interest
rates make dollar-denominated investments more attractive.
   ``But the current dollar-buying trend will slow down as next
week's U.S. monthly trade report approaches,'' the dealer added.
   Another dealer at a major commercial bank said that as long as
investors do not anticipate a rapid decline in the dollar, their
strong appetite for the currency will continue.
   On the stock exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which
climbed 136.94 points Wednesday to a record high close of 31,143.45,
finished at the same level today. In the afternoon session, the
index regained the 86.50 points lost in morning trading.
   Dealers said speculative investors' buying interest, targeted on
steel issues Thursday afternoon, helped the market's main barometer
to recover.
   Trading was active, with volume traded on the first section
estimated at 1.2 billion shares.
</TEXT>
