<FIRST>r i PM-Sweden-Schools     01-12 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sweden-Schools,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Protest Proposed Teachers Wage Cuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estimated 10,000 students, most of
them high-school age or younger, marched on the Education Ministry
to protest a proposed cut in teachers' pay.
   Some schools let their students off for the mile-long march,
Others counted participation as a classroom exercise in social
science courses. Some students simply cut classes to be there.
   ``Who Will Rule Sweden In 20 Years, Educated People or
Uneducated'' said one placard.
   The rally came a day after Finance Minister Kjell Olof Feldt
presented a budget bill to Parliament that trimmed $27 million, or
about 0.5 percent, off teachers' wages.
   Feldt said teachers' salaries went up last year by more than the
5.6 percent limit set by Parliament.
   The cut was condemned by all five opposition parties, which
threaten to unite to kill the measure.
   Critics say schools are run down, textbooks tattered and torn,
qualified teachers too few and meals in the free school canteens are
tasteless.
   Primary school teachers earn up to $2,000 a month, while the
best-qualified secondary-school teachers earn up to $2,270 a month
after 15 years in the profession.
