<FIRST>r a PM-HudsonLawsuit     01-12 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hudson Lawsuit,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>AIDS Infection Allegedly Withheld From Screen Idol's Lover</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note Contents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rock Hudson's former homosexual lover said the
actor began losing weight and having night sweats in June 1984, but
it wasn't until a year later that he learned Hudson was stricken
with AIDS.
   ``I was sitting alone in Rock's home. I turned on the television
set: `Rock Hudson had acquired immune deficiency syndrome,''' Marc
Christian told a Superior Court jury Wednesday in his $11 million
lawsuit against Hudson's estate.
   ``I began to sweat. I blacked out. I thought, `Oh my God. I'm a
dead man.'' Harold Rhoden, Christian's attorney, asked him why he
thought he would die.
   ``Because I had very intimate sexual contact with Rock Hudson
(and) he had full-blown AIDS,'' Christian replied.
   Christian, 35, an aspiring musician, is suing the actor's estate
and former secretary, Mark Miller, alleging they didn't tell him
Hudson had acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
   Christian, who said he does not have the sexually transmitted
disease that killed Hudson in 1985, denied defense assertions that
he was publicity-seeking opportunist who filed the lawsuit after he
learned Hudson did not include him in his will.
   Christian, under questioning by Rhoden, said he had no idea
whether he was included in the will.
   The lawsuit also contends Christian should receive compensation
for emotional distress and fear that he had been infected with the
deadly disease.
   Christian said Hudson developed a sore on his neck in June 1984,
which Hudson told him was caused by the sun, and was losing weight.
   ``His skin became very dry. He had scales. He was itching a lot.
He had skin rashes. He began to sweat at night,'' Christian
testified.
   Although he questioned Hudson about the symptoms, Hudson told him
he either was dieting, had the flu or gallstone problems, and Miller
told him the actor was anorexic, Christian said.
   Christian said he believed Hudson and continued to have
unprotected sexual intercourse with him until February 1985, when
Hudson lost interest in sex. Christian said he has been celibate
since then.
   It wasn't until he heard a July 1985 television news broadcast
that Hudson had AIDS that Christian learned his lover had the fatal
disease, he said.
   Christian said Miller called him from Paris, where Hudson had
collapsed, to see how he was taking the news.
   According to Christian, Miller said Hudson told him to ``do
anything you can for the kid, I may have killed him.''
</TEXT>
