<FIRST>r a PM-ResumeTrouble     01-12 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Resume Trouble,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kentucky Town to Drop Theft Charge in Alleged Resume Scam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE ROBRAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PIKEVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City Commission has voted to seek
dismissal of a theft charge against its former city manager because
he faces a stiffer charge in Alaska for using a bogus resume to get
a municipal job, officials said.
   Carl R.T. Keyser Jr., who is accused of using false resumes to
apply for city government jobs in four states, was arrested in
Alaska on Dec. 20 on a theft-by-deception charge filed in Kentucky.
   Keyser, 34, was fired the next day as city administrator in Kake,
Alaska, a job he had held since October. The Huntington, W.Va.,
native was charged last week with first-degree theft for allegedly
using a false resume to obtain $28,000 in salary, moving, travel and
other work-related expenses from the Alaska town.
   ``He's going to have some problems up there,'' Pikeville
Commissioner Greg Justice said Wednesday. ``They've already got
him.''
   Justice said the more serious charge in Alaska and the estimated
$30,000 cost of extradition persuaded the commission to unanimously
seek to drop the charge.
   A formal dismissal of the Kentucky charge was expected in a few
days, authorities said.
   Keyser resigned the Pikeville job in August after only six days
when reporters uncovered several apparently false entries on his
resume. He was indicted in October for allegedly failing to return
$697 in travel reimbursements.
   Keyser, who is jailed in Petersburg, Alaska, in lieu of $10,000
bond, has called the Alaska theft charge ``preposterous'' and said
he would have returned the money in Kentucky had he been asked.
   The Kake City Council hired Keyser based on glowing
recommendations from references on his impressive, four-page resume.
   The resume listed master's and bachelor's degrees in public
administration from La Salle University in Philadelphia, officials
said. He also listed experience as a consultant to the International
City Managers Association and the International Association of
Chiefs of Police, officials said.
   Officials say there is no record that Keyser attended the
university or worked for the associations. In October, the city
managers' group issued a warning about Keyser in its newsletter,
leading officials in Kake to investigate him.
   Kake officials also said they were unaware that Keyser pleaded
guilty in January 1988 to a misdemeanor perjury charge in Florida
stemming from alleged false information he provided while applying
for chief of police in Oak Hill, authorities said.
   The mayor of Port Royal, S.C., has said he reported Keyser to the
International City Managers Association after Keyser made an
allegedly false application there in September.
</TEXT>
