<FIRST>r a PM-CentralAmericans-Exodus     01-12 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Central Americans-Exodus,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Extends Window For Asylum-Seekers To Leave Southern Texas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge granted asylum-seeking Central
Americans another three weeks to leave south Texas, bringing sighs
of relief for some of the hundreds trapped in desperate conditions
by an immigration policy.
   ``Now we can go and be a little more tranquil about when we
leave,'' said Jose Narvaez Romero, 34, of Nicaragua. Narvaez said he
hoped to leave for a cousin's home in Hollywood, Calif., on Friday.
   U.S. District Judge Filemon Vela on Wednesday postponed until
Jan. 31 a hearing in a lawsuit filed last week against the
Immigration and Naturalization Service.
   The hearing had been scheduled for today, when a temporary
restraining order Vela issued Monday against an INS policy was to
expire.
   The order restored asylum-seekers' right to travel to U.S.
destinations while their cases are resolved. They retain that right
until the rescheduled hearing.
   ``It will help some,'' said City Manager Steve Fitzgibbons,
adding that the crisis is not over for Texas' southernmost city.
   ``We have unofficial reports that there are 20,000 to 50,000
people still in the pipeline, on their way here,'' he said.
   The Red Cross is operating four shelters for Central Americans at
churches, and Fitzgibbons said they should be replaced by a single,
large center such as the local National Guard armory.
   The INS policy put into effect Dec. 16 required that asylum
seekers stay close to the application center nearest their point of
entry while their requests are considered.
   Asylum seekers unable to leave the area because of the policy
resorted to living in primitive camps, abandoned buildings and
church shelters.
   Many Central Americans enter the United States in southern Texas
and file their requests at the busy INS center in Harlingen, 25
miles northwest of Brownsville. Monday's order sparked an exodus,
and hundreds of asylum seekers swamped the Harlingen center to
ensure their applications would be processed by Thursday.
   The INS office processed 967 asylum applications Tuesday, a
one-day record, and 739 Wednesday, INS spokeswoman Virginia Kice
said in Harlingen.
   Ms. Kice said the agency had asked the judge to postpone the
hearing so it could prepare its defense.
   ``We will be ready to go'' by Jan. 31, she said. ``And we are
going to fight it all the way.''
   She said about 95 percent of the applicants ``are here for jobs,
not political asylum.''
   Mark Schneider, an attorney with the Harlingen-based Projecto
Libertad legal office and a co-counsel to the class-action lawsuit
against the INS, said the asylum seekers are ready for trial but
welcome the extended travel time.
   ``This should remedy the huge backlog of thousands of people
stuck in the (Rio Grande) valley, so I think we'll see a lot less of
the hardship and the crisis that we've seen in the past three
weeks,'' Schneider said.
   Bus companies added extra northbound runs Tuesday and Wednesday,
including a Greyhound Lines bus added Tuesday evening in which ``the
whole busload was going to Miami,'' said George Gravley, a Greyhound
spokesman in Dallas.
   Those remaining in Harlingen and Brownsville continued to receive
donations of food and clothing from the community.
   ``Whether you agree with everything that's been happening, or if
they're illegals, they're still hungry,'' said Bob Bush, who with
members of Harlingen's First Assembly of God dished out beans and
tortillas to Central Americans gathered at the INS office.
   Brownsville city officials Wednesday took more than 100 Central
Americans out of squalid conditions at the condemned Amber Motel and
bused them to church shelters.
</TEXT>
