<FIRST>u i PM-LibyaPlant     01-12 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Libya Plant,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shipping Company Head Charged with Forgery In Libya Plant Shipments
^With PM-Germany-Libya, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANTWERP, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of an Antwerp shipping company
has been arrested in connection with the building of Libyan plant
the United States claims is a chemical arms factory, a justice
source said today.
   The source said Jozef Gedopt, director General of Cross Link, has
been charged with forging shipping documents. He is to be arraigned
Monday.
   ``We have found that there are grounds for prosecution,'' said
the source, who asked not to be named and declined to elaborate.
   Gedopt is charged with altering documents for the shipment by sea
of construction materials to Libya that were allegedly used to build
the plant at Rabta, 40 miles south of the Libyan capital of Tripoli.
   His arrest is part of a windening international probe into the
nature of the Rabta plant and the role played by West German and
other companies in its construction.
   Libya denies the plant can make chemical weapons, saying it was
built to produce pharmaceuticals.
   The United States has charged that five West German companies
helped Libya build the plant, notably Imhausen-Chemie of Lahr and
I.B.I. Engineering of Frankfurt.
   Gedopt was taken in for questioning Wednesday on his arrival at
the Brussels airport from Geneva and formally arrested Wednesday
night.
   According to news reports in Belgium and West Germany, he
allegedly alterted documents to hide the nature and destination of
cargo he shipped from Imhausen-Chemie to Libya.
   One shipment, in February, 1986, on the Wilhelm Schulte, a
Cypriot-registered freighter, listed Hong Kong as the final
destination but the freighter unloaded its cargo at Tripoli.
   Gedopt's arrest came just days after officials of the
investigation section of West Germany's customs service visited
Antwerp.
</TEXT>
