<HEAD>Freezing Rain in East; Snow out West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Freezing rain slickened roads in New York state today, heavy rain
triggered flash flood warnings in the South and the West began
digging out from a storm that dumped 13 inches of snow on Denver.
   Rain and thundershowers continued into the early morning over the
lower Mississippi Valley and the Tennessee Valley. Rain also was
falling from northern Florida to the Virginias.
   Flash flood watches were posted for Tennessee and Alabama.
   Snow was scattered over Minnesota, North Dakota, Colorado, Utah,
Idaho and Washington. Snow also fell in Upper Michigan while rain
and freezing rain covered the state's Lower Peninsula.
   A winter storm watch was in effect today over portions of New
Mexico.
   Gale-force winds were reported in California late Wednesday,
where gusts reached 69 mph at Ontario and 57 mph at El Toro.
   In Colorado, 13 inches of snow in Denver Wednesday prompted
officials to close Interstate 270 temporarily. Hundreds of
fender-benders were blamed on the rush-hour storm.
   Today's forecast called for snow over northern New England to
become freezing rain in Vermont. Rain was predicted for the rest of
New England, the Carolinas, the lower Great Lakes, the Ohio and
Tennessee valleys, Georgia, Alabama, Illinois, Missouri, the lower
Mississippi Valley, Texas and the northern Pacific Coast.
   Temperatures were to reach the 20s over New England, Michigan,
the upper Mississippi Valley, the northern Plains, the Rockies, the
Texas Panhandle and much of Wyoming.
   Temperatures were to reach the 30s and 40s in New Jersey, the
remainder of the Great Lakes, Nebraska and portions of Texas and the
Pacific Coast.
   The rest of the nation was to have highs in the 50s and 60s, with
portions of Florida and Texas to hit the 70s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 9
degrees below zero at Yellowstone, Wyo., to 85 degrees at McAllen,
Texas. Other reports:
