<FIRST>r a PM-Scout-Molest     01-12 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scout-Molest,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boy Scouts Call Reduced Award in Molestation a Victory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRFAX, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury ordered the local scouting council to
pay $45,000 to a youth because he was sexually molested by his
former scoutmaster but rejected the boy's $10 million claim against
the national Boy Scouts of America.
   The Boy Scouts called the decision a vindication of their
treatment of the complaint and of the scouts' supervision of local
councils that hire scoutmasters.
   The Fairfax County Circuit Court jury had deliberated for five
days after a six-week trial before deciding Wednesday that former
scoutmaster Carlton L. Bittenbender, a convicted pedophile, had
molested the youth.
   Jurors agreed with scout attorneys, however, that the Washington,
D.C., area council was liable for selecting Bittenbender.
   The youth, identified in court papers as ``Infant C,'' is now 17
and claimed he was molested by Bittenbender over a 10-month period
in 1984.
   The youth's lawyers claimed the scouts were negligent in choosing
Bittenbender to lead Troop 1970 because he had pleaded guilty to a
molestation charge while a scoutmaster in Rhode Island three years
before.
   The introduced confidential scout files hoping to prove that the
organization wouldn't act against pedophiles within its ranks
because of the fear of bad publicity.
   ``We're very pleased with the outcome,'' said Frank Hebb,
director of public relations for the national Boy Scouts of America.
   ``The evidence at the trial clearly demonstrated that scouting is
a local activity and that parents, neighbors and fellow members are
the people best suited to select scouting membership,'' Hebb said in
a statement.
   The youth's lawyer, Douglas B. Wessel, called the damages award
``grossly inadequate'' and said he will ask presiding Judge Richard
J. Jamborsky to overrule the jury's decision at a hearing Jan. 27.
   The damages does not cover the $58,907 in medical expenses the
youth has incurred, according to testimony presented at the trial.
   ``How this boy could have suffered $45,000 worth of damages, I
simply don't understand. ... This boy deserves better than this,''
he said.
   The teen and his family initially sought $30 million from the
scouts and Bittenbender. But the amount was reduced during the trial
to $10 million and the judge dismissed Bittenbender from the suit,
ruling the man's actions were intentional and so not negligent.
</TEXT>
