<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Lebanon 2ndLd-Writethru   01-12 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Lebanon, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0487,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Planes Raid Abu Nidal Base For Second Time In 13 Hours</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with eight grafs with casualties reported, quotes. Picks
up 6th pvs, `Fatah guerrillas ...' EDITS thereafter to conform.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli warplanes today rocketed bases of
Palestinian terrorist Abu Nidal outside this southern port for the
second time in 13 hours and police reported an undetermined number
of casualties.
   Two Israeli jets roared in at 10:05 a.m. to attack camps
belonging to Abu Nidal's Fatah-Revolutionary Council in Majdalyoun
Valley, four miles east of Sidon.
   Israeli military authorities said the bases served as a planning
and staging areas for terrorist attacks.
   The Fatah-Revolutionary Council, an extremist PLO splinter group,
has been blamed for terrorist attacks against Israel and Western
European countries, most notably the Rome and Vienna airport
massacres of December 1985.
   A police spokesman said the two Israeli jets in today's raid
fired four rockets ``in a few seconds and flew away west toward the
Mediterranean.'' The spokesman, who cannot be identified under
standing rules, said smoke billowed from the valley.
   Fatah guerrillas at first turned away ambulances dispatched from
Sidon, claiming there were no casualties.
   But the police spokesman said the ambulances later were allowed
into Majdalyoun Valley and returned with sirens wailing. He said
they took an undisclosed number of casualties to a Fatah clinic in
the Druse-controlled Chouf mountains northeast of Sidon.
   ``These people (Fatah) are clever in hiding their losses. It is
very difficult to estimate their casualties,'' the spokesman said.
   Fatah guerrillas opened up at the raiding jets from twin-barreled
anti-aircraft guns, but no hits were observed, he said.
   In Israel, the army said in a statement that the bombing followed
an earlier raid at 9 p.m. Wednesday. It did not say if the target
was destroyed, but said the Israeli warplanes had returned safely
from both raids.
   The attacks were the first two Israeli air raids on guerrilla
targets in Lebanon this year. According to a police count, 128
people were killed and 356 wounded in 25 Israeli air raids on
Lebanon in 1988.
   Abu Nidal, whose real name is Sabri al-Banna, broke away from PLO
chief Yasser Arafat's mainstream Fatah guerrilla group in 1974 and
formed his faction two years later. He is the most wanted
Palestinian terrorist in the United States and western Europe.
   Fatah opposes Arafat's explicit recognition of Israel and the
Palestine Liberation Organization dialogue with the United States.
</TEXT>
