<DOCNO> AP890112-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 0815EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Egypt     01-12 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Egypt,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mubarak Calls On Shamir to Accept International Peace Conference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hosni Mubarak today urged Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir of Israel to agree to an international
Middle East peace conference and said he won't visit Israel until
that happens.
   ``All countries of the world except Israel'' have accepted such
an international conference as the proper framework for Arab-Israeli
peace talks, Mubarak said. A conference, under U.N. auspices, would
bring together concerned parties and the five permanent members of
the U.N. Security Council.
   Egypt and the Palestine Liberation Organization say the
conference should lead to direct Arab-Israeli talks.
   Mubarak discussed the conference and other matters at a news
conference following a private meeting with Austrian Chancellor
Franz Vranitzky.
   Mubarak told reporters he plans to discuss peace and other
regional problems when he visits Washington after President-elect
George Bush takes office on Jan. 20. Mubarek didn't say when he will
go, but political adviser Osama el-Baz says the visit is expected in
the first half of this year.
   ``I have known Bush as vice president. We used to exchange views
on Middle East problems,'' Mubarak said. ``We understand each other
well.''
   Mubarak noted that Shamir has repeatedly rejected a peace
conference, believing that Israel would be forced to make
territorial concessions by countries who are biased against Israel.
   ``I believe world opinion fully agrees to an international
conference and I appeal to Mr. Shamir to respond to the voice of
peace that is backed by world opinion,'' Mubarak said.
   Asked about prospects of his visiting Israel, Mubarak replied:
   ``I have said it repeatedly before, and I sent a message
accordingly to Mr. Shamir: if my visit to Israel will lead to good
progress in (solving) the Middle East problem, then I am ready to go.
   ``I cannot visit Israel particularly after Mr. Shamir announced
he will not make territorial concessions and does not accept an
international peace conference. He is not giving something in return
or (paying) a price for my visit, and we will not go there to have
tea and coffee or to have a good time.'' A visit ``must achieve
something tangible'' in furthering efforts for an Arab-Israeli
settlement, Mubarak said.
   Shamir has refused to relinquish any Arab territory his forces
presently occupy: the West Bank, the Gaza Strip and the Golan
Heights, all seized in the 1967 Middle East war.
   Egypt and Israel signed a peace treaty in 1979 and established
diplomatic relations, but Mubarak has not visited Israel since
taking office in 1981.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
