<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-AIDS 1stLd-Writethru a0430 01-12 0705</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-AIDS, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0430,0722</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets To Require Foreigners To Have AIDS Tests</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with one graf to CORRECT spelling of ``minuscule,'' PICKS
UP 2nd graf `Foreigners who...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union says it will try to maintain its
minuscule AIDS rate by screening foreigners for the deadly virus,
even forcing mandatory tests of some visitors who cannot provide
proper medical proof.
   Foreigners who want to stay in the country for three months or
more will be subject to testing for the disease beginning next
month, Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said.
   ``Here, there cannot be any discrimination,'' Gerasimov said.
``We conduct tests of our own people and besides, statistics show
the Soviet Union is sharply lagging behind other countries, say the
United States, in the number of ill people (with AIDS). And we just
don't want to catch up.''
   The Soviets once regarded AIDS as a disease spawned by Western
sexual depravity and drug use. One Soviet newspaper's account had
even claimed the virus was the result of a U.S. biological warfare
experiment gone haywire.
   Gerasimov said the regulations were introduced to supplement a
1987 decree of the Soviet Council of Ministers.
   That decree made it a crime to knowingly spread AIDS, punishable
by up to eight years' imprisonment, and said anyone in the Soviet
Union could be forced to take a test to determine whether they were
carriers.
   According to Gerasimov, the new rules go into effect Feb. 1.
Summarizing them at a news briefing Wednesday, he said: ``Foreigners
coming into the Soviet Union for over three months, if they don't
have certificates which would be mutually accepted by agreement,
should be screened.''
   As outlined by Gerasimov, the new regulations on testing for AIDS
antibodies appear to exempt short-term tourists but to apply to all
foreigners _ diplomats, students, business people and journalists _
who live in the Soviet Union.
   As of late 1988, Gerasimov said, AIDS testsof 17 million people
in the Soviet Union had turned up 112 Soviets who carry the virus,
as opposed to 334 foreigners residing in the country.
   Eight people have the disease, five foreigners and three Soviets,
he said.
   ``We do not want this kind of import,'' Gerasimov said. ``I don't
want to say foreigners are a risk group. But we don't take any
chances.''
   Gerasimov said a traveler who tests AIDS-positive may be asked to
leave the country.
   ``People who try to avoid medical examination or treatment may be
expelled from the Soviet Union, following a prosecutor's sanction,''
he said.
   Soviet doctors customarily use hypodermic needles that are then
boiled to sterilize them for re-use, but Gerasimov told one
inquiring foreign reporter: ``Don't worry, we'll do our best so that
you will have single-use needles.''
   Stephen Walker, U.S. vice consul in Moscow, said Gerasimov's
announcement was the first indication he'd had from Soviet officials
that U.S. residents in Moscow would have to prove they were
AIDS-free.
   The U.S. community in Moscow numbers about 800, Walker said.
   Rick Kenney, public affairs specialist for the U.S. Immigration
and Naturalization Service, said that since the autumn of 1987 AIDS
has been on the list of contagious diseases which require a
rejection of an application for a U.S. visa.
   Pravda reported Nov. 11 that the Soviet Union had concluded
agreements with Britain, Denmark and its East bloc allies that
require their nationals seeking to enter the Soviet Union to prove
they are not AIDS carriers. It did not say whether the regulation
was already in effect.
   Gerasimov said the ``overwhelming majority'' of foreigners
diagnosed as AIDS carriers had left the Soviet Union. The state-run
press has previously reported the departure of African students
found to be infected with the virus.
   Last year, the official Tass news agency reported the first
Soviet AIDS deaths: a 4-month-old baby from the Odessa region on the
Black Sea, apparently infected by its mother, and a 29-year-old
Leningrad prostitute.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that
damages the body's immune system, leaving victims extremely
susceptible to infections and cancer. It is spread most often
through sexual contact, shared hypodermic needles, transfusion of
infected blood and from pregnant women to their offspring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890112-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 0942EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CriticBanned     01-12 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Critic Banned,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Small-Town Movie Critic Banned From Area's Only Theater</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLYTHE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The only film critic in town, a free-lancer
who refuses to write about R-rated pictures, has been barred from
this desert hamlet's lone theater because of her negative reviews.
   Cathy Monnett, who writes for the twice-weekly Palo Verde Valley
Times, was handed her admission fee back during a recent screening
of ``Gorillas in the Mist'' and asked to leave the Blythe Cinema.
   ``People were staying away from the theater because of her
reviews,'' Don Davis, the owner's brother and an attorney for the
theater, said in today's Los Angeles Times. ``The feeling inside the
theater, whether right or wrong, was that her criticism was not
evenly balanced.''
   Ms. Monnett argued that her reviews of family-oriented films are
largely positive, and she vowed not to be silenced.
   The 29-year-old wife of an elementary school teacher, who gets $8
for each review, said she will cross into Arizona and make the
90-mile desert drive to Yuma, site of the next-closest theater, to
see the same films showing at the Blythe.
   ``I'm incensed,'' Ms. Monnett said. ``By driving to Yuma I'm
telling them they can't stop me from writing reviews.''
   The drama in this town of 8,400 residents situated about 220
miles east of Los Angeles has prompted angry editorials by the
4,500-circulation newspaper and picketing outside the 600-seat
theater at the paper's urging.
   The critic said the ban was unfounded. ``Of the 28 reviews I have
written, 17 have been positive,'' she said.
   ``That's a pretty good percentage,'' mused David Anson, a movie
reviewer for Newsweek magazine. ``I don't think any of us would
survive in Blythe.''
   Blythe co-owner Paul Davis, whose theater doesn't advertise in
the newspaper, has called Monnett a dilettante with no credentials
to review films.
   ``Were her distorted, negative and unfair criticism harmless,''
he said in a letter to the editor, ``we could perhaps ignore her,
and chuck it off to a small-town mind that dabbles in writing
newspaper articles.''
</TEXT>
