<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--PracticeBomb     01-12 0166</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Practice Bomb,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Jet Drops Practice Bomb on Man's Backyard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDDLEBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy fighter jet on a training mission
accidentally dropped a three-foot practice bomb, digging a foot-deep
crater in a family's back yard but causing no injuries, officials
said.
   The eight-pound bomb had a detonator charge, similar to a shotgun
shell, that emits smoke when it hits the ground, said Bert Byers,
spokesman for Cecil Field Naval Air Station.
   A Navy team removed the bomb from William Larsen's back yard, 113
feet from his home. Larsen was alone at the time but said if it had
been 20 minutes later, his children and their friends would have
been playing on a backyard trampoline.
   The FA-18 Hornet was on a mission to Pinecastle Electronic
Warfare Range in the Ocala National Forest when the bomb tumbled
free at 1:50 p.m. Wednesday, the Navy said.
   ``We don't know how it happened, but there will be an
investigation to determine the cause,'' Byers said.
</TEXT>
