<FIRST>r i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0505 01-12 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0505,0607</SECOND>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Jerusalem</HEAD>
<HEAD>Settlers Shout Down Shamir, Boy Killed In Clash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Shamir shouted down by settlers.
No pickup. ^By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRAKHA, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angry settlers shouted down
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir today and demanded that the government
do more to quell the Palestinian uprising.
   In the West Bank town of Tulkarem, troops shot and killed an
11-year-old Palestinian during clashes following the funeral of a
Palestinian teen-ager who died of wounds suffered earlier, Arab
doctors said.
   The army confirmed both deaths.
   Shamir, who spoke at a mourning ceremony in Brakha for a slain
Jewish settler, was confronted by a crowd of 200 settlers.
   They screamed demands that he put an end to attacks on Jews by
Palestinians and chanted: ``You are doing nothing.''
   Shamir told the settlers that the greatest danger to Israel was
dissension among Jews. ``One thing only can hurt our ability to
stand firm: quarrels among brothers, or worse civil war among
them,'' he said.
   Elsewhere in the West Bank, troops broke up a sit-in by hundreds
of Jewish settlers near the settlement of Yakir who also demanded
the army crack down harder on Palestinians involved in the
13-month-old uprising.
   The army set up roadblocks throughout the area to prevent more
settlers from reaching the site where the sit-in began Wednesday but
dozens broke through one roadblock and were chased by troops, Israel
army radio said.
   Also today, 18-year-old Nasser Mohammed Salah Irut of the West
Bank city of Nablus was shot in the head and critically wounded by
Palestinians who accused him of collaborating with Israel, Arab
doctors said.
   In Hebron, troops wounded three Palestinians in a clash with
stone-throwers, the army said. Palestinian reports said the
confrontation began after settlers opened fire on a Palestinian
youth who stoned their car.
   In east Jerusalem, the army imposed a curfew on the Silwan
neighborhood and arrested Arab residents according to prepared
lists, police said.
   Jerusalem police commander Yosef Yehudai said on Israel radio
that the action was the start of a new policy of imposing curfews on
Jerusalem neighborhoods to quell disturbances.
   Curfews are frequently imposed in the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip, but rarely used in Jerusalem, which Israel considers its
capital.
   In Tulkarem, Abdul Ahmed Abdul Salam, 11, died of a bullet wound
to the chest during a clash in which hundreds of Palestinians hurled
rocks and burned tires to protest the death of another Tulkarem
youth hours earlier, Arab doctors said.
   Three other Tulkarem residents were in critical condition after
being shot in the clash, hospital officials said. Troops imposed a
curfew on the city and a nearby refugee camp.
   The clashes were caused by news of the death of 17-year-old
Marwan El Maddeni of Tulkarem, who died at east Jerusalem's Mukassed
Hospital after being shot in the head in a Jan. 1 clash.
   Residents called a general strike following Maddeni's death and
raised outlawed Palestinian flags and black flags of mourning, the
Arab reports said. Hundreds of students poured into the streets upon
hearing news of the death.
   The deaths raised to 351 the number of Palestinians killed in the
Palestinian revolt against Israel's 21-year occupation. Fifteen
Israelis also have died.
   Since the uprising began, settlers have complained of
insufficient protection by the army. They have sought permission to
fire on stone-throwers and demanded deportations of Palestinian
activists on a large scale.
   About 65,000 Jewish settlers live in the West Bank, along with
about 850,000 Palestinians.
</TEXT>
