<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Shamir     01-12 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Shamir,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir Accepts U.N. Role in Arranging Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir told visiting U.S.
congressional aides today he would accept an active U.N. role in
arranging Arab-Israeli peace talks but not in actual negotiations,
his spokesman said.
   Avi Pazner, Shamir's spokesman, quoted Shamir as telling the
20-member delegation that the United Nations could send out
invitations and bring the parties together.
   Shamir has been under increased pressure to find new ways to
reinvigorate the peace process since Yasser Arafat, chief of
Palestine Liberation Organization, proposed a U.N.-sponsored peace
conference and opened direct talks with U.S. officials last month.
Israel rejects such a conference, saying the United Nations is
biased.
   Shamir's spokesman said the U.N. role could resemble the one
played by U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar in bringing
Iran and Iraq to the negotiating table.
   Perez de Cuellar met with leaders of both warring nations,
shuttling between their capitals to arrange talks leading to a
cease-fire in August.
   ``In order to get to direct talks, Israel is ready for the
auspices of the two superpowers and is ready to have the United
Nations play a certain role in inviting the parties to negotiate,''
said Pazner.
   The spokesman stressed, however, that Israel would not agree to
either the superpowers or the United Nations ``getting involved in
the substance'' of negotiations.
   Officials say Shamir will unveil a peace plan when he visits
Washington, probably in late February or March.
   The liberal daily Haaretz reported today that Shamir would give
French President Francois Mitterrand a preview when he travels to
France in February.
</TEXT>
