<FIRST>r p PM-Dukakis-Taxes     01-12 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dukakis-Taxes,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor Gets Chilly Response to Request for Air Time</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael Dukakis, who just months ago could
command a national television audience, got a chilly response to his
request for five minutes' air time on Massachusetts TV stations to
pitch a tax increase.
   Dukakis on Wednesday asked stations for time at the start of
their newscasts tonight to make his case directly to voters.
   WCVB said no. News executive Philip Balboni called the request a
``completely inappropriate'' attempt to manipulate the news.
   ``Our responsibility is to cover that story but to cover it from
all sides and then report it to our viewers, and that is what we
will do,'' he said.
   Executives at WNEV agreed to the governor's request. Other
stations said they were discussing it.
   WBZ demanded a copy of Dukakis' speech before noon today before
deciding whether to give him air time, a request Dukakis' press
secretary said would not be met, news director Stan Hopkins said. As
a result, the station will not provide air time.
   Boston public TV station WGBH was not asked for the time.
Managing editor John VanScoyoc said the governor would appear on its
news show tonight in an interview.
   ``It's a way for the governor to reach the most people
directly,'' Steve Crawford, a Dukakis press secretary, said in
explaining the request.
   Crawford insisted Dukakis was not seeking the TV time because
news accounts are incomplete or biased. He said the hope was to
deliver to viewers the type of statement newspapers often provide
when they publish texts of major addresses.
   According to officials familiar with the governor's thinking,
Dukakis plans to seek up to $200 million extra income in the current
fiscal year, which ends on June 30, and as much as $600 million next
year.
   Dukakis has acknowledged a shortfall of at least $600 million in
the state's current $11.6 billion budget, a gap he attributes to a
revenue slowdown.
