<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Libya 3rdLd-Writethru a0524 01-12 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Libya, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0524,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>West Germany Says It's Checking Evidence on Libyan Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: New throuout to UPDATE with government statement that indications
point to involvement in Libya chemical plant. TRIMS to tighten. No pickup.
^By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today said West German
companies or individuals may have helped build a suspected chemical
arms plant in Libya and that it is checking for any violations of
export laws.
   The issue has aggravated normally warm relations between the
United States and West German.
   ``The federal government has indications of the possible
participation of German companies or persons at this plant in
Libya,'' chief government spokesman Friedhelm Ost said in a
statement.
   ``West German authorities are intensively pursuing these leads,''
Ost said without providing details.
   He said the government is checking documents held by the Customs
Service to decide if it should prosecute violations of export law
that may have occurred.
   Earlier today, government officials said indications that West
German companies helped build and outfit the plant had embarrassed
the government and damaged the nation's image.
   ``There is no question these allegations have caused serious
damage to West Germany's international prestige,'' said a
high-ranking government official who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   ``The government is in an extremely embarrassing and difficult
position,'' said the official, referring to developments that forced
Chancellor Helmut Kohl to reverse statements that there was no
evidence of involvement by West German companies in the affair.
   Earlier today, authorities conceded unofficially they had found
``indications'' that at least two West German companies played major
roles in supplying equipment for the plant, and a shipper also
implicated in the affair was arrested in Belgium on Wednesday night.
   Libya's ambassador to the United Nations, Ali Treiki, said today
on ``CBS This Morning'' that West Germans ``did help us, not only in
this plant, in other plants also.
   ``We have a vast cooperation with West Germany and certainly some
companies participated in this pharmaceutical plant,'' Treiki said.
   The Libyan leader, Col. Moammar Gadhafi, says the factory, 40
miles south of Tripoli, is for the production of pharmaceuticals,
not chemical weapons.
   Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher conceded in an interview
with the ARD television network that ``there are a number of
indications that evidently point in this direction'' of West German
involvement in the plant.
   Federal officials confirmed a criminal investigation has begun
against a now-defunct Frankfurt company _ I.B.I. Engineering _ and
that investigators had seized company documents.
   Officials also confirmed that the documents linked another
company, Imhausen-Chemie of Lahr, to the construction project,
backing claims made by the United States last month.
   A source with the Belgian Justice Ministry reported today that
Jozef Gedopt, director-general of Cross Link of Antwerp, was taken
into custody and charged with forging shipping documents for goods
sent to Libya.
   Under West German law, the Economics Ministry must approve export
licenses for arms, hazardous substances or components that can be
used to produce them. There is also a ban on export of high
technology to ``sensitive areas.''
   Bonn last week announced that an initial investigation of
Imhausen-Chemie turned up no evidence of illegal shipments. But U.S.
officials did not let up in pressing their case on the involvement
of West German firms, and the controversy has dominated news reports
and political discussions in Bonn.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
