<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 1135EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ArsenalPlague     01-12 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arsenal Plague,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plague Wipes Out Arsenal Prairie Dogs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An outbreak of plague has wiped out one-fifth of
the prairie dogs at the Rocky Mountain Arsenal, but the onset of
winter is believed to have killed the fleas carrying the disease,
Army officials say.
   ``We've lost 1,000 of our 5,500 acres of prairie dogs,'' Capt.
Andrew Kingery, spokesman for the Army's chemical contamination
cleanup operations, said Wednesday.
   No humans are believed to have contracted the disease, but it may
have spread to coyotes, officials said. Only fleas, not mammals, can
transmit the disease, which usually takes the form of bubonic plague
in humans.
   Kingery said U.S. Fish and Wildlife biologists noticed a large
decline in the prairie dog population last month.
   The Army restricted access to the area and called in an Army
entomologist, but the weather turned cold and the scientist was
unable to obtain flea samples, Kingery said.
   ``So we contracted for a coyote specialist to trap four
animals,'' Kingery said. ``We forwarded blood samples from the
coyotes to the Center for Disease Control in Fort Collins and on
Jan. 3 they confirmed the presence of plague.''
   The coyotes carried antibodies to the plague, but it was not
known whether they had contracted the disease, he said.
   Kingery said there is no threat to anyone visiting the arsenal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
