<FIRST>r a PM-FugitiveIndian     01-12 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fugitive Indian,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Stays Extradition Of Fugitive Indian</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM KATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WAMPSVILLE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge today blocked Gov. Mario Cuomo's
order to return an American Indian to North Carolina to face
kidnapping charges brought after an armed takeover of a newspaper
office.
   Madison County Judge William O'Brien III set a Feb. 28 hearing
date for arguments on whether Timothy Jacobs should be returned to
North Carolina.
   Jacobs' lawyers asked for the stay after Cuomo signed a request
from North Carolina Gov. Jim Martin on Tuesday to return Jacobs.
   O'Brien allowed Jacobs to remain free on $25,000 bail and told
him he must remain in the custody of the Onondaga Indian Nation and
not leave New York.
   District Attorney Neal Rose opposed allowing Jacobs to remain
free, saying that Jacobs might flee as his extradition nears and
that his freedom might send a message that New York is a ``safe
haven for people who commit violent acts.''
   ``At least now we have time to make plans,'' Jacobs said. ``I
hope we are allowed to present the case on why I should not be
returned to North Carolina.''
   Jacobs has said that he would not receive a fair trial in Robeson
County, N.C., and that he fears for his life if he is returned there.
   Jacobs, 20, and Eddie Hatcher, 31, were charged in the 1988
takeover in Lumberton, N.C. They said they took over the newspaper
to bring corruption by county officials to light.
   A federal jury Oct. 14 acquitted them of federal hostage-taking
charges, but they still face the state kidnapping charges.
   Jacobs, after his indictment on state charges, fled to the
Onondaga Indian Nation reservation south of Syracuse but was
captured Dec. 13 after a car chase.
   He was released on bail under an agreement with Onondaga leaders
that he would be turned over to authorities should Cuomo order his
return.
   Hatcher also fled to the Onondaga territory but has since moved
to a Shoshone-Bannock reservation in Idaho.
</TEXT>
