<SECOND>PM-Secret Investments,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>Assistant City Clerk Fired After Secretly Investing, Losing City
Funds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The assistant city clerk secretly
invested more than $2 million in city money and lost almost half of
it, officials said.
   Police Chief Paul Brown said Wednesday that Frank Vestal, who was
fired Monday, made unauthorized investments for the beach city in
high-risk government bonds in 1987 and 1988, resulting in an
estimated loss of $901,000.
   ``The investment itself is not the type ... the city could have
ever considered being involved in,'' Brown said. ``Normally, they
purchase guaranteed government securities for an absolute known
return.''
   Brown said the matter would be referred to the State Attorney's
Office for possible criminal charges.
   City Manager Lester Griffis said that the community of about
20,000 is checking on how to recoup the the money. But he said the
city has a $50 million annual budget and should be able to cover its
losses without major difficulty.
   Vestal, 42, had been employed by the city since 1982 and was
promoted to assistant city clerk in 1986. He worked as the city's
senior accountant.
   Calls to his home today went unanswered.
