<FIRST>r a AM-Ryan'sHope     01-12 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ryan's Hope,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ryan's Hope Ends 13{-Year Run</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After Maeve Ryan sings one last rendition of
``Danny Boy,'' the long-running soap opera ``Ryan's Hope'' fades to
black on Friday, leaving fans to wonder for eternity, who is Grace's
father?
   ABC announced in October that it was canceling the daytime drama
after 13{ years and 3,515 episodes.
   After wrapping up most of the storylines, the final scene has
Maeve (Helen Gallagher), joined by family and friends in Ryan's Bar,
singing ``Danny Boy'' as she has traditionally on every St.
Patrick's Day. This year, there will be no St. Patrick's Day for the
Ryans.
   ``Yes, it is a tear-jerker,'' said Karen Reynolds, the publicist
for the show who attended the taping of the final episode.
   The final episode features the wedding of reporter Jack Fenelli
(Michael Levin) and newspaper publisher Leigh Kirkland (Felicity
Lafortune). Of the series' other continuing storylines, the only
major one to be left hanging is the paternity of 4-year-old Grace
Coleridge.
   In the final scene, Pat Ryan (Malcolm Groome), who suspects he
might be the child's father, asks Faith Coleridge (Karen
Morris-Gowdy) who Grace's father is. Faith says she'll tell him
after Maeve sings. Fans, like Pat Ryan, will never hear the answer.
   ABC said it canceled the soap because too many affiliates chose
to pre-empt the low-rated drama for noon newscasts.
   ```Ryan's Hope' has not been rejected by the audience, it has
simply been unavailable to viewers,'' Jo Ann Emmerich, vice
president of daytime programs for ABC Entertainment, said at the
time. ``Without sufficient stations to carry it, it has become a
victim of audience erosion.''
   At its lowest ebb, the show was carried by only 75 percent of
ABC's 200-plus affiliates. ABC said the show was being dropped
instead of moved because the network did not have an appropriate
timeslot for a half-hour drama.
   The series has won 17 Daytime Emmys _ including three for Helen
Gallagher as Maeve _ and 11 Writers Guild awards. It launched the
careers of many well-known actors, including Corbin Bernsen, who
stars on NBC's ``L.A. Law,'' and Kate Mulgrew, star of ABC's
``HeartBeat.''
</TEXT>
