<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Battlefield     01-12 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Battlefield,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Gives OK to Highway Through Historic Battlefield</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court has given authorities permission to build a
highway through a 17th-century battlefield, capping a 13-year
struggle.
   The Court of Appeal says the Transport Department can go ahead
with the four-lane highway across fields where Oliver Cromwell's
13,000-member parliamentary force routed King Charles I's 9,000
royalists in 1645 in the decisive battle of the English Civil War.
   In a unanimous ruling Wednesday, the three judges sympathized
with historians opposing the highway. But they said the victors in
the 17th century battle at Naseby in central England would have
preferred the court to abide by Transport Minister Peter Bottomley's
decision.
   ``The wisdom of investing this exercise of judgment to a
democratically elected minister rather than the court would have
appealed to those who won the day at Naseby,'' wrote Lord Justice
Thomas Bingham.
   Sir Charles Rowley, vice chairman of the Society for the
Protection of the Field of the Battle of Naseby, shot back:
``Cromwell might have been a bit of a destructive chap himself, but
he would never have approved of this.''
</TEXT>
