<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Potatoes     01-12 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Potatoes,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Potatoes in Four Never Make It to Soviet Tables</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union is suffering through a potato
shortage, and more than three out of every four spuds never make it
to the dinner table because of waste, rot and loss in transit, a
newpaper said Thursday.
   ``What's happening in our country with the potato?'' the
Communist youth daily Komsomolskaya Pravda asked. ``Why is it on the
list of goods in short supply?''
   The potato, known to Russians as their ``second bread,'' is an
important staple in many Soviets' diet. But it has been absent or in
short supply in many of the country's food stores for weeks.
   Vladimir Tikhonov, a member of the Soviet National Agricultural
Academy, told Komsomolskaya Pravda that Soviet state and collective
farms produce more than 31 million tons of potatoes annually _ twice
the American crop.
   Americans, though, can eat potatoes all year because crop loss,
from the field to the kitchen, is only 5 percent, Tikhonov said.
   In comparison, Soviets buying potatoes _ a crop that's usually
packaged with a generous quantity of dried mud and already rotten
vegetables _ end up throwing out half the purchase, Tikhonov said.
   ``It happens that if all losses are counted en route to the
consumer, only 7 million tons of potatoes make it `to the cooking
pot,''' Tikhonov told the paper. ``Less than a quarter of the entire
harvest!''
   He called the potato shortage an indication of the woes of Soviet
agriculture as a whole, which because of more than a half-century of
state planning has been geared to meeting government production
targets rather than developing efficient techniques of management
and food transportation and storage.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has called for the widespread
leasing of state-owned farm land to individual peasants to increase
food supply by allowing them to earn more for producing more. The
Communist Party has scheduled a meeting on agriculture in February.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
