<FIRST>u a PM-TrappedDiver     01-12 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trapped Diver,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>2 Divers Trapped in Dam Die</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILLINOCKET, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers used harnesses to free two
divers trapped in icy water 55 feet down for up to 11 hours, but
both died, officials said today.
   The divers, who were repairing an 80-foot-high, 72-year-old
wilderness dam owned by Great Northern Paper Co., became trapped
Wednesday by water pressure at openings they had cut in the dam on
Chesuncook Lake, authorities said.
   The diver credited with hooking the two up to the harnesses
against the enormous pressure created by lake waters pressing
against the dam was hospitalized today in good condition, State
Police said.
   Albert O. Harjula, 29, of Thomaston, became trapped first, said
Paul Fournier, a spokesman for the state Department of Inland
Fisheries and Wildlife.
   Daniel Sullivan, 30, of Boothbay, went down to help and also
became stuck, Fournier said.
   During the 10-hour rescue, diver Brian Michaud of Millinocket
hooked the men to harnesses, and rescuers dragged them to the
surface with winches.
   Harjula was under water for more than 11 hours. He was pronounced
dead on arrival at the hospital early today, said Trooper Kathy
Roope.
   Sullivan died at the hospital nearly three hours after he was
pulled from the water. He was in the water about 4{ hours, Fournier
said.
   Both died of hypothermia, or severe loss of body heat, the
trooper said. Fournier estimated the water temperature was 35
degrees.
   Michaud spent the night in Millinocket Regional Hospital but was
in good condition today, authorities said.
   Harjula had a telephone link with the surface and was able to
alert workers at the top that he was in trouble, Fournier said.
</TEXT>
