<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 1245EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     01-12 0758</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Independence May Not End Troubles in Namibia's Embattled North</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ONDANGWA, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 22 years of warfare, curfews and
atrocities, the beleaguered Ovambo people of northern Namibia are on
the threshold of emerging as power brokers in the transition to
independence.
   There is an air of excitement in Ovamboland, where half of all
Namibians live. But there also are worries about the staggering
problems that will confront a new government after independence
elections Nov. 1.
   South Africa, which has ruled the territory for 74 years, has
agreed to withdraw from Africa's last colony under the terms of a
1978 United Nations resolution.
   The pullout of South African troops will deprive garrison towns
of their main source of income. The return of tens of thousands of
exiles and refugees will strain local resources, and the possible
takeover of power by the SWAPO guerrilla movement could trigger
vendettas against Ovambos who worked with or fought for South
African authorities.
   ``To be free and independent doesn't mean we are suddenly in
paradise,'' said Bishop Kleopas Dumeni, head of the Evangelical
Lutheran Church, by far the largest denomination in the region. ``We
can accomplish the task of nation-building only if we do it
together.''
   Dumeni's plea for reconciliation is heartfelt. His brother was
killed by a military patrol and one of his daughters was killed in a
bomb blast blamed on SWAPO.
   Ovamboland, in the center of northernmost Namibia, covers only 7
percent of territory's land, but accomodates roughly half its 1.3
million people, most of them living in huts or corrugated metal
shacks.
   It is the region where the guerrillas of SWAPO _ the South-West
African Peoples Organization _ has its strongest support and where
most of the low-intensity guerrilla war has been waged. SWAPO has a
legal political wing operating in Nambia, but the guerrilla movement
is outlawed.
   In the coming months, Ovamboland is expected to become a
political and propaganda battleground, with an array of factions
trying to ward off a SWAPO victory in United Nations-monitored
elections.
   Holding SWAPO to less than two-thirds of the vote would prevent
it from having total control over the elected assembly that will
draft Namibia's new constitution.
   SWAPO sympathizers claim South Africa will try to rig the voting
to favor parties it considers more moderate. Ovambos say security
forces are visiting villages with the message that SWAPO plans
communist-style collectivization and should be opposed.
   SWAPO leader Sam Nujoma has said he does not forsee blanket
nationalization of industries, but his exact political and economic
programs have not been spelled out.
   Among those caught in the political crossfire is Peter Kalangual,
chairman of the Ovambo Regional Administration. He has cooperated to
a degree with the territorial government while at the same time
trying, with mixed success, to maintain cordial relations with SWAPO.
   ``True reconciliation is not a superficial thing,'' he said.
``For people who've been embittered it's not all that easy.''
   In many cases, the conflict has splintered Ovambo families. While
one son may have fled north to Angola to join SWAPO, his brother may
have joined Koevoet, a police counterinsurgency unit widely accused
of brutality.
   ``The parents are caught in the middle,'' said Kalangula, 62.
``They don't know whether to turn left or right.''
   Israel Shikongo, who works at a human rights center near
Ondangwa, predicted that SWAPO would discourage widespread
retribution against Ovambos who served in the security forces but
would conduct some sort of reorientation program.
   A retired Lutheran minister sympathetic to SWAPO, German-born
Peter Paully said some vengeance-taking was inevitable.
   ``Certainly people who have been really devilish will be hunted
down,'' said Paully, who moved to Namibia in 1951 and has married an
Ovambo woman. ``Those in power in South Africa have done nothing to
defuse this situation.''
   The social and economic needs of post-independence Ovamboland
will be vast.
   Up to 100,000 refugees and exiles, many of them ill or crippled,
will be returning to a region already lacking adequate services and
job opportunities.
   Many adults will lose their jobs as maids or maintenance workers
when the South African army bases close. Changes will be needed in
an education system where one underqualified teacher instructs 50 or
more children in a South African-designed curriculum.
   ``Some students are anticipating a utopian world where, in an
independent state, everyting is candies and honey,'' said Denys
Nandi, Ovamboland's education director. ``I tell them the opposite
is true _ if independence comes everyone must be prepared to work 20
times harder.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890112-0100 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 1246EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Reagan 1stLd-Writethru a0415 01-12 1035</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Reagan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0415,990</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan Honored by Armed Forces</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 13 grafs new with Reagan remarks, picks up pvs 3rd graf,
``We meant;'' deletes pvs 8th graf, ``The president,'' and cuts from end
to tighten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan hailed America's servicemen
and women today as ``America's pride'' at an elaborate military
review designed by the Pentagon to bid farewell to their
commander-in-chief.
   Reagan, speaking at the end of the 45-minute ceremony at Andrews
Air Force Base outside Washington, also called for a moment of
silence to remember the 595 persons who had died in the service of
their country over the past eight years of his presidency.
   ``They are not with us today, because they are at God's right
hand. ... They voluntered. They chose to serve, they gave their
lives. They are our heroes,'' Reagan said.
   The president was treated to as much pomp and circumstance as the
Pentagon could muster for the rainy-day ceremony, which was moved
inside a 14-story-tall hangar at the Maryland base.
   Although a fly-by of military jets had to be cancelled because of
the foul weather, Reagan was treated to a review of troops, music by
the scarlet-uniformed Marine Band, and a movie hailing his military
buildup during his two terms in office. He also received service
medals during the festivities.
   Arrayed as a backdrop were the Air Force's new B-1B bomber, as
well as jet fighters and helicopters, many of them purchased during
Reagan's trillion-dollar military buildup.
   ``Mr. President, the pride people feel today _ certainly the
pride felt by the men and women in our armed forces _ is a direct
result of the leadership you have provided as commander-in-chief,''
said Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci. ``You have restored not only
our national strength _ but also our sense of purpose.''
   Reagan said he was thankful to have born ``the most sacred of
tasks'' as the nation's commander-in-chief and to oversee a
resurgence of spirit among the nation's military.
   ``Where, I have at times asked myself, where have you come from?
How you've managed to cohere into the crack, disciplined, patriotic
band of brothers I see before me this morning?'' Reagan asked. He
offered his own answer:
   ``You come from America and you are America's pride. On behalf of
all America, I thank you, and pray God that he may bless you now and
forever.''
   The president said he ordered first lady Nancy Reagan to cancel
plans to attend the ceremony because she was suffering from
laryngitis.
   The farewell came the day after Reagan offered his own Oval
Office goodbye, in which he said he was handing the nation over to
the ``good hands'' of George Bush.
   In a televised speech bidding adieu to the nation, Reagan boasted
Wednesday night of his accomplishments and ignored many of the
difficulties that arose during his eight years in office.
   ``We meant to change a nation, and instead, we changed a world,''
he said.
   Yet Reagan also admitted that his self-styled conservative
revolution left many things unchanged, and he asked his followers to
stick around and help his successor.
   ``If we're to finish the job, Reagan's Regiments will have to
become the Bush Brigades,'' Reagan said. ``Soon he'll be the chief,
and he'll need you every bit as much as I did.''
   The president said he was leaving office with the central message
of his political life strengthened _ that an unfettered economy, a
strong defense and a free citizenry forged a nation ``respected in
the world, and looked to for leadership.''
   ``Democracy, the profoundly good, is also the profoundly
productive,'' he said. ``Because we are a great nation, our
challenges seem complex. It will always be this way. But as long as
we remember our first principles and believe in ourselves, the
future will always be ours.''
   Reagan addressed the nation from his Oval Office desk, his left
hand in a splint and swathed in bandages from weekend surgery on a
finger.
   Speaking nine days before his retirement to California, Reagan
called his departure ``sweet sorrow.'' But he also said he looks
forward to a renewal of personal freedom, contending a modern
president must live ``somewhat apart. You spend a lot of time going
by too fast in a car someone else is driving.''
   Another regret, Reagan said, was his failure to tame the nation's
deficit. But that merited only a paragraph in the roughly 21-minute
speech. ``I've been talking a great deal about that lately, but
tonight isn't for arguments and I'm going to hold my tongue,'' he
said.
   The national debt almost tripled in Reagan's term and he ran up
the biggest budget deficits in history. His final budget proposal,
released earlier this week for the 1990 fiscal year starting Oct. 1,
projects a deficit of $92.5 billion.
   The president's remarks were void of any mention of such national
tragedies as the barracks bombing that killed more than 241
servicemen in Beirut, the Challenger disaster or the Americans held
hostage in the Middle East.
   There was no word of the trade deficits or the scandals that
tarnished his administration, such as the sale of arms to Iran and
use of the proceeds to fund the Contra rebels in Nicaragua
illegally. The Contras, subject of so many Reagan speeches, were not
mentioned at all.
   As triumphs Reagan listed the nation's economic recovery, its low
unemployment and inflation, and its bolstered military.
   The president who warned early in his tenure of the ``evil
empire'' in the Soviet Union took credit at the end of his
presidency for forging ``a satisfying new closeness'' with the
Soviets. He said the new relationship helped bring about the first
U.S.-Soviet treaty to eliminate an entire class of nuclear weapons,
as well as ``a new peacefulness around the globe.''
   ``What it all boils down to is this: I want the new closeness to
continue,'' Reagan said. But he advised those who follow to ``trust
but verify. ... Watch closely _ and don't be afraid to see what you
see.''
   ``We must keep up our guard _ but we must also continue to work
together to lessen and eliminate tension and mistrust,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890112-0101 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 1247EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Iran-Women     01-12 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Iran-Women,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Khomeini's Daughter Wants to Form Women's Organization</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The daughter of Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini has asked the government for permission to form a women's
association, an official report said Thursday.
   The Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in Nicosia, quoted
the English-language daily Tehran Times as saying Zahra Mostafavi
applied for permission with the Interior Ministry ``to form the
Women's Society of the Islamic Republic of Iran.''
   The agency quoted the newspaper as saying Mrs. Mostafavi has been
active in Iranian women's affairs. It added, ``She has always
emphasized that women should better realize their rights and
concentrate their efforts on regaining their denied ones.''
   Women are not regarded as equal with men in Iran and generally
are required to go out in public in traditional Islamic dress, the
head-to-toe black veil known as a chador.
   Last month, Interior Minister Hojatolesman Ali Akbar Mohtashami
said Iranians could submit applications to form political parties
and other groups. Mrs. Mostafavi, 49, is one of Khomeini's three
daughters. He also has a son who serves as an adviser.
