<HEAD>Kenyan President Dismisses Commerce Minister</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel arap Moi dismissed his
commerce minister Thursday and replaced him with a former assistant
minister for education, Voice of Kenya radio announced.
   The president gave no explanation of the move, the radio said.
But he complained Wednesday of nail shortages which he said were
artificially created.
   In the past, nailmakers charged that the Ministry of Commerce
failed to issue licenses to import steel needed to manufacture nails.
   Kimaiyo arap Sego, who was appointed to the Cabinet after general
elections in March, was replaced by John Cheruiyot.
   A branch of the country's sole legal political party, the Kenya
African National Union, said Jan. 3 the party should discipline
Sego. It gave no reason.
   Sego was the second minister to leave the Cabinet within five
weeks. Kenneth Matiba resigned Dec. 9 as minister for transport and
communications after a dispute over the outcome of party elections
in his central Kenya constituency.
