<HEAD>Officers Sue Over Job Transfers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two police officers who led the
investigation of the deaths of seven people unearthed in a
boardinghouse yard are suing their bosses for transferring them to
other jobs.
   Lt. Joe Enloe and Sgt. James L. Jorgensen allege their
reassignments were punitive and illegal; their superiors maintain
the transfers were routine.
   ``These transfers were precipitous, unwise and unfair,'' said
Blake Koller, president of the Sacramento Police Officers
Association. ``It was an effort to use the officers as scapegoats
for the errors of management.''
   The Police Department came under fire for allowing Dorothea
Montalvo Puente to walk away from the house Nov. 12, one day after
the first body was discovered in her yard. Police have also been
criticized for allowing a reporter to interview Puente on a
media-chartered flight back to Sacramento after her capture in Los
Angeles.
   Puente, 59, has been charged with murdering one of her tenants,
and prosecutors have said they expect to file more murder counts at
a court hearing next week.
   The officers' lawsuit seeks a court order directing the city and
the City Civil Service Board to provide the officers with an
administrative appeal hearing so they can challenge the transfers.
