<FIRST>u w PM-Iran-Contra     01-12 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Contra,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thornburgh, Walsh Press Iran-Contra Judge To Drop Charges Against
North</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh and
independent counsel Lawrence Walsh today pressed the federal judge
in the Iran-Contra case to drop conspiracy and theft charges against
fired National Security Council aide Oliver L. North.
   Walsh filed a memorandum under seal in U.S. District Court in
support of his motion of last Thursday to dismiss the two central
counts. The charges that would be dropped allege that North and
three co-defendants illegally diverted more than $14 million in
U.S.-Iran arms-sale profits to the Nicaraguan rebels.
   The memo was accompanied by declarations from Thornburgh and
Walsh, the independent counsel said in a statement. The material
outlines the position of the Reagan administration that, out of
concern for national security, it cannot allow certain classified
documents to be disclosed at North's trial in support of Walsh's
case.
   U.S. District Judge Gerhard Gesell refused to dismiss the two
counts on Monday, saying he first wanted an affidavit from
Thornburgh detailing the administration's objections to releasing
the classified material contained in documents Walsh wanted to use
to prosecute North.
   On Dec. 12, Gesell said a substantial amount of classified
material must be disclosed in order to give North a fair trial,
including the names of Central American countries where North was
involved in the secret resupply operation to the Contras.
   Gesell also said that the ranks and duties of officials of
foreign governments who appear in the classified documents must be
disclosed, although the judge permitted the names of the officials
to be deleted.
   Gesell also insisted that CIA personnel be identified as working
for the agency, although not by name, and that the text of
information obtained by intelligence be presented verbatim in most
instances.
   Last Thursday, Walsh moved to dismiss the conspiracy and theft
charges, citing North's ``insistence on introducing classified
information in his defense'' and the Reagan administration's refusal
to release material the judge ruled North would need at trial.
   North is still confronted with 12 felony charges that carry
prison terms totaling as much as 60 years.
   These include obstructing various congressional and presidential
inquiries into the Iran-Contra affair by preparing false statements
and destroying documents.
</TEXT>
