<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Quake 7thLd-Writethru a0584 01-12 0685</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Quake, 7th Ld-Writethru, a0584,0701</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Survivors Found in Rubble 35 Days After Armenian Earthquake</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Fixes 1st graf to clarify survivors weren't rescued today.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six people were pulled from the basement of a
collapsed apartment building in Leninakan, 35 days after the
Armenian earthquake, Tass said today. The men were quoted as saying
they survived on canned vegetables, fruit, pickles and ham.
   The survivors were rescued Wednesday, Tass said, the 35th day
after the Dec. 7 earthquake that killed an estimated 25,000 people
in northwest Armenia. Rescuers last pulled a person alive from the
wreckage Dec. 26, Tass said.
   The six men were found under the rubble in the basement of a
nine-story apartment building which had collapsed on them, the
official Soviet news agency said in a report from Yerevan, the
capital of Armenia.
   They survived because there was plenty of canned food stored in
the basement, Tass said. All are hospitalized in Yerevan but none
are in danger, doctors told the news agency.
   Tass did not say how the six men were found or who rescued them.
Officials had ended the search for survivors weeks ago, saying it
was necessary to clear away the rubble to prevent disease spreading
from decayed bodies.
   Authorities have been demolishing buildings that could not be
rebuilt after the earthquake.
   One of the six survivors, Aikaz Akopyan, had medical training and
administered massages to the others to relieve the pain of their
injuries, Tass said. One of the men, Karlen Sarkissyan, had a broken
arm and the others sustained only minor injuries, Tass said.
   ``On the day of the earthquake, I asked five neighbors to help me
carry two heavy wooden kegs to the basement,'' Akopyan was quoted as
telling Tass. ``Just then, we suddenly heard a terrible roar. The
earth trembled, and walls began to collapse. I thought a war had
started.''
   ``It's true, we used the food sparingly,'' the 50-year-old
electrician said. ``After all, we had no idea what had happened, nor
how long we would be entombed. We lost track of time completely. But
we never doubted for a minute that we would be found and released.
   ``I had only one thought _ to do everything necessary so my young
friends would not go crazy,'' Akopyan said. ``I entertained them,
calmed them, sang, and told stories about my life.''
   He identified two of the other survivors as Rafik Simonyan and
Vanik Khachaturyan. He said he could not remember the names of the
others.
   Akopyan said the men never had to worry about food and water
because the basement was used to store tins of vegetables, fruits
and pickles.
   ``It's true, we conserved the food in every possible way. But we
never doubted for a minute that we would be found and released,'' he
was quoted as saying.
   An editor at Armenpress, the Tass affiliate in Yerevan, said in a
telephone interview there were no details of how the men were
discovered because there is still only one telephone line to
Leninakan.
   The editor, who would not give his name, said Akopyan said
nothing about the rescue or conditions in the basement, and doctors
were refusing to allow further interviews with him because he had
developed pneumonia. He said his staff had not yet been able to meet
with the other five survivors.
   The quake leveled much of Leninakan, Armenia's second-largest
city 10 miles east of the Turkish border and left thousands homeless.
   Once home to more than 280,000 people, Leninakan today has only
100,000 inhabitants, thousands of whom now live in tents. Many
residents have been evacuated.
   Survivors also have had to deal with bitter cold conditions and
snow, which officials said hampered the rescue efforts.
   On Dec. 14, rescuers pulled a mother, Susanna Petrosyan, and her
4-year-old daughter, Gayaney, out of the rubble in Leninakan.
   The two had been buried alive for eight days. To keep her
daughter alive after their only food _ a jar of blackberry jam _ was
gone, the mother had cut her fingers and fed the child blood.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
