<HEAD>Quayle's Parents Still Stinging From Campaign Coverage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President-elect Dan Quayle's father
has turned his television set back on, but he said he and his wife
are still stinging from the slings and arrows flung at their son
during the presidential campaign.
   ``The untruths and distortions could have filled a 12-volume
encyclopedia,'' James C. Quayle told a hometown audience Wednesday.
   The elder Quayle, publisher of the Huntington Herald-Press, said
the family is still upset by media coverage of his son's selection
as President-elect George Bush's running mate, and of the campaign
that led to their election in November.
   ``I hope nobody at the Herald-Press does to you what the media
did to Dan,'' he told about 170 people at the Huntington Chamber of
Commerce dinner.
   Quayle said he and his wife, Corinne, developed a routine for
reading papers during the campaign. He would go out to the mailbox
and glance at the headlines. Then his wife would ask: ``Should I
read it?'' Often, he said, the answer was no.
   Quayle said he told a ``Nightline'' producer that he would not
talk to host Ted Koppel about their son's treatment by the media
because he and his wife were boycotting TV.
   ``We've turned our set back on, but only for Pat Buchanan (a
conservative commentator), the World Series and weather,'' he said
he told the producer.
   The Quayles received about 1,500 letters during the campaign,
most of them regarding their son's National Guard service and the
``you're no John Kennedy'' remark by Lloyd Bentsen, Michael Dukakis'
running mate, during the vice-presidential debate. Quayle said
responses on both were overwhelmingly in his son's favor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
