<HEAD>Police Stake Out Mortuary, Nab Suspect in 16-Year-Old Murder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators who saw an obituary on a murder
suspect's brother staked out the mortuary and arrested their man
when he showed up to view the body, police said today.
   Police arrested 37-year-old Donny G. Silcox on Wednesday in the
1973 slaying of 29-year-old John Paul Scott, a Canadian professor
whose body was found by a trucker last month in woods off a highway
in Carroll County, Miss.
   Police said Silcox confessed to the slaying when they found him
driving the victim's van a few weeks after Scott's disappearance. At
the time, Silcox accompanied police in the search for the body but
never was charged with murder because it wasn't found.
   Mississippi authorities issued a murder warrant for Silcox on
Tuesday after finding the remains. Silcox now faces extradition to
Mississippi.
   Police got a break after reading an obituary on the suspect's
brother, John Silcox, 39, who died Tuesday.
   Police said Silcox, who served a prison sentence for stealing
Scott's van and carrying a concealed weapon, reported that Scott had
picked up him up while he was hitch-hiking. Scott's skull contained
one bullet hole, authorities said.
