<FIRST>r i AM-Greece-US     01-12 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-US,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Major Progress Reported in Talks on U.S. Bases Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greek and American officials Thursday ended
another round of talks on U.S. military bases without making much
headway toward a new agreement, a government spokesman said.
   ``A disagreement of views continues to be observable even though
a deadlock was not noted,'' said Greek government spokesman Sotiris
Kostopoulos.
   A spokeswoman for the U.S. Embassy declined to comment on the
three-day talks.
   It was the first round of talks since a five-year operating
agreement for the four U.S. military installations expired Dec. 20.
Under the old accord, the United States has 17 months to negotiate a
new agreement or dismantle the bases.
   ``The talks were held, as in the past, in a serious and
professional climate and an exchange of views continued,''
Kostopoulos said.
   He said the talks, the 13th round since negotiations began in
November 1987, focused on the legal aspects of a ``possible'' new
agreement. He did not elaborate.
   He added, however, that negotiators were still at the
``preamble'' stage of a new accord.
   ``Discussion resumed on the preamble of a new agreement...which
has been under continuous processing during the negotiations,'' he
said
   The talks have made little progress because of the socialist
government's insistence that a new agreement provide assurances that
the United States will help solve the country's longtanding disputes
with neighboring Turkey. The two NATO allies have been at odds over
military control of the Aegean Sea, its seabed mineral rights and
the divided eastern Mediterranean island of Cyprus.
   U.S. officials say they don't want to involve regional politics
in the bilateral bases talks.
   Premier Andreas Papandreou, whose ruling Panhellenic Socialist
Movement has been rocked by series of financial scandals, is
expected to use the bases issue to attract leftist voters in the
upcoming June elections.
   In order to bolster public support, Papandreou has said he will
hold a national referendum on the bases and announced his intention
to scrap one of the installations: Hellenikon Air Force base
adjacent to Athens airport.
   Three other major bases have been operating here since the early
1950s _ another near Athens and two on the southern island of Crete.
</TEXT>
