<FIRST>r a AM-T-ShirtFlap     01-12 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-T-Shirt Flap,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Border Patrol Museum To Halt Sales of Controversial T-Shirt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A T-shirt being sold at the U.S. Border
Patrol Museum has been removed after complaints that it was
emblazoned with an ethnic slur.
   The $10 shirt is black and shows a grinning Mexican whose foot is
thrust through a wire fence, with the slogan, ``Who Are You Going To
Call?'' in an apparent spoof of the movie ``Ghostbusters.''
   The shirt has a circle slashed diagonally by a bar printed over
the man wearing a wide-brimmed sombrero. In the movie
``Ghostbusters,'' the slashed circle was printed over a ghost, to
represent a ghost exterminating business.
   ``It's obviously racist. I detest the racist attitudes we have in
El Paso,'' said Robert Conner, a registered nurse and free-lance
writer who complained about the shirts to the Border Patrol and the
El Paso Times. ``I thought that was a particularly obnoxious
manifestation of it.''
   Gus De La Vina, Border Patrol deputy chief in El Paso said Terry
Cornell, the museum's director, had assured him Wednesday that the
shirts will be removed.
   ``I talked to (Cornell) and she said the shirts were not meant by
any means as a racial slur,'' De La Vina said. ``Somebody came up
with the shirts and they've been selling them, but no more T-shirts
will be available.''
   The museum was created by the Fraternal Order of Retired Border
Patrol Officers and opened to the public in October 1985. Border
Patrol agents support the museum with contributions, but the agency
doesn't sanction the sale of any items, De La Vina said.
   ``This is not a T-shirt put out by the Border Patrol or
sanctioned by the Border Patrol,'' he said.
</TEXT>
