<FIRST>r a AM-ShuttleTest     01-12 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shuttle Test,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thiokol Reschedules Sixth And Final Booster Rocket Test-Firing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIGHAM CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Morton Thiokol Inc. has tentatively
rescheduled its final full-scale test-firing of the redesigned space
shuttle booster rocket for Wednesday.
   The firing will be the sixth and last full-scale test to formally
qualify major design features of the 126-foot-long solid-fuel
rocket, Morton Thiokol spokesman Rocky Raab said Thursday.
   The new booster already has been used on two successful shuttle
missions.
   Raab said the test, initially set for Tuesday at the company's
plant 25 miles west of Brigham City, was delayed because engineers
said additional time was needed to adequately chill the solid-fuel
motor.
   The procedure is necessary to test the redesigned rocket's new
heating system properly.
   NASA ordered the rocket redesigned after a presidential
commission blamed a faulty seal on one of Challenger's boosters for
the Jan. 28, 1986, explosion that killed its seven-member crew.
   Investigators found that one of the Challenger booster's O-ring
joint seals failed to contain superhot gases during launch. The
gases ignited the shuttle's exterior fuel tank.
   The disaster grounded the nation's manned space flight program
until last fall, when NASA launched Discovery using revamped
boosters that included more and stronger O-rings.
   Morton Thiokol engineers examined the new O-rings after shuttle
launches on Sept. 29 and Dec. 2 and found them in excellent
condition, Raab said.
</TEXT>
