<SECOND>PM-Drexel, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0546,0712</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drexel and Howard Baker End Talks; Shad Said to Be Considering Job</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with Drexel confirming it made
offer to Shad, and also asked Hills to become a director. PICKS UP 9th
graf pvs, `Word that ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. said today it has
asked former Securities and Exchange Commissionchairman John Shad to
become chairman of the Wall Street giant struggling to rebound from
a scandal raised by the SEC under Shad's leadership.
   The nation's fifth-largest securities firm also said it had
approached Roderick M. Hills, SEC chairman from 1975 to 1977, to
become a Drexel director. Hills, a trade consultant, is the husband
of Carla Hills, tapped by President-elect Bush to be U.S. trade
representative.
   Drexel said Chief Executive Officer Frederick Joseph,
instrumental in the firm's record $650 million settlement last month
of securities-fraud charges, would continue in that role. There had
been rumors he might resign.
   The announcements appeared to reflect an effort by Drexel's
senior management to distance the firm as much as possible from the
Wall Street insider trading scandal that has entangled it since late
1986.
   ``The firm's objective is to develop a fresh outlook on the
problems and opportunities it faces, and to continue to make an
important contribution to the nation's capital markets,'' Drexel
said in a statement disclosing the job offers.
   Leonardo Williams, information officer for the U.S. Embassy at
the Hague, Netherlands, where Shad is ambassador, confirmed in a
telephone query that he'd ``been approached by Drexel Burnham about
becoming chairman of the board.''
   Neither Williams nor Drexel would comment on a report in The New
York Times today that quoted unidentified sources as saying Shad was
close to accepting a Drexel offer.
   It was not clear whether Hills would accept the Drexel
invitation. A receptionist at the Manchester Group Ltd., a
Washington-based consulting firm of which Hills is chairman, said he
was out of the office.
   Shad ran the SEC when it began a fraud probe of Drexel more than
two years ago after speculator Ivan Boesky implicated the firm in
his illegal acts.
   That probe resulted in SEC securities-fraud charges against
Drexel as well as a record $650 million plea bargain with the U.S.
attorney's office last month.
   The firm has been seeking a well-known and respected figure to
take the chairman's job as part of an effort to recover from its
legal ordeal.
   Shad is credited with strengthening the agency's efforts to
reduce insider trading and other abuses on Wall Street. He resigned
in 1987 after a six-year tenure to accept the ambassador's post.
   Word that Shad had been approached came a day after Drexel said
it had agreed to end talks with former Sen. Howard Baker about a
possible role for the former White House chief of staff in the
firm's senior management.
   Baker had been negotiating with Drexel since November about a
senior role in the management of the nation's fifth-biggest
securities firm, possibly as chairman.
   His involvement was seen as part of a possible Drexel strategy to
minimize the impact of criminal charges that were then expected
against the firm and some of its key employees.
   The announcement came as Drexel and the SEC worked to settle a
civil suit filed by the agency against the firm in September. The
settlement of criminal charges was reached Dec. 21 but is not final
until resolution of the SEC suit.
   Drexel officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
talks might be completed in a few days. SEC spokeswoman Mary McCue
declined to comment.
   The government investigation into Drexel's financial dealings
began more than two years ago after now-imprisoned speculator Ivan
Boesky turned state's evidence and implicated the firm in his
illegal acts.
   Drexel denied wrongdoing until last month, when it was threatened
with possibly crippling charges of racketeering unless it agreed to
plead guilty to lesser charges.
   Under its settlement agreement, Drexel will plead guilty to six
unspecified felonies, pay a record $650 million in fines and
restitution and cooperate in the government's crackdown on
securities fraud.
</TEXT>
