<FIRST>r a AM-FreeBikes     01-12 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Free Bikes,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Businessman To Give Free Bikes To Kids Who Improve Grades, Attendance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A businessman whose efforts at philanthropy once
were rebuffed by an entire school has turned to bicycles as a way to
peddle education.
   Frank Argenbright is offering 1,500 students at 22 Atlanta
elementary schools free bicycles if they improve their attendance,
behavior and grades.
   ``To me, it will be a real ego thing for these kids to show off
those bikes,'' said Argenbright, chief executive officer of the
security and transportation firm Argenbright Inc. ``They'll have
worked hard to earn them.''
   Schools were chosen for their low or declining test scores, and
only students who aren't living up to their potential will be
offered a chance to earn a new bicycle.
   The principal and teachers at each of the participating schools
will select students for the program and will draw up a personal
challenge for each child, specifying what changes in attendance,
academic achievement and discipline must be demonstrated in order to
earn the bicycle.
   ``These are our students with the greatest potential to
improve,'' said Atlanta Superintendent J. Jerome Harris.
   ``I think this is an excellent program that will have a needed
impact on the students,'' said Kimberly Elementary School Principal
Effie Turner. ``Our underachievers and those children who are
overlooked or who are continually posing problems need that extra
incentive and this appears to be the answer.''
   The program will be launched at the Atlanta Civic Center on Jan.
19, and the students' progress will be monitored weekly.
   Argenbright promised to pay the administrative costs of the
program and chip in at least $5,000 toward the purchase of the
bicycles. He will try to raise another $100,000 from large
corporations.
   Argenbright hopes his latest plan will be more popular than last
year's offer of a free college education to each graduate of Madison
High School in his hometown of Madison, Fla. He flew 40 Madison
students to Morris Brown College in Atlanta to tour the city and
campus.
   ``And then not one single student even bothered to fill out the
application'' to attend Morris Brown, he said.
</TEXT>
