<FIRST>r w AM-East-WestMeeting     01-12 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East-West Meeting,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Supports Economic Conference in Bonn</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has agreed in principle to
convene an East-West economic conference in Bonn, West Germany, in
1990 as part of an overall agreement to expand economic ties, the
State Department announced Thursday.
   The purpose of the meeting, which still requires final approval,
is to exchange views on economic issues and for the 35 participating
nations to learn more about their economies, spokesman Charles E.
Redman said.
   However, Redman said, the meeting will not be a forum for
negotiations between East and West, nor will it deal with Western
controls on trade in strategic items.
   A final decision is expected before the 35 nations conclude their
review of the 1975 Helsinki agreement in Vienna. In all, 11
follow-up conferences have been proposed. Redman said the United
States wanted to scale the number down.
   The United States, Canada, the Soviet Union and 32 European
countries agreed in Helsinki to expand human, political and economic
contacts between East and West.
