<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 1541EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-India     01-12 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sikhs Kill 20 in Punjab</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikhs waging a separatist war in Punjab
killed 36 people, hanging four in revenge for the executions of two
Sikhs convicted in the assassination of Prime Minister Indira
Gandhi, police said Thursday.
   The two Sikhs were hanged Jan. 6 for the murder of Mrs. Gandhi,
who was shot down Oct. 31, 1984, by Sikh members of her personal
bodyguard. Militants have been fighting since 1982 for an
independent Sikh nation in Punjab, the only Indian state where the
sect has a majority.
   Police superintendent Govind Ram said the headman of Bhujiawali
village and his three brothers, all Hindus, were kidnapped Wednesday
night by a raiding party of five Sikhs and found hanging from trees
the next morning.
   He said a handwritten note claimed responsibility for an
underground Sikh militia and threatened more hangings of Hindus in
revenge for the executions of Satwant Singh and Kehar Singh at the
Tihar Central Jail in New Delhi.
   Others killed Thursday were a Hindu couple and their two
daughters and another Hindu couple; Sikh farmer Fakir Singh, his son
and nephew, and seven others killed in separate attacks, police
reported.
   Police in Chandigarh, the state capital, said 16 more people were
reported killed Wednesday night, including other relatives of the
hanged village headman and his brothers.
   Most victims of the Sikh radicals are Hindus, but they also
attack moderate Sikhs who oppose the separatist campaign.
   The latest deaths bring the number of people killed in Punjab so
far this year to more than 90. At least 2,400 people were killed in
1988.
   Although they have a majority in Punjab, a northern state that
includes India's richest agrucultural land, Sikhs make up less than
2 percent of this predominantly Hindu nation's 800 million people.
Those fighting for independence claim discrimination by the Hindus.
</TEXT>
