<SECOND>AM-Brites,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCK HILL, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No one quite knows why a Democrat with no
ties to George Bush got invited to his Jan. 20 inauguration, but the
lucky lady says she's putting the gift tickets in her pocket and
heading for the festivities.
   Mary Campbell, a former Democratic member of the Clover Town
Council, got the unasked-for tickets in the mail last month.
   It's only a guess, but her name may have something to do with the
mystery.
   Gov. Carroll Campbell and President-elect Bush, both Republicans,
are friends and political allies.
   Campbell, who is going to the inauguration, asked that his sister
Mary, who lives in Rock Hill, be mailed tickets as well.
   The sister, whose married name is Mary Carpenter, didn't get the
tickets. So the governor called for replacements for her.
   Tony Denny, executive director of the state Republican Party,
said he didn't know of any mix-up, but that Mary Campbell of Clover
is free to keep her tickets.
   ``Of course she is,'' he said. ``I don't know her, but I hope she
has a great time.''
   ``I have no idea how I got an invitation, and I'm not trying to
find out,'' Mrs. Campbell said. ``I am thrilled to be going and I
can't wait.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A team of wool wizards clipped, spun and
wove their way to victory turning a sheep's wool into a shawl in 107
minutes using techniques artisans used centuries ago.
   ``We have a good team, everybody worked well together,''
breathless team captain Carolyn Peyser said Wednesday night when the
judges announced the winner in the Pennsylvania Farm Show's Sheep to
Shawl contest.
   After buying the shawl for $1,600, Darryl Breniser of Blue Ball,
said the approximately 2-by-5 foot shawl was worth the money.
   ``It was a fair price,'' he said. ``They worked hard for it.''
   The team earned about $14.95 per minute of work on the shawl.
   The Wool Wizards of Dauphin County beat out eight other teams of
five.
   The contest began when nine shearers armed with snapping electric
razors unceremoniously hauled a sheep between their legs, waited for
the starting signal and began shaving the animal bald. Chris Herr,
shearer for the winning Wool Wizards, finished his sheep first in
about 2{ minutes.
   The workers then carded the wool, brushing it with paddles so the
fibers lay in one direction, worked it into yarn on a spinning
wheel, and finally wove it into a shawl on a wooden frame loom.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A billboard featuring a punk ``tooth
fairy'' has been put up by an artist who proposes building a huge
molar in the Grand River to honor the first city to fluoridate its
drinking water.
   The $550 billboard, put up Tuesday night, seeks support for
``Operation: Pearly White,'' of a proposed 600-pound, 18-foot-long
abstract sculpture of a fiberglass tooth balanced atop a stainless
steel pole 22 feet above the river, near downtown.
   Mark Heckman proposed his sculpture in June.
   But the West Michigan Dental Society objects to the sculpture,
contending a symbol of an extracted tooth may perpetuate stereotypes
linking dentistry to pain.
   ``The billboard's got a big-time wrestler'' posing as the tooth
fairy, Heckman said. ``He's got pink, spiked hair with a big white
tooth earring. He's a bad dude, 6-3, 230 pounds solid. The billboard
says `Tooth or Consequences' and says `Support Operation: Pearly
White.'''
   Heckman said Wednesday he's raising money for his sculpture, but
wouldn't say how much. The billboard will be in place for 10 days to
two weeks, he said.
</TEXT>
