<FIRST>r i AM-Sweden-Schools     01-12 0628</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sweden-Schools,0647</SECOND>
<HEAD>Schools in Firing Line of Finance Minister's Crusade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Proposed cuts in next year's school
budget have unleashed a tempest of opposition, with one 11-year-old
pupil reported to suggest that the finance minister ``should go hang
himself.''
   Expressen, the country's highest-circulation daily, ran the quote
in bold type. It said it was quoting an 11-year-old it identified as
Calle, one of hundreds of students who wrote to the daily papers to
complain of a proposed reductions in next year's school budget.
   Education exploded into a political drama when Finance Minister
Kjell-Olof Feldt, one of Sweden's most popular leaders, targeted
schools for spending reductions in the 1989-90 budget package
presented to Parliament this week.
   Trimming the education budget was Feldt's latest move to hold the
line on wages and put a lid on inflation, now running at more than 6
percent, well above the European average.
   Sweden's taxes have long been among the highest in the world, and
generous education benefits are a big part of what the taxes buy.
   On Wednesday, 12,000 primary and high-school students marched
through downtown Stockholm to Parliament. Some climbed up on window
ledges and overturned flowerpots, chanting ``Stop Feldt!''
   Opposition to Feldt's governing Social Democrats united in
Parliament and threatened to kill the budget legislation.
   Feldt said teachers' salaries went up last year by more than the
5.6 percent ceiling set by Parliament and that schools should take
into account a falling number of students.
   Primary school teachers' salaries start at $1,400 monthly, and
college-trained teachers with 15 years of experience earn $2,267,
near the average national income.
   Critics charge that the planned cut of $27 million from
education, or 0.5 percent of its budget, ignored a crisis resulting
from 10 years of insufficent government allocations.
   They say school buildings are falling into disrepair, tattered
textbooks are handed from one class to the next, and qualified
teachers are abandoning education for better-paid jobs in industry.
   The protesters demand a limit of 20 pupils per class, newer
books, better food in schools, and a doubling of the monthly
government stipend to each student from the current $78.
   Feldt's proposals are part of his broad efforts to keep the
Swedish budget in shape. In seven years as finance minister, he has
wiped out a huge annual deficit to give Sweden its first surplus
budget since 1962, often through policies that go against the
socialist leanings of his party.
   He has proposed a sweeping reform to simplify taxes, plug
deduction loopholes and reduce tax on overtime payments.
   At the same time, Feldt has been unable to buck the tide in his
party for more benefits and leisure time for workers.
   The Social Democrats have promised six weeks annual vacation for
everyone. They have pledged to extend parental leave for new parents
_ mother or father _ from nine months with full pay to 12 months
this year and 18 months in 1990.
   The school crisis has prompted Claes-Goran Kjellander, political
editor of the conservative Svenska Dagbladet, to question Swedes'
favorable attitude toward Feldt and his predecessors.
   ``They raise our taxes, they spend our money for unnecessary
things, and cut the grants for things we think are important. This
is repeated year after year. The more it's repeated, the better we
like them,'' he wrote.
   The pupil identified as Calle was reported to hold other notions.
   After Feldt complained that Expressen reached ``the lowest point
of Swedish journalism'' by using the schoolboy to attack his draft
budget, Expressen put this response from Calle on its front page:
   ``Hey, Kjell-Olof Feldt: You know you don't really have to hang
yourself. I only meant, for example, `Go throw yourself against a
wall.' You are making a booboo.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
