<FIRST>r i AM-Bhutto     01-12 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bhutto,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Returns from First Trip Abroad</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ISL1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Benazir Bhutto came home Thursday from
her first trip abroad as prime minister, a pilgrimage to Moslem holy
sites during which she discussed Afghanistan and the Middle East
with King Fahd of Saudi Arabia.
   Ms. Bhutto, the first woman to lead a Moslem nation, did not say
whether she and Fahd would press Afghan guerrillas for a political
settlement before the Feb. 15 deadline for withdrawal of Soviet
forces.
   ``We are watching what form of government is offered by the
mujahedeen (guerrillas) before making an assessment of the Afghan
problem,'' she said. ``It's for the Afghans to decide ... because
they're the ones fighting.''
   Pakistan, Saudi Arabia and the United States support the Moslem
guerrillas, who began fighting after a communist coup in April 1978.
Soviet military forces entered the country in December 1979 and an
estimated 115,000 Red Army soldiers were there when withdrawals
began May. 15 under a U.N.-mediated agreement.
   The insurgents, most of whom are based in neighboring Pakistan,
broke off direct talks with the Soviets this week to protest Kremlin
insistence that Communists be included in a postwar government.
   About 3.5 Afghan refugees live in border camps and towns in
Pakistan, which the insurgents use as bases and supply points.
   Reports in Pakistani newspapers have said Ms. Bhutto's government
is trying for a resumption of negotiations to avoid more bloodshed
after the Soviets leave.
   Ms. Bhutto, 35, said the religious part of her first trip abroad
since taking office Dec. 2, including a visit to Mecca, was a
pilgrimage ``to offer prayers and thanksgiving to God for the
restoration of ... democratic rule in Pakistan.''
   Her Pakistan People's Party won the most Parliament seats in the
first free elections for more than a decade. The last were under her
father, Prime Minister Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, who was overthrown by
Gen. Mohammad Zia ul-Haq in 1977 and hanged two years later.
   Zia died in a plane crash in August.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
