<FIRST>r a AM-Philadelphia-Markers     01-12 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philadelphia-Markers,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmaker Introduces Resolution to Commemorate Civil Rights Deaths</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Mississippi legislator introduced a
resolution Thursday to commemorate the 25th anniversary of the
slayings of three civil rights workers in 1964.
   Rep. George Flaggs Jr. said the resolution would put the state of
Mississippi ``on record'' in commemorating the June 21, 1964, deaths
of James Earl Chaney, Andrew Goodman and Michael Schwerner.
   None of the sites of significant events during the civil rights
era bear state monuments, including the site near Philadelphia,
Miss., where the three slain civil rights workers were found buried
in an earthen dam.
   There is a monument to the three men at Philadelphia, but it was
erected by the Mississippi NAACP.
   Talk about state markers has been fueled in recent weeks by the
release of the movie ``Mississippi Burning,'' a fictionalized
account of the slayings and subsequent investigation.
   ``We keep saying Mississippi is changing,'' said Cleve McDowell,
former field director for the state NAACP, ``but we don't do
anything to show it.''
   A state marker ``would speak louder and show we actually have
changed,'' McDowell said. ``That would be a better indicator that
Mississippi is changing than anything else.''
   It was too early to assess reaction from the Legislature. Flaggs
issued a statement saying the three civil rights workers ``dedicated
and sacrificed their lives for the benefit of others.''
   ``It is imperative that the citizens of this state recognize the
humanist efforts which were demonstrated by those three courageous
civil rights workers who believed in justice and equality for
everyone, regardless of race, color or creed,'' he said.
   State historian Michael Beard said funding for state markers was
lost in 1980 and has not been restored. But he called the slayings
the turning point in the civil rights movement, and clearly favored
commemorating them.
   ``It's one of the most historic sites in Mississippi,'' he said.
A marker, he said, would show ``we can recognize the truth and no
longer cover it up. We are no longer a closed society.''
</TEXT>
