<FIRST>r i AM-ArabLeague     01-12 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arab League,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arab League Denounces U.S. Action Against Libyan Jets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Arab League on Thursday condemned the
U.S. downing of two Libyan jets Jan. 4 as a threat to all Arab
nations.
   The 21-nation Arab League issued a statement of condemnation at
the end of a special session in Tunis called at the request of
Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi.
   Palestine Liberation Organization chairman Yasser Arafat
addressed a league committee and berated Arab colleagues for
reneging on their promise of aid to the people of the Israeli
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The resolution on the jet downing asked the United States to
``refrain from all actions against Libya that could have negative
consequences on Arab-American relations.''
   During the meeting, Libyan Foreign Minister Jadallah Azzouz Talhi
said U.S. actions against his country were aimed at dissuading Arab
states from possessing arms that could threaten Israel.
   Gadhafi requested the meeting of foreign ministers after two U.S.
Navy planes downed the Libyan jets, which American officials say
were about to attack the U.S. craft.
   The United States says the action was unrelated to concern that
Libya has built a plant for making chemical weapons.
   The plant, which Libya says is for producing medicine, was a main
topic at a five-day international conference this week in Paris on
banning chemical weapons.
   ``The U.S. has the biggest stock of chemical arms in the world,
and it is trying to obstruct other countries from having their
own,'' said Arab League Secretary-General Chedli Klibi.
   The conference ended without agreement on a ban.
   Arab League members who attended sought to tie chemical
disarmament to nuclear disarmament. They said that until Israel
gives up its nuclear force, Arab states need chemical arms for
defense.
   The Arab position was not included in the final document.
   Arafat spoke to the league's uprising subcommittee of six foreign
ministers that has been responsible for ensuring support for
Palestinians in the occupied territories. He charged the group with
neglecting its responsibility.
   The exact amount of aid promised is not known, but is generally
believed to be about $128 million in emergency aid and $43 million
in additional help each month.
   Arafat first began complaining about a lack of aid at a June
meeting in Algiers that was dedicated to organising financial and
diplomatic support for Palestinians.
   The committee issued a statement urging league members to adhere
to their promises.
</TEXT>
