<FIRST>r i AM-India-Carbide     01-12 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Carbide,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge in Bhopal Gas Leak Case is Transferred</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BHOPAL, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge hearing the case for compensation
to victims of the 1984 gas leak in this city has been transferred
after he was found to be biased against the company, officials said
Thursday.
   He is the fourth judge to be moved from the Bhopal District Court
trying the case since the world's largest civil suit began in 1985.
   The state High Court ruled in November that Bhopal District Judge
M.W. Deo was prejudiced after Union Carbide Corp. complained that he
ordered it to pay interim relief of $290 million to victims before
fixing liability for the leak.
   Deo was transferred to a trial court at Mandleshwar in central
Madhya Pradesh state, 190 miles east of the state capital Bhopal,
according to officials handling the case who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Nirmal K. Jain, another district judge, has been appointed to
hear the case in Bhopal, the officials said.
   Two earlier judges resigned voluntarily. Another was removed when
he was found to be among the 500,000 claimants.
   The Indian government, which filed suit on behalf of all the
victims, says at least 20,000 people are still suffering from
exposure to the toxic gas that leaked out of the Bhopal pesticide
plant on Dec. 3, 1984. More than 3,300 people were killed.
   India's $3 billion damage suit against Union Carbide, a
multinational whose Indian subsidiary operated the plant, has bogged
down in the country's labyrinthine court system.
   Union Carbide, whose headquarters are in Danbury, Conn., says the
gas leak was the result of sabotage by an employee. The Indian
government contends the leak was caused by negligence.
</TEXT>
