<FIRST>u i AM-SriLanka     01-12 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sri Lankan Government Frees Hundreds of Political Prisoners</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government released more than 200
political prisoners Thursday after newly elected President
Ranasinghe Premadasa lifted a 5{-year state of emergency in this
ethnically troubled land, the military said.
   ``I still don't know why I was brought here,'' said Jeffrey
Simon, 39, as he left Tyronne Fernando Cricket Stadium, a temporary
military camp in Moratuwa, about six miles south of Colombo.
   Rupasinghe Padmasiri, the father of another prisoner, said, ``My
son is a rice paddy farmer, the father of three children. He has no
involvement with the Sinhalese extremists.'' He said his 28-year-old
son, Panduka, was arrested while buying groceries.
   Military officials speaking on condition of anonymity said 234
political prisoners were freed after the emergency rules were lifted
at midnight.
   The rules were imposed in May 1983 after ethnic riots between the
Sinhalese majority and Tamils, who are fighting for independence.
Extended month by month, they empowered security forces to arrest
and indefinitely detain a suspect without charge and to search
houses without warrants.
   When the president revoked the emergency state three days before
it was again to expire, he said about 1,800 political prisoners
detained without charge would be released.
   Within hours, 110 prisoners were freed at a detention camp in
southern Sri Lanka, the military said. Ninety-nine were released
from the Moratuwa camp, and 25 others were allowed to leave a prison
in Colombo, it said.
   All had been held without charge since November for alleged
involvement with Sinhalese extremists trying to overthrow the
government, said one military official. Each signed a statement
before leaving prison saying he had been treated well and would not
bring charges against security forces, the official said.
   Military officials said other prisoners would be released later
but gave no details. The detainees include both Sinhalese and Tamils
accused of violence against the state and assassinations of
government legislators, police and soldiers.
   This island off the southern tip of India has suffered spiraling
violence since 1983, when militant Tamils launched their separatist
war.
   Since then, more than 8,500 people, mostly Sinhalese civilians,
have died in massacres, ambushes and guerrilla battles. The dead
include more than 600 Indian soldiers, part of a peacekeeping force
sent to Sri Lanka in July 1987 to try to disarm Tamil insurgents.
   In his campaign for president, Premadasa pledged to press for
withdrawal of the 50,000 Indian troops. A few thousand were reported
to be pulled out earlier this month.
   Premadasa, a Sinhalese, was sworn in as president on Jan. 2 after
winning last month's presidential election.
   In addition to the other deaths, more than 650 government
supporters, mostly Sinhalese, have been killed by Sinhalese
extremists. They oppose former President Junius R. Jayewardene's
efforts to make peace with the Tamils by granting them limited
automony in the northern and eastern provinces.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindu, make up 18 percent of the island's
16 million people. They say they are denied jobs and education by
the Buddhist Sinhalese, who comprise 75 percent of the population
and control the government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
