<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 1905EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AirlinerTests     01-12 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Airliner Tests,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airlines Begin Testing For Cross-Wiring In 737s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. airlines began testing Thursday for faulty
engine warning systems in Boeing 737 airliners similar to one that
crashed in England. A spokesman for one U.S carrier said 80 percent
of its 737s had been tested with no problems found.
   Officials of other airlines said they were complying with the
testing as a precautionary measure but expected to find no faulty
wiring of fire and vibration warning lights that might mislead a
pilot into shutting down his only good engine if the other one
showed problems.
   That is one possibility being investigated in England, where a
British Midland 737 crash killed 44 people Sunday. Investigators
said the pilot was trying to land with his malfunctioning left
engine after his good right engine was shut down.
   Tests on British-owned planes were completed Thursday under a
Civil Aviation Authority order that grounded them until the systems
were checked out. No problems were reported.
   The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration ``air worthiness
directive'' issued late Wednesday did not order any U.S. planes
grounded. It gave airlines with 292 Boeing 737-300s and eight
737-400s until Sunday morning to conduct checks for possible
cross-wiring. Each test takes about an hour.
   The British agency also ordered increased inspections of CFM56
engines on the planes, but the FAA had not taken that step. FAA
officials identified the affected airlines as Aloha, America West,
American, Continental, Delta, Orion, Piedmont, Southwest, United and
U.S. Air.
   ``We found no anomalies or discrepancies,'' said Continental
spokesman David Messing in Houston, reporting on inspections
conducted by Thursday afternoon. He said 80 percent of the 55 Boeing
737-300s flown by Continental had been checked and the rest would be
finished overnight.
   He said no flights were affected by the checks.
   United spokeswoman Sara Dornacker in Chicago said the airline
supported the FAA action ``even though we regard it as
precautionary.''
   She said all of United's fleet of 49 affected airliners had been
tested for possible cross-wiring by test pilots after delivery from
the Boeing factory.
   United inspections were to be conducted Thursday, Friday and
Saturday nights at airports around the country, she said.
   American spokesman Jim Brown said inspections of some of the
airlines' eight 737s were conducted Thursday, and the remainder
would take place before Sunday.
   ``We have no reason to expect discovery of any abnormalities in
these systems,'' Brown said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
