<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan-Starvation     01-12 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan-Starvation,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands More Reported Dead of Starvation in Sudan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 6,000 people starved to death in
southern Sudan in the past three months, but international airlifts
of food and medicine have improved the situation, a Red Cross
official said Thursday.
   Dominique Beuff of the International Committee of the Red Cross
in Khartoum said he had reports of people dying at the rate of up to
four a day in some areas of the south affected by a 5-year-old civil
war.
   Reith Chuol, governor of the Upper Nile region, told reporters
there were unconfirmed reports of 15 people dying there every day.
No relief aid has reached the Upper Nile.
   Beuff said: ``Between last September and December, about 6,000
people have died in the south of the Sudan, but that is not the case
anymore. ... People suffer but they are not dying. The situation is
still not under control, but it is better than last year.''
   Since the civil war began, nearly 2 million southerners have fled
fighting in the countryside, trekking northward or going to
government-controlled towns where they became dependent on relief
food.
   Western relief officials estimate up to 560,000 southerners died
from starvation, disease or fighting in 1988.
   Rebels led by John Garang, a former army colonel, are fighting
for greater autonomy for the south, most of whose people are
Christian or animist, from Moslem-dominated northern Sudan.
   Last summer, tens of thousands of southerners were isolated by
heavy rains and thousands died of starvation.
   When the rains ended, several international airlifts started
flying food and medicine to the towns in the Bahr el-Ghazal and
Equatoria regions. Several operations by the Red Cross and United
Nations continue.
   As many as 80 people a day died last summer in Bahr el-Ghazal
towns.
</TEXT>
