<FIRST>r w AM-Abrams-Salvador     01-12 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abrams-Salvador,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Sees Rebel ``Campaign of Terror'' in El Salvador''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assistant Secretary of State Elliott Abrams
claimed Thursday that El Salvador's leftist rebels have had to
resort to a ``campaign of terror'' against civilian targets because
of declining popular support and increased resistance from the
country's armed forces.
   Abrams, in a speech at the University of Oklahoma, said the
rebels have assassinated eight mayors in recent months, prompting 35
other mayors to resign.
   ``Denied success in the countryside, the guerrillas have embarked
on a campaign of terror in the cities,'' said Abrams, whose remarks
were made available by the State Department.
   The rebels have met greater resistance from the armed forces and
have had difficulty recruiting, forcing them to press men ``_ indeed
children _ into a dirty war,'' he said.
   ``These are the tactics of a marginalized force driven to
extremes by desperation,'' said Abrams, whose 3{-year service as
head of the Latin America bureau will end next week with the
inauguration of President-elect Bush.
   He expects to practice law after spending about two months with
the Heritage Foundation, a conservative research group.
   Summing up what he described as the eight-year legacy of
President Reagan in Latin America, Abrams praised the democratic
gains in the hemisphere and touched only briefly on the region's
debt-induced economic crisis, which has led to declining living
standards in most countries.
   The return of economic growth, he said, ``will depend upon a
pragmatic, open-ended search for solutions among creditors and
debtors _ coming together as partners realizing their common stake
in the outcome.''
   Abrams also was sparing his in remarks on Nicaragua, his major
area of concern since his appointment in 1985.
   ``The Nicaragua that chose to become part of the Soviet bloc was
not democratic,'' Abrams said. ``A democratic Nicaragua would have
no use for a standing army of intimidating dimensions. Real peace in
Central America depends on the prospects for democratization in
Nicaragua.''
   He made no reference to the Nicaraguan Contras, who have had
unswerving support from Abrams.
   Expressing confidence that El Salvador's fledgling democracy will
be able to ride out the rebel challenge, he said the electoral
process which began in that country six years ago led to a marked
improvement in the security situation there.
   ``As the people voted in record numbers to put civilian leaders
in charge, the military, freed to meet its professional challenge,
began to reverse the progress made by the guerrillas.
   ``At the same time, a people who could see the prospects for
peaceful change under elected governments could only reject the
violence of the guerrillas as gratuitous and regressive.''
</TEXT>
