<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 1911EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-KingCelebrations     01-12 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-King Celebrations,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rosa Parks Says the Fight is Not Over</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rosa Parks, whose refusal to sit at the back of
the bus sparked the modern civil rights movement, said the fight
continues as she joined others Thursday honoring the Rev. Martin
Luther King Jr.
   King rose to prominence after Mrs. Parks' action in December 1955
in Montgomery, Ala., set the stage for a boycott and subsequent
demonstrations that caught the nation by surprise.
   King was killed April 4, 1968, in Memphis, Tenn., and what would
be his 60th birthday Sunday is celebrated as a national holiday
Monday; the celebration began with several events on Thursday.
   Mrs. Parks, 75, praised King as she answered questions on radio
station WLIB. She said the struggle to attain rights is not over.
   ``I feel a kindred to the people of South Africa as well as any
other people who are being denied freedom, and as we try to free
ourselves we must help those who are not free and are suffering all
kinds of physical reprisals or denial,'' she told listeners.
   ``It seems as long as we don't all unite together en masse that
we will have to repeat marches over and over again and I do hope to
live to know and see the day come when we will all be free citizens,
to have any opportunity any other persons have to assume the
responsibilities as others.''
   At a breakfast at the Waldorf-Astoria sponsored by the NAACP and
Anheuser-Busch Cos., several people were honored who exemplified
King's meaning of taking ``the measure of a man'' at times ``of
challenge and controversy.''
   Those honored were Jean Griffith, mother of a man killed on a
Howard Beach, Queens, parkway after being chased by a gang of whites
in December 1986; Jean Chappell, president of an advocacy and
service group helping welfare hotel residents; and Diane and Ernest
McCaine, who adopted a child with AIDS.
   The American Jewish Congress held a meeting for 100 school
children, about one-third Jewish, two-thirds black, to emphasize
that the ``black and Jewish communities have long worked together in
the movement for civil rights,'' the congress said.
   Attending were Spencer Christian of ABC's ``Good Morning,
America''; Bob McGrath of ``Sesame Street''; former New York Met
Rusty Staub; city Comptroller Harrison J. Goldin; and Manhattan
Borough President David Dinkins.
   ``The friendship between African-Americans and Jews, the alliance
for social change, goes back a long way, well before the '60s,''
Dinkins told the gathering. ``Dr. King understood that when he spoke
out against anti-Semitism and said that nobody should be
anti-Semitic, least of all blacks.''
</TEXT>
