<FIRST>r w AM-Flue-curedFees     01-12 0169</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flue-cured Fees,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>USDA Sets '89 Assessment at 1.12 Cents Per Pound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flue-cured tobacco farmers and buyers each will
be assessed 1.12 cents per pound for the 1989 crop, the Agriculture
Department said Thursday.
   The total of 2.24 cents covers a no-net cost assessment of 2
cents per pound and 0.24 cents to help cover the federal budget
deficit. The total 1989 assessment will be down slightly from last
year's 2.26 cents per pound.
   Department officials said they consulted with the Flue-cured
Tobacco Cooperative Stabilization Corp., the producer-owned
association that handles the support program, before determining the
1989 assessment.
   The budget deficit assessment will be imposed according to the
Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act of 1987, which calls for a
reduction in the price support level by 1.4 percent or,
alternatively, an assessment on producers to achieve an equal
reduction in spending.
   Officials said the 1989 price support for flue-cured tobacco will
remain at $1.468 per pound as announced on Dec. 15 for this year's
crop.
</TEXT>
