<FIRST>r w AM-Murders-Non-Whites     01-12 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Murders-Non-Whites,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Non White Males More Likely to Be Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The odds of becoming a murder victim are five
times greater for non-white males born now than for the overall
population of the United States, the FBI said Thursday.
   Americans born today have a 1 out of 177 chance of being
murdered, while the risk for non-white males is 1 in 38, according
to the study based on 1987 Uniform Crime Reporting statistics added
to a computer model.
   If there were no murders, the average lifespan for all Americans
would increase by almost 3 months, and the average lifespan for
non-white males would increase by more than 11 months, the study
found.
   Sharon Propheter, a statistician with the Uniform Crime Reporting
program, cautioned the predictions are based on 1987 figures and do
not account for the possibility of substantial changes in the murder
rates.
   ``We can't look into the future and say there are going to be so
many murders in 1999,'' said Propheter, who compiled the report with
statistician Harvey Rosenthal. ``This is based on what happened in
1987.''
   In 1987, when the murder rate was 8.3 per 100,000 population,
there were an estimated 20,100 murders. Of those, 9,510 were
non-white, 7,436 of them non-white males.
   The study _ which calculated the probabilities of being murdered
for newborns, those age 20 and those age 40 _ did not break down the
non-white category for blacks, Hispanics and other minorities,
Propheter said.
   The study predicted that while newborn non-white males have a one
in 38 chance of becoming a murder victim, the chance for non-white
females is one in 138. For both sexes, the chance is one in 60.
   For newborn white males, the chance is one in 204, while for
white females, it's one in 437 for a combined chance of one in 277.
   For newborns of all races, the chance of being murdered is one in
122 for males, one in 324 for females and one in 177 for both sexes.
   As for men who already have reached age 20, non-whites have a one
in 41 chance of being murdered, while whites have a one in 224
chance, for an overall chance of one in 136.
   For females who are now 20, non-whites have a one in 157
likelihood of being murdered, and whites have a one in 504 chance
for a total probability of one in 376.
   The least likely to be murdered _ among the ages calculated by
the FBI _ are white women who are now 40. They have only a one in
931 chance of being murdered. Of all the groups now 40, the highest
probability of being murdered remains non-white males, with a one in
97 chance.
   The overall murder rate in the United States has leaped 34
percent between 1967 and 1987, the FBI reported. In the past 10
years, the highest rate was 10.2 per 100,000 population in 1980, and
the lowest was 7.9 per 100,000 in 1984 and 1985. The 1987 rate of
8.3 per 100,000 compares with 2.5 per 100,000 in Canada.
   In 1987, 36.7 percent of murders resulted from arguments, and
19.6 percent occurred in connection with felonies such as robbery,
narcotics, sex offenses and arson, said Chris Waskiewicz, an editor
with the Uniform Crime Reporting unit.
   Meanwhile, 1.1 percent occurred from suspected felonies, 17.7
were miscellaneous _ including such things as the assailant being
under the influence of alcohol or drugs _ and the circumstances for
24.9 percent are unknown, she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
