<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Walesa     01-12 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Walesa,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Warns of Worsening Social Mood</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lech Walesa said Thursday the people are
angry and trouble is in store unless a Communist Party Central
Committee meeting next week does something to improve living
conditions.
   Walesa, a shipyard electrician who founded the independent
Solidarity union movement in 1980, said Poles are restive and fed up
with high prices and shortages.
   ``We hope for God's sake that this plenum will go a little bit
farther than its own nose,'' He told a news conference in Gdansk.
``If it doesn't, it will be like a shout of encouragement to society
and to us all, and I don't know where we will end up.
   ``I appeal for getting out in front of society's demands. If not,
I'm really afraid.''
   The meeting Monday and Tuesday of the 230-member Central
Committee is expected to produce confrontation between conservatives
and those willing to recognize Solidarity and negotiate with the
opposition.
   Solidarity was legal after its birth in the labor turmoil of
August 1980 as the first free trade union in the Soviet bloc. It was
suppressed and outlawed after the imposition of martial law in
December 1981.
   Walesa said Solidarity wants to avoid unrest.
   ``We want it to be quiet ...both for the side of Solidarity and
the government ... to get ready for talks, for attempts at
solutions,'' he said. ``So we've given plenty of time.
   ``Unfortunately I am worried because there have been more and
more days, but no more solutions. ... There are price hikes, but
there is a lack of effect of reforms. ... Society is so tired, so
fed up with it.''
   He said he had expected protests to begin in April if nothing was
done, ``but it may happen sooner. Let's hope we can avoid it. Poland
really doesn't need it.''
   A rally of several thousand Solidarity supporters was held
Tuesday at the Lenin Shipyard in Gdansk, where Walesa works. He
mentioned that during the news conference, along with minor work
stoppages or strike threats at various plants in the past few weeks.
   In an appeal for unity, he said: ``If we start jumping out in
different places over different problems it will be anarchy, and it
will be a reason that may be used to strike against (the union's)
mainstream, to break, dissolve and destroy it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
