<DOCNO> AP890112-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 1730EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Reagan-NuclearSafety     01-12 0778</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagan-Nuclear Safety,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Calls For Major Overhaul, Cleanup Of Atomic Arms Complex</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Thursday recommended
spending $81 billion over 20 years to modernize the government's
crippled nuclear arms factories and to begin cleaning up the
nationwide trail of waste left by four decades of bomb-making.
   President-elect Bush said he did not know whether he would
support the proposal, which was prepared by the Energy Department.
   The plan includes closing four nuclear materials plants,
consolidating work at other facilities and building two reactors to
make a radioactive gas vital to continued production of nuclear
warheads.
   Reagan, in a report to Congress, said the blueprint ``will enable
the administration and the Congress to adopt a long-term approach to
modernization rather than a piecemeal response to the problems
within the nuclear weapons complex.''
   The cost of modernizing the aging weapons-making plants through
the year 2010 would be at least $52 billion, the report said.
Cleanup costs over that period would total $29 billion, although the
report said environmental repairs would have to continue far beyond
2010. There are 17 major plants in 12 states.
   These figures are in addition to normal operating costs over the
next 20 years which, combined with the modernizing and cleanup
costs, would total $244 billion.
   The cost estimates underscore the difficulties facing the
incoming Bush administration, which has pledged to maintain the
nation's nuclear deterrent while protecting the environment and
cutting government spending to balance the budget.
   Coincidentally, Reagan sent his recommendations to Congress on
the same day that Bush nominated retired Adm. James D. Watkins to
head the Energy Department, which is responsible for developing,
building and testing the nation's nuclear warheads.
   Bush told a news conference he did not feel bound by the
recommendations in Reagan's report and indicated he would make no
decisions on the weapons plants problem until after he and Watkins
had studied the security implications.
   ``I think there's a risk, if we imprudently go forward, until he
and I have had a chance to take a hard look,'' Bush said.
   Watkins was trained in nuclear engineering during a 1958 stint at
Oak Ridge, Tenn., National Laboratory _ one of the military-related
nuclear weapons facilities.
   Concern over the nuclear weapons complex heightened last fall
after the last of the nation's tritium-producing reactors at the
Savannah River Plant near Aiken, S.C., was shut down for safety
reasons. Tritium is a short-lived gas that is vital in nearly all
U.S. nuclear warheads. Pentagon officials have expressed concern
that unless at least one tritium-making reactor is restarted soon
the nation's nuclear arsenal could be weakened.
   Reagan's report to Congress said it was unlikely the Savannah
River reactors would be operating before the end of the year. The
unclassified version released publicly did not say whether that
would be soon enough to avoid a tritium shortage.
   It appeared to suggest, however, that even after costly safety
and technical improvements, the Savannah River facilities would be
unable to supply enough tritium.
   ``In spite of these improvements and increasingly extensive
maintenance, the reactors may not be able to achieve acceptable
production efficiencies,'' the report said.
   The report specifically recommended:
   _Investing $400 million to improve safety and technical
operations at the Rocky Flats plutonium-processing plant near
Denver, Colo., and then spending $6.1 billion to close down the
plant and transfer its operations to other sites.
   _Phasing out all nuclear materials-processing work at the Hanford
Plant near Richland, Wash., between 1995 and 2000. A cost estimate
was not made available. This plant, opened in 1944, was one of three
original Manhattan Project sites responsible for producing
plutonium, including the material used in the bomb that destroyed
Nagasaki.
   _Shutting down the Feed Materials Production Center at Fernald,
Ohio, and shifting its operations elsewhere. The report gave no
specific cost figure and did not say where the Fernald activities
should be moved. This plant, which makes uranium metal cores used in
nuclear reactors at Savannah River and Hanford, has drawn fierce
public opposition due to leaks of uranium dust into the atmosphere
and toxic chemicals and uranium into wells used for drinking water.
   _Transferring the nuclear waste-recovery operations of the Mound
Plant, near Cincinnati, to other unspecified Energy Department
weapons plants at a cost of $255 million, starting in 1995. The
plant's main work _ producing small explosive devices and timers for
nuclear weapons _ would continue at the same site.
   _Building two new nuclear reactors to produce tritium. The report
said the preferred sites would be at Savannah River and at the Idaho
National Engineering Laboratory, near Idaho Falls. It estimated the
combined cost at $6.6 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
