<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 1732EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-CargoPlaneCrash     01-12 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cargo Plane Crash,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Killed in Crash of Cargo Plane</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assciated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canadian cargo plane crashed and exploded
in a fireball near a row of houses Thursday, killing the two pilots
aboard and setting nearby woods afire, authorities said.
   ``We thought we were dead. That's how close it was,'' said Dewey
Meade, who was in his home a few hundred yards from the crash site.
``We've got debris all over the roof and everything.''
   No one on the ground was injured, and no homes suffered serious
damage.
   Bruce Jonasson, manager of Bradley First Air, said pilots from
Montreal and Ottawa were the plane's only occupants. Jonasson
declined to release their names until families had been notified.
   A small quantity of explosive and corrosive materials were aboard
the plane, but they posed no environmental hazard, Jonasson said.
   The twin-engine plane took off from Dayton International Airport
and crashed at 4:45 a.m. in a heavily wooded area about a half-mile
away, said James Francis, acting aviation director for Dayton.
   Meade described it as ``a fireball coming right at the side of my
house.''
   The explosion set fire to about 100 yards of wooded area, said
Lt. Jim Bowell of the Butler Township Fire Department. Several
witnesses reported seeing a fireball in the air before the crash.
   Several hours after the crash, broken limbs and branches
surrounded the smoldering wreckage and small fires continued to
burn, although they were later extinguished. Boxes and other cargo
littered the area.
   Two bodies were discovered at the site, one in the wreckage of
the Hawker-Siddley turboprop and the other nearby, said Gene Brown,
chief investigator for the Montgomery County coronor's office.
   The plane, owned by Bradley First Air, of Ottawa, Canada, was
carrying cargo to Montreal for Emery Air Freight Corp., an air
freight courier service with a hub at the Dayton airport. It was at
least 9 years old.
   Airport officials said they were unsure how long the aircraft was
in the air following takeoff.
   Gary Hess, an Emery employee, saw the plane go down as he was
getting off work at the airport.
   ``It was kind of like just going across the horizon, and then it
just blew,'' he said. ``It was just a big ball of fire.''
   Joe Weitz, another Emery employee, said the plane appeared to
burst into flame shortly after it cleared the runway.
</TEXT>
