<FIRST>r w AM-SAfricanTape 1stLd-Writethru a0673 01-12 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrican Tape, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0673,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Recorder Fished From Deep Ocean Offers Possible Clues In Year-Old
Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT that only tape taken to NTSB.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cockpit recorder recovered by an underwater
robot from the year-old wreckage of a South African Airways Boeing
747 nearly three miles deep in the Indian Ocean could provide the
latest clue in a $6 million effort to determine cause of the crash
that killed 159 people.
   The recorder's tape, recovered from the ocean last week, was
taken Thursday by South African investigators to the National
Transportation Safety Board, where it was copied for use by the
investigators.
   Safety board officials said they only provided equipment for
processing the tape and would have no role in playing, transcribing
or analysing it. The Unites States is providing the technical
assistance at the request of the South African government.
   Meanwhile, search continues in the Indian Ocean for other
evidence in the Nov. 28, 1987, crash, including the flight data
recorder, which would include technical information on the last few
minutes of the flight. The cockpit tape, which officials said was
flooded but has been cleaned and dried, records all talk and other
noise in the cockpit.
   Eastport International of Upper Marlboro, Md., which has been
involved in deep-water recovery of wreckage of the space shuttle
Challenger as well as other air crashes, retrieved the recorder last
Friday from a depth of 14,800 feet with its $5 million ``remote
recovery vehicle'' known as Gemini 6000.
   Craig Mullen, president of the company, said in a telephone
interview that the plane ``looks like it went in intact and hit at a
high rate of speed.'' He said recovered parts show evidence the
plane may have been on fire.
   The South African government has refused to release contents of a
control tower tape of conversation with the airliner pilot, who
officials earlier said reported smoke in his cockpit before the
crash. The government says contents of the conversation ``might be
misunderstood or cause embarrassment.''
   The airliner was on a flight from Taipei, Taiwan, to
Johannesburg, when it disappeared near the island of Mauritius where
it was to make a scheduled landing. Only 11 bodies were recovered
and it took two months to locate the wreckage which Mullen said is
strewn over a square mile of deep ocean. The victims included
Taiwanese, South Africans and Japanese.
   The recorder box, about a foot square, was found lying by itself
and was picked up as the Gemini was preparing to bring a larger
piece of the aircraft to the surface, Mullen said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
