<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--MountBlanc 2ndLd-Writethru a0642 01-12 0107</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Mount Blanc, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0642,0105</SECOND>
<HEAD>Europe's Highest Peak is 10.6 Feet Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to CORRECT that mountain is highest in Western Europe.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AOSTA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mount Blanc, Western Europe's highest peak,
is 10.6 feet shorter than reported on world maps, the Italian army's
Geographic Institute reported Thursday.
   The institute said that measurements made from satellites and
more sophisticated equipment showed that Mount Blanc, in the western
Alps, stands at 15,862.4 feet, compared with a previously accepted
height of 15,873 feet.
   In August, the same institute revised upward the height of Mount
Rose, the second-highest Alpine peak, to 15,312 feet, from 15,302
feet.
</TEXT>
