<FIRST>r i AM-Flight103-Claim     01-12 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight 103-Claim,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Letter Claims Responsibility for Pan Am Bomb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A letter signed ``Jewish Defence League'' that
reached the London office of the Associated Press on Thursday
claimed responsibility for the bomb planted on Pan Am Flight 103.
   There was no evidence that the letter, which used the British
spelling ``defence,'' came from the Jewish Defense League, which is
based in the United States.
   ``We think the moment has come to disclose to the world from
which side the bomb was placed which destroyed the Boeing 737 from
Panam,'' the typewritten letter said. ``We, a radical group of the
Jewish Defence League, take the responsibility for this action.''
   Mordechai Levy, a spokesman who returned a call to the JDL
offices in New York, said: ``Anyone could type a letter. It was not
us. ... Why would we or any other Jewish group bomb an American
plane?''
   Levy said his group now is called the Jewish Defense Organization.
   The plane blown up by a bomb Dec. 21 was a Boeing 747, not a 737.
The letter said the bomb was planted ``by our fighters in
Frankfurt'' to protest the U.S. decision a week earlier to open
talks with the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   It bore a Dutch stamp and a Leeuwarden postmark. Another postmark
had been added in London, apparently because it was insufficiently
addressed and required rerouting.
   ``We are firmly decided to continue our attacks on U.S.A. objects
until the American Government returns from its detestable policy,''
it said. ``We mean the condemnable friendly connections with our
enemy, the P.L.O.''
   Scotland Yard said it was investigating the claim.
   Comments by police in Leeuwarden, northern Holland, cast doubt on
the letter's authenticity.
   A police officer, speaking on condition of anonymity, said there
had been previous cases of Dutch citizens making false claims of
responsibility for violent incidents.
   Ian Geldard, an expert at the independent Institute for the Study
of Terrorism, also was skeptical. If the motive was the U.S.-PLO
connection, he said, it would have been impossible to prepare and
plant a sophisticated bomb in the few days between the U.S.
announcement and the crash.
   Geldard also said he doubted the JDL had access to the plastic
explosive Semtex, which officials say probably Semtex was used for
the bomb. All 259 people on the plane and 11 on the ground were
killed.
   The Jewish Defense League was founded in the United States in the
1960s by Rabbi Meir Kahane, who now lives in Israel and pursues a
militant anti-Arab line.
   An Iranian group also claimed responsibility for the bombing in
two telephone calls to the AP in London, calling it retaliation for
the shooting down of an Iranian passenger jet in July by a U.S.
warship in the Persian Gulf.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
