<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Angola     01-12 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Angola,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Assures Angolan Rebel Leader Of Support</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush said Thursday he intends
to support Angolan rebel leader Jonas Savimbi and, at the same time,
push for peace talks between the rebels and the Marxist government.
   Bush confirmed he had sent a letter to Savimbi last week on the
occasion of the signing of a U.S.-mediated agreement for the pullout
of Cuban troops from Angola.
   ``I want to join you in welcoming this great diplomatic
achievement, which holds out so much hope for the Angolan people,''
Bush said in the letter.
   But he added that the next step must be talks between Savimbi's
Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) and the
government of Jose Eduardo Dos Santos on ending their 14-year civil
war.
   Bush said his administration ``will accord the highest priority
to the full and prompt implementation'' of the pullout accord so
that Angolans can settle their future ``without the destructive
presence of foreign military forces.''
   Until then, ``my administration will continue all appropriate and
effective assistance to UNITA,'' the letter said.
   In brief comments at a news conference, Bush said that ``clearly
in expressing determination to support UNITA and urge at the same
time reconciliation between Dos Santos and Savimbi, I'm for that
policy and I want to try and enhance it.''
   There is strong bipartisan support in Congress for the $15
million annual appropriation to UNITA to fight the Cuban-backed
government.
</TEXT>
