<DOCNO> AP890112-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 2006EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Canada-Language     01-12 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Language,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polls Show Support For Bilingual Signs, Free Trade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most Canadians believe bilingual commercial signs
with messages in English and French should be allowed in the French
enclave of Quebec, according to a Gallup poll published Thursday.
   The poll, published in the Toronto Star, also found growing
support for the Canadian-U.S. free trade agreement.
   According to the survey, 85 percent of all Canadians and 61
percent of Quebec residents favor bilingual signs.
   Tensions have increased in the predominantly French-speaking
province since December, when the Supreme Court of Canada ruled that
a provincial law requiring all signs to be only in French was
unconstitutional.
   The provincial government overrode the ruling and issued
compromise legislation that allows bilingual signs indoors but still
requires all outdoor signs to be in French only.
   Gallup said the poll surveyed 1,021 Canadians Jan. 4-7 and has a
margin of error of 3 percent.
   Supporters of Quebec's language restrictions argue that the
province is an island of French culture in English-speaking North
America and entitled to protect its special qualities.
   Power in Quebec shifted from the English minority to the French,
which make up 81 percent of the population, during the 1970s, a
tumultuous decade of separatist sentiment that subsided when voters
rejected a sovereignty referendum in 1980.
   The law requiring all commercial signs to be in French was passed
in 1977.
   The Globe and Mail, which calls itself Canada's national
newspaper, said in an editorial Thursday that Quebec Premier Robert
Bourassa ``has received, and deserves, strong criticism for his
decision on the language of commercial signs in Quebec. ... There is
a danger, however, in raising the temperature on this issue.''
   The Gallup poll also found increased support for the
Canadian-U.S. free trade agreement since the Nov. 21 election that
cleared the way for the deal.
   According to the poll, 45 percent of Canadians support the
agreement, under which all tariffs between the two nations will be
eliminated within 10 years.
   Before the election, which hinged mainly on free trade, Gallup
found that 34 percent of Canadians supported the pact. The latest
poll indicated that 29 percent oppose it, down from 41 percent
before the election.
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney's Progressive Conservative Party
won its second consecutive majority government in the election, and
he signed the trade pact with President Reagan in January 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
