<FIRST>u i AM-Korea-Corruption     01-12 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-Corruption,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chun Aide Arrested On Corruption Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors arrested a senior
government party lawmaker on corruption charges Thursday in their
investigation of alleged abuses under the authoritarian rule of
former President Chun Doo-hwan.
   Lee Hak-bong, a member of parliament from the party in power, the
Democratic Justice Party, was charged with taking bribes and with
aiding corrupt relatives of Chun while he was Chun's chief
presidential secretary.
   Lee served as a top official at government security organizations
after helping Chun seize power with military backing in 1980.
   His was the first such arrest of a government lawmaker accused of
corruption. Prosecutors in recent weeks have arrested government
officials on charges of extorting money from businesses, diverting
government funds, selling influence and forcing political donations.
   Chun has denied any personal corruption, but his relatives,
associates and former government ministers have been arrested or
convicted of dishonest practices. The former president went into
rural exile last month after apologizing for misdeeds under his rule.
   President Roh Tae-woo, once a close ally of Chun, asked Koreans
to forgive his disgraced predecessor. But the opposition says it
will not agree to consider a pardon for Chun until he appears for a
National Assembly probe.
   The opposition-controled assembly has been investigating
allegations of human rights violations and other wrongdoings under
Chun's seven-year rule, which ended in February 1988.
   Prosecutors also on Thursday questioned Kim Ju-ho, former head of
the Office of Supply, on charges of selling influence in importing
rice from the United States.
   The prosecutors spoke on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
