<DOCNO> AP890112-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 2010EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-UndergroundVaults     01-12 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Underground Vaults,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Upholds New York City's Ability to Tax Vaults</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Geraldo Rivera may have trouble finding
something in vaults, but not New York City's tax collectors.
   The state's top court Thursday upheld the city's authority to
collect taxes from the owners of underground vaults that extend
beneath public streets and sidewalks.
   Unlike Al Capone's vault, which Rivera found empty in a
nationally televised program, there's money in New York City vaults.
The city is owed an estimated $20.3 million in back taxes dating to
1962, according to the city Finance Department.
   The Court of Appeals ruled against a Manhattan property owner who
complained that he shouldn't have to pay a $250,000 tax bill on his
vault because he didn't use it.
   ``It's the biggest crime in the world,'' said lawyer Philip
Smith, owner of the $20 million building.
   There are 14,616 underground vaults in the city, said Claire
Tallarico, spokeswoman for the Finance Department. Since 1962, the
city has imposed a yearly tax of $2 per square foot on the vaults,
some of which are ``cavernous,'' she said.
   ``It's the biggest bargain for storage space in town, we think,''
Tallarico said.
   Many property owners, however, complained they didn't even know
they had the vaults until they received a tax bill.
   Smith said the basement of his building is used to store
furniture for an Ethan Allen franchise, but the vault has been
unoccupied since it was flooded in the 1960s.
   The finance department said the vault is taxable unless it is
rendered unusable by a wire mesh screen or sheetrock partition with
an opening no larger than three feet by three feet.
   All seven Court of Appeals judges said Smith could be taxed
because he didn't follow these rules.
   Smith said the entrance to his vault is barricaded by
cinderblocks.
   ``How can they say a chicken-wire fence is more inaccessible than
cinderblocks?'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
