<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Mideast     01-12 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Mideast,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mubarak Chides Shamir; Newspaper Reports New Peace Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hosni Mubarak on Thursday urged
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir of Israel to agree to an international
Middle East peace conference.
   In a related development, a state-run newspaper in the United
Arab Emirates said Shamir has proposed a peace conference that would
include the superpowers and Palestinian representatives elected from
the Israeli-occupied lands.
   A Shamir spokesman denied the report and said Shamir still is
working on a new peace proposal.
   Mubarak reiterated on Thursday that he will not visit Israel
unless that country agrees to an international peace conference on
the Palestinian conflict.
   ``All countries of the world except Israel'' have accepted such a
conference as the proper framework for Arab-Israeli peace talks,
Mubarak said. A conference, under U.N. auspices, would bring
together concerned parties and the five permanent members of the
U.N. Security Council.
   Egypt and the Palestine Liberation Organization say the
conference should lead to direct Arab-Israeli talks.
   Mubarak told reporters he plans to discuss peace and other
regional problems when he visits Washington after President-elect
George Bush takes office on Jan. 20.
   Asked about prospects of his visiting Israel, Mubarak replied:
   ``I cannot visit Israel particularly after Mr. Shamir announced
he will not make territorial concessions and does not accept an
international peace conference. He is not giving something in return
or (paying) a price for my visit, and we will not go there to have
tea and coffee or to have a good time.''
   Shamir has refused to relinquish any Arab territory Israeli
forces now occupy: the West Bank, the Gaza Strip and the Golan
Heights, all seized in the 1967 Middle East war.
   Egypt and Israel signed the Camp David accord in 1978 and
established diplomatic relations, but Mubarak has not visited Israel
since taking office in 1981.
   In Abu Dhabi, the state-run newspaper Al-Ittihad said a new plan
by Shamir was presented to U.S. Secretary of State George Shultz and
to his Soviet counterpart, Eduard Shevardnadze on Sunday in Paris.
   Al-Ittihad attributed the report to an unidentified source in
Washington that it described as ``close to the U.S. administration.''
   The paper said the plan proposed ``a Middle East peace conference
hosted by the superpowers'' and talks between Israel and
``Palestinians to be elected in the occupied territories.''
   At the end of a three-year autonomy _ two years less than the
autonomy under the Camp David accords _ Shamir proposed a
confederation with Jordan and the Palestinians and allowing
Palestinians and Jordan an access to the sea, it said.
   Under the plan, Israel, Palestine and Jordan would be linked
economically in a way similar to that of the European Economic
Community and a joint authority should be created to explore water
and soil, Al-Ittihad said.
   The Camp David accords were a tripartite framework for an overall
Arab-Israeli settlement that was signed by the United States, Egypt
and Israel in 1978. It was rejected by other Arab nations.
   Shamir spokesman Yosi Achimeir said the Al-Ittihad report was
``just speculation. Nothing formal has been released, although the
prime minister is considering many plans based on Camp David.
   Foreign Minister Moshe Arens, not Shamir, was in Paris on Sunday
to meet with Shultz.
   ``No peace plan was presented by Mr. Arens in Paris. Shamir is
now working on a plan to be presented to President Bush in March,
but nothing has been completed yet,'' Achimeir said.
   Achimeir said the plan would contain ``no peace conference, but
there could be a ceremonial opening by the superpowers or an
initiative by the secretary-general of the United Nations.''
</TEXT>
