<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Enclave     01-12 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Enclave,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Presidium Gives Disputed Region Special Status</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government gave special status Thursday to
Nagorno-Karabakh, a disputed region with a predominantly Armenian
population, but kept it within the republic of Azerbaijan, Tass
reported.
   The decision by the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet represented
another attempt by Moscow to ease tension over the area, focus of a
struggle between ethnic Armenians and Azerbaijanis that has led to
60 deaths in the past year.
   About 200,000 refugees have left Nagorno-Karabakh for Armenia,
which wants to annex it. The region is an enclave in Azerbaijan, to
which it was assigned in 1923.
   Martial law and curfews were imposed in many parts of the two
Caucasus republics two months ago to quell ethnic violence.
   Tass said Thursday's decision was made at a meeting of the
Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, the government's highest executive
body, convened by President Mikhail S. Gorbachev to consider
``urgent'' issues.
   Unconfirmed reports had circulated for more than a month that the
Kremlin would transfer Nagorno-Karabakh to the Russian federation,
largest of the 15 Soviet republics, in an effort to end the dispute.
   A Tass statement Thursday, however, made clear it would remain
within Azerbaijan.
   The official news agency said the Presidium ``found it expedient
to temporarily introduce in the Nagorno-Karabakh autonomous region a
special form of administration, with Nagorno-Karabakh retaining its
status as an autonomous region incorporated in Azerbaijan.''
   It did not describe the special administration, but said a decree
would be published later.
   Gorbachev said last week a special commission of the Communist
Party Politburo would meet Wednesday to consider the ethnic dispute,
but there was no word that such a meeting had occurred.
   Tass said the party chiefs of the two republics met in Moscow on
Wednesday and agreed to try to persuade people who fled ethnic
violence to return home.
   Armenian residents of Nagorno-Karabakh began agitating in
February for annexation by Armenia, and huge demonstrations for the
cause were held in Yerevan, the Armenian capital, and other cities
of the southern republic.
   In July, the Presidium rejected the annexation requests but
announced a program of economic and other aid for Nagorno-Karabakh.
</TEXT>
