<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Namibia     01-12 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Namibia,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Official: Time Running Out To Approve Namibia Peacekeepers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Namibia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time is running out for the Security
Council to approve a peacekeeping force that would be ready by the
April 1 deadline to oversee Namibia's move to independence, a U.N.
official said Thursday.
   The Security Council has been deadlocked for weeks over demands
by its five permanent members that the cost of the force be cut.
Also, the non-aligned members insist that the maximum force of 7,500
peacekeepers be dispatched.
   Council members continued to consult this week in an effort to
reach a compromise, said U.N. spokesman Francois Giuliani.
   Plans for the Namibia force call for up to 7,500 peacekeepers,
2,000 civilian administrators and 360 police to supervise Namibia's
transition to independence after 74 years of South African rule.
   U.N. officials have estimated a peacekeeping mission that large
would cost $600 million to $800 million, more than the combined cost
of last year's peacekeeping activities.
   The five permanent members of the Security Council _ the United
States, Soviet Union, Britain, France and China _ collectively are
assessed 57 percent of the cost of peacekeeping operations.
   They have agreed that Namibia's operations should not top $450
million. They also have been studying a U.S. proposal to cut the
military component of the force.
   Undersecretary-General Martti Ahtisaari, the secretary-general's
special representative for Namibia, said Thursday that ``time is
running out'' for the council to reach agreement.
   Even if an agreement were reached by the end of the week, it
would take at least until the end of February before U.N. committees
could develop and approve budgets for the Namibia force, he said.
   Until the budgets are in, his office cannot complete plans for
ordering equipment, supplies and transportation for the force,
Ahtisaari said.
   The U.N.'s one-year plan for Namibia's transition to independence
is to begin April 1. Elections are to be held Nov. 1 for a
constituent assembly, which is to draft a constitution and form a
parliament.
   The non-aligned members of the Security Council are Ethiopia,
Colombia, Malaysia, Algeria, Nepal, Senegal and Yugoslavia. The
other non-permanent members of the council are Canada, Finland and
Brazil.
   Namibia's independence was part of a peace agreement that also
calls for the withdrawal of Cuban forces from Angola. Cuba sent
forces into Angola in July 1975 to support forces fighting
guerrillas backed by the United States and South Africa. Cuba has
begun withdrawing troops.
</TEXT>
