<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Soviets 1stLd-Writethru a0633 01-12 0718</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Soviets, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0633,0737</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dribble Diplomacy: A Sign of Improving Ties Between U.S.S.R, Israel</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERT 3 grafs after 5th, `Even Prime...' UPDATING with additional
reaction. Pick up 6th pvs, `The late...' with minor editing to trim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel and the Soviet Union traded shots on the
basketball court Thursday night in a game followed so intently in
Israel that radio appeals were made to taxi and bus drivers not to
mix driving and listening.
   The dribble diplomacy was the latest sign of improving relations
between America's closest Middle East ally and the Soviet Union, the
main political and military backer of Israel's Arab enemies.
   ``The fact that our team is there and playing is quite an
encouraging step,'' said Foreign Ministry Deputy Spokesman Daniel
Scheck.
   The viewing audience was huge for the first live broadcast from
Moscow in which underdog Tel Aviv Maccabi beat the Red Army's CSKA
team 97-92. In a nation of only 4.2 million, more than 2 million
people were watching at the last basket, according to TV managing
director Chaim Yavin.
   Even Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, not a noted sports
enthusiast, took time out to watch the game on a small portable set
in his office.
   After the victory fans took to the streets shouting ``We won, we
won!,''and bus and taxi drivers beeped their horns.
   ``It's a great victory for Maccabi Tel Aviv in the heart of
Moscow, in the eyes of the world,'' Education Minister Yitzhak Navon
told the national Itim news agency.
   Over 1,000 Maccabi fans applied to go to the Soviet Union, but
only about a dozen were granted visas.
   The late afternoon starting time cut rush-hour traffic to a
trickle in major cities as workers raced home early to see the game.
Jerusalem's central Mahane Yehuda market closed three hours ahead of
schedule.
   Some Israelis gathered in pizzerias and cafes to watch, cheering
wildly at each basket. Nut stands and candy stores reported a
booming business as sports fans bought up nibbles for the big game.
   Shaul Yefan, director of the electric company, appealed to
viewers not to use water heaters and ovens during the game. He said
power blackouts might occur because so many TV sets were on at the
same time.
   In basketball-crazy Israel, the sports interest for Israel's
first Moscow game since 1973 was a major factor. But there was also
an unmistakable sense of drama over the changing political climate.
   Israel TV opened its broadcast with a shot of the onion-domed
Kremlin and a voice-over commentary by correspondent Yoram Arbel who
said ``history is being made.''
   Israel and the Soviet Union have been without diplomatic
relations since the 1967 Middle East war, when the Kremlin broke
ties in protest of Israel seizure of Arab territory.
   The climate has warmed markedly since the Soviets sent a
diplomatic delegation to take up residence in July 1987.
   Part of the reason for the improved Soviet image is attributed to
steadily building contacts at the non-official level, including the
visit of Soviet musicians, a leading poet and ordinary Soviet
tourists. Cultural visits are particularly popular, not leastly
because Israel has 250,000 immigrants from the Soviet Union.
   Foreign Minister Moshe Arens said the rapprochement is motivated
by the Soviet desire to play a role in any Middle East peace
settlement and the necessity to convince Israel such a role can be
constructive.
   Israel had conditioned Soviet participation on enlarged Jewish
emigration and freedom of Jewish cultural life in the Soviet Union
as well as restoration of full diplomatic ties.
   ``Whatever hesitations we may have had in the past, they were
concerned with the fact that many Jews who pursued Zionist activity
have been imprisoned'' and emigration was restricted, Arens said
Tuesday upon return from Paris, where he met with Soviet Foreign
Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze.
   ``Most of that has disappeared,'' Arens acknowledged.
   The two nations appeared to be moving steadily _ if slowly _
toward renewal of diplomatic relations.
   Shevardnadze announced Sunday the Soviet decision to upgrade the
status of an Israeli delegation in Moscow and include political
matters in its range of activities.
   Israeli Foreign Ministry officials say this means Israel's envoys
and their Soviet counterparts in Tel Aviv will turn into de facto
permanent diplomatic missions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
