<FIRST>r i AM-UNDebt 1stLd-Writethru   01-12 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN Debt, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0661,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>United States is Main Offender in U.N. Debt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 5th, `Officials at...' to UPDATE with
comptroller comment. Pick up 6th pvs, `Washington was...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Nations ended 1988 more than
$750 million in the red mainly because the United States withheld
its dues during the Reagan administration, according to figures
obtained Thursday.
   The United States, the largest U.N. contributor, owed $401.7
million, according to an advance copy of the 1988 annual financial
figures obtained by The Associated Press. That figure equals 53.5
percent of the total arrears of the regular and peacekeeping
budgets, according to the advance copy.
   The regular budget ended the year $394.9 million in the red, more
than $40 million over the arrears at the end of 1987. Peacekeeping
budgets ended 1988 $355.2 million in arrears.
   The United States had said it was withholding funds to protest
anti-U.S. bias in the world body and inefficient administration.
President Reagan said in September he was satisfied with the
progress of reforms at the United Nations and ordered the State
Department to devise a schedule for repaying all U.S. arrears.
   Officials at the New York-based world body said the funding
crunch had jeopardized the U.N. payroll and could undermine U.N.
efforts to field international peacekeeping troops, which won the
1988 Nobel Peace Prize.
   ``We've spotted land, but are not yet ashore,'' said U.N.
Comptroller Luis M. Gomez. ``Clearly, to successfully take on the
many tasks now being given us by the world community, member states
are going to have to start paying in full and on time, and these
arrears must be reduced.''
   Washington was responsible for $307.6 million, or about 77
percent of the arrears in the regular budget. The Soviet Union owed
$9 million, or 2 percent of the regular arrears.
   Moscow was responsible for $172.1 million, nearly half the
arrears in peacekeeping. The United States was responsible for $94.1
million, or 26 percent.
   Eighty-six of the 159 member nations paid all their dues through
the end of 1988, a better showing than in the past. At the end of
1987, only 75 nations were paid up.
   Brazil, a nation with its own serious financial troubles,
pleasantly surprised the world body in December by paying all its
dues, $17.9 million, said Martti Ahtasaari, the U.N.
undersecretary-general in charge of administration.
   The total regular U.N. budget is about $880 million, of which the
United States is assessed one-fourth and the Soviet Union 11.8
percent.
   In addition to the United States and the Soviet Union, 10 other
nations owe more than $1 million to the regular budget: South
Africa, $33.9 million; Iran, $7.9 million; Argentina, $5.2 million;
Poland, $4.3 million; Romania, $4 million; Yugoslavia, $3.5 million;
Israel, $3.1 million; Libya, $2.8 million; Peru, $1.4 million; and
Hungary, $1.2 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890112-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 1853EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Iran-Contra 3rdLd-Writethru a0737 01-12 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Contra, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0737,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Sees No Problems in Remaining Charges Against North</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs lead graf to clarify</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Independent counsel Lawrence Walsh said
Thursday he believes former presidential aide Oliver L. North can be
tried on cover-up charges without raising the national security
concerns which undermined conspiracy and theft counts.
   ``The government's case no longer depends on proving that the
proceeds of the Iranian arms sales constituted government property,
or that by diverting those proceeds to the Contras, North embezzled
them,'' Walsh said in a court filing.
   Walsh outlined the prosecution's legal theory of the case against
North in the event the conspiracy and theft charges against the
fired National Security Council aide are dropped, as expected.
   North's possible defenses to the charges, which focus largely on
the coverup of various aspects of the Iran-Contra affair, ``are
narrowly circumscribed,'' Walsh said in the court filing.
   ``The classified information problems affecting'' the conspiracy
and theft counts ``should no longer be at issue,'' Walsh said.
   Walsh's view differs sharply with that of North's attorney,
Brendan Sullivan. Last Thursday, Sullivan said that ``classified
information pervades the remaining charges as well.''
   The independent counsel said the government will prove that North
aided the Contras and then misrepresented his activities'' to
Congress in 1985, obstructed a congressional inquiry into his
activities a year later and then lied to the attorney general about
details of the diversion of money to the Contras.
   Walsh also said the government need not establish North's motives
for committing acts such as destroying and altering documents and
misrepresenting his activities to Congress.
   Walsh said North may attempt to bring classified information into
the case by saying that he had covered up because superiors directed
him to or because everything he did was ``authorized and perfectly
legal.'' In neither approach should North be permitted to bring up
classified information, said Walsh.
   On Monday, however, U.S. District Judge Gerhard Gesell said that
while motive does not determine guilt or innocence under the law,
North does have the right to show that the activities he sought to
cover up were not illegal. North might then seek to bring in some of
the same classified information that led to Walsh abandoning the
conspiracy and theft charges.
   ``No doubt North's motives were mixed,'' said Walsh. ``To cover
up activities in support of the Contras which the Congress might
protest, to cover up prior lies, to avoid political embarrassment to
the administration, or to avoid charges of illegality.''
   However, Walsh added, ``the jury will not be asked to decide this
case on the basis of North's motives, or the legality of the conduct
he was covering up.''
   The independent counsel last week gave up his pursuit of the
conspiracy and theft of government property charges against North
because the Reagan administration refused to declassify portions of
documents U.S. District Judge Gerhard Gesell said were needed to
conduct a fair trial.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh and Walsh filed declarations and
a memorandum under seal with Gesell that outlined the national
security problem. Gesell may dismiss the two counts on Friday.
   Nine of the 12 counts that would remain focus on North's
allegedly concealing from Congress and former Attorney General Edwin
Meese III his efforts on behalf of the Contras.
   In addition, North is accused of illegally accepting a $13,800
security system at his home from co-defendant Richard Secord,
converting to his own use at least $4,300 in traveler's checks from
Contra leader Adolfo Calero and conspiring to defraud the Treasury
of tax revenue in connection with charitable contributions
supporting the Contras.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
