<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Psacharopoulos     01-12 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Psacharopoulos,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nikos Psacharapoulos, Theater Director, Dies In Virgin Islands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILLIAMSTOWN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nikos Psacharopoulos, longtime
director of the Williamstown Theatre Festival, one of the nation's
leading summer theaters, died Thursday in the Virgin Islands. He was
60.
   During his 34-year tenure, the Williamstown festival grew from a
sleepy summer theater to a national showcase that featured such
stars as Christopher Reeve, Blythe Danner, Frank Langella,
Christopher Walken and Karen Allen.
   Psacharapoulos, who died of colon cancer while vacationing, was
engaged to be married to actress Jean Hackett of New York City. They
had planned an April wedding.
   Born in Athens, Psacharopoulos came to the United States at age
17 to enter Oberlin College, where he studied art history. After
earning a master's degree at the Yale School of Drama, he taught
drama at Amherst College for a year and then became associate
artistic director of the Williamstown festival in 1955.
   He was named artistic-executive director the following year.
   Over the years he directed 97 shows in Williamstown and several
on Broadway and for the New York City Opera. His credits included
one of Broadway's first musicals with an all-black cast,
``Tambourines to Glory.''
   In 1988, he directed three productions: ``A Street Car Named
Desire'' on Broadway, ``Sweet Bird of Youth'' at the Royal Alexandra
Theatre in Toronto, Canada, and ``The Legend of Oedipus'' in
Williamstown.
</TEXT>
