<FIRST>r a AM-Dollar-Gold     01-12 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls as Central Banks Intervene; Gold Slips</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Longer version on financial wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Central banks fought off speculators and managed
to knock the dollar slightly lower in wild foreign-exchange trading
on Wednesday.
   Traders said there was concerted dollar-selling by the Federal
Reserve and the central banks of West Germany, Switzerland, Britain,
Belgium, Austria, Canada, Italy, the Netherlands and perhaps others.
   ``It was very hectic. The market just sort of twisted and
turned,'' said Jeff Mondschein, vice president and manager of
foreign-exchange trading at Continental Bank in Chicago.
   High U.S. interest rates have made the dollar attractive to
global investors, while the West German mark has been under heavy
selling pressure because of low German interest rates.
   Central banks have been fighting the trend because of fears that
currencies are becoming misaligned and could cause economic damage.
Among other things, a strong dollar would hurt progress in reducing
the huge U.S. trade deficit.
   The dollar reached a three-month high of 1.84 marks in European
trading before succumbing to central-bank intervention and finished
the day in New York between 1.82 marks and 1.83 marks.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 1.25 Japanese yen to a closing 126.95 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 126.15 yen. In New York, the dollar fell to
125.78 yen from 126.33 Tuesday.
   The dollar fell against the British pound as well. Sterling
fetched $1.7815, compared with $1.7643 Tuesday. In New York,
sterling rose to $1.7866 from $1.7649.
   Gold prices fell slightly. In Hong Kong, where the day's trading
begins, gold fell $2.70 a troy ounce to close at a bid price of
$404.48 an ounce.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $403.50 a troy ounce,
compared with $404.75 bid late Tuesday. In Zurich, Switzerland, gold
closed at $403.30 an ounce, up from $405.10.
</TEXT>
