<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-IsraelGame 1stLd-Writethru a0705 01-12 0775</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Israel Game, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0705,0797</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Jews Cheer Israeli Team to Victory Over Soviet Army</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 4th graf, `Ken Barlow...' with two grafs to CORRECT that
four players American-born, not Americans, and ADD Israeli reaction. Pick
up 5th pvs, `Maccabi captain...' with minor editing to trim; ADDS 3 grafs
background at end. No home town available for Mercer</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel-Soviets, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Soviet Jews, given a rare chance by
improved relations to wave the Israeli flag and proclaim their
heritage, rocked a basketball stadium with cheers Thursday as
Maccabi of Tel Aviv edged the Soviet Army 97-92.
   ``This is joy, this is happiness,'' exulted Merab
Detrokalashuvili, a 38-year-old Jew from the Soviet Georgian
republic, hugging and kissing others in a crush of Jews at the army
sports complex on Moscow's west side.
   ``The Jewish nation is one nation,'' he said, clutching a
blue-and-white Israeli flag that he brought to the game.
   Ken Barlow, one of four American-born black players on the
Israeli basketball team, put the game away for Maccabi with a short
jumper from the left side in the final seconds.
   In Israel, a nation of 4.2 million people, more than 2 million
were watching at the last basket, according to TV managing director
Chaim Yavin in Jerusalem. Fans rushed outside shouting ``We won, we
won!,''and bus and taxi drivers beeped their horns.
   Maccabi captain Doron Jamshi and coach Zvi Sherf stressed that no
incidents occurred on the court and none was evident in the stands
or outside.
   Jamshi said the teams know and respect each other because they
have played each other often in neutral settings.
   ``Relations are very good,'' he said. ``It's like a little war.
We won the war and go home happy.''
   The team's appearance in Moscow for a European Championship Cup
game was the first by an Israeli basketball team in 15 years.
   The Israelis said they tried to keep out politics, but it proved
impossible because of the recent history of poor Israeli-Soviet
relations. ``It was not a regular game for us,'' Sherf said in a
post-game interview. ``The players were very, very excited before
and during the game.''
   The Soviet champions will travel to Israel for a return game in
March.
   The Soviet Union broke diplomatic relations with Israel after the
Middle East War of 1967. In recent years, under President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, it slowly has been seeking a thaw with Israel.
   The last Israeli basketball team to appear in the Soviet Union,
participants in the University Games, was jeered as it strode into
Lenin Stadium in August 1973.
   Only the Soviet flag was hung above the central scoreboard
Thursday.
   Maccabis owner Shimon Mizrahi said Soviet officials decided not
to display an Israeli flag but such a display was not mandatory
because the game was not between two national teams.
   Fans of the Israeli team chanted ``Maccabi, Maccabi!'' and waved
a dozen blue-and-white banners emblazoned with the Star of David.
   At one point, several broke into an old Israeli folk song,
``We've Brought Peace to You.''
   Cheers got louder, and Maccabi fans jumped from their seats as
Maccabi broke out to a 10-point lead as the game was reaching
midpoint and then made it 71-51 with about 12 minutes left.
   The Soviets came storming back, led by guard Vladimir Gorin and
forward Sergei Tarakanov.
   The roar grew deafening when Tarakanov brought the Soviets to
93-89, with a jump shot from the free throw circle and then scored
two free throws to make it 95-91 with about a minute left.
   Barlow wrapped it up for the Israelis with his jumper shot,
however.
   Soviet Jews said they had no trouble buying tickets.
Detrokalashuvili, who said he plans to join his parents, sister and
brother in Israeli in April, bought 20 tickets and distributed them
to friends who came up from Georgia for the game.
   Four U.S.-born blacks play for Maccabi. Willie Sims, a black
American Jew from New York City, is an Israeli citizen who has been
on the team for 12 years. He came to Israel as a college student to
play in the Maccabiah Games, an Olympic-type event for Jews across
the world.
   Lavonne Mercer, from Georgia, has been on the team about eight
years and became an Israeli citizen two years ago. Kevin Magee, born
in Gary, Ind., and a team member for five years, and Barlow, from
Indianapolis, are the professional team's two foreign players.
   With the exception of Sims, who was born Jewish, the Americans
were recruited for Maccabi out of college and are paid more than
Israeli players.
</TEXT>
