<FIRST>u i AM-East-WestTalks     01-12 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East-West Talks,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greece-Turkey Dispute Hampers Arms Pact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO and Warsaw Pact nations on Thursday
broke off discussions on arms control talks because of a lingering
dispute between Greece and Turkey, Western diplomats said.
   Western diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said East
and West negotiators agreed to meet again on Friday.
   The 16 NATO nations, meanwhile, will continue to search for a way
to break the impasse between Greece and Turkey over the eastern
Mediterranean port of Mersin, the diplomats said.
   Greece wants the port included in the new talks on cutting
conventional forces across Europe because it alleges the port is a
base for shipping arms to northern Cyprus, which is controlled by
Turkey.
   Turkey insists the port be excluded, since it is close to Syria,
which is not included in the new arms talks or in the 35-nation
Helsinki process on security and human rights.
   The Soviet Union agreed to exclude the port and the nearby U.S.
air base of Incirlik from the East-West arms talks. Turkey fears
reopening the issue of Mersin also could change Moscow's mind over
the air base, which it long sought to include in the new talks.
   The dispute threatens to block new East-West agreements on arms
control talks and a landmark human rights accord.
   The arms talks are designed to reduce Warsaw Pact and NATO
troops, tanks and airborne forces from the Atlantic to the Ural
mountains deep inside the Soviet Union.
   They could begin as early as March, according to diplomats from
NATO and Warsaw Pact nations.
   But if the Greek-Turkish dispute is not solved by the end of this
week, the new East-West arms talks cannot be set before the Reagan
administration leaves office, diplomats say.
   The overall agreement at the 35-nation Helsinki review conference
on security and human rights in Europe also would be at risk.
   The mandate for the new arms control talks is supposed to be part
of the final document agreed on by the 35 nations at the conference,
which began work in November 1986.
   A draft of the final document was presented last week, a day
before the United States and Britain removed a major obstacle by
announcing they are willing to attend a 1991 human rights meeting in
Moscow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
