<FIRST>r w AM-US-Germany     01-12 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Germany,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>West German Warns Against US Imports of Cash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German Finance Minister Gerhard
Stoltenberg on Thursday urged the incoming Bush administration to
make reducing the U.S. budget deficit a top priority, saying more
reductions are needed to take pressure off international financial
markets.
   Stoltenberg said the United States is still importing large sums
of foreign capital to finance its large twin trade and federal
budget deficits.
   This flow of foreign capital, estimated at around $10 billion a
month, means less money going into productive investments in
countries outside the United States, Stoltenberg said in a speech.
   ``Further reductions in the U.S. federal deficit would take a lot
of pressure off the international capital markets and help stabilize
interest rates around the world,'' Stoltenberg said.
   Stoltenberg was asked during a question period following the
speech how fast Congress and the Bush administration need to act on
the deficit problem in order to reassure jittery world financial
markets.
   He said he realized ``it takes some time'' to work out
governmental problems in the United States, ``but I hope it will be
a solution this year and not only in the last months as it was in
1987.''
   In 1987, Congress and the Reagan administration forged an
agreement in December to lower the federal deficit following
negotiations which had been prompted by the collapse of the stock
market in October.
   Stoltenberg met earlier in the day with Treasury Secretary
Nicholas Brady. He met with Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan
on Wednesday and is scheduled to meet Friday with Richard Darman,
nominated by Bush as his budget director.
   Treasury Department spokesman Art Siddon said Brady and
Stoltenberg exchanged ``views on a wide range of issues that will
confront the new administration.''
   Officials said no decisions were reached on a proposed meeting
between the United States and its top economic allies, West Germany,
Japan, Britain, France, Canada and Italy.
   Brady is expected to attend such a meeting to assure U.S. allies
the new administration plans to pursue Reagan administration
policies which have sought to stabilize the value of the U.S. dollar
relative to other currencies.
   In his speech, Stoltenberg said President-elect George Bush has
made plain that he will continue to try to reduce the federal
government deficit. He said Americans see that as the key to making
more of their savings available for investment, to keeping prices
stable and interest rates low and to reducing the need to get money
from abroad.
   ``The very low savings ratio in the U.S. and the effect of the
budget and trade deficit necessitate a very high level of capital
imports, which in the long run would cause serious problems,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
