<FIRST>r i AM-Angola     01-12 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Angola,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angolans Concerned over Gaps in Truce Monitoring Area</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN LINNEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUEDAS DA RUACANA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Angolan who monitors a truce
line on the Namibian border said Thursday there is an unpatrolled
gap in the area to be checked for violations of a cease-fire between
Angolan and South African forces.
   Five months after the shooting stopped, three of a scheduled 11
posts have not yet been established along a 600-mile stretch from
Ruacana east to Zambia, said Maj. Valeriano Martinho, second in
command of the Angolan contingent on the joint commission.
   Martinho said 11 posts were to have been set up by the end of
September, after the truce was declared Aug. 8. He spoke to
reporters at his camp near the Ruacana control point 570 miles south
of Luanda, capital of Angola.
   He said the unpatrolled sector runs from the town of Cuangar
about 315 miles east to the Zambian frontier and includes the
Caprivi strip.
   ``The presence of UNITA forces along the Angolan border is
obstructing the establishment of the three final posts,'' he said.
``We believe they (South Africans) are continuing to support UNITA
from that area.''
   Asked whether Angola had proof, he replied: ``No. We have
suspicions.''
   Guerrillas of UNITA, the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola, which the United States supports, have
fought Angola's Marxist government since independence from Portugal
in 1975. South African troops have operated in southern Angola,
helping UNITA and pursuing Namibian guerrillas of the South-West
Africa People's Organization.
   South Africa said Dec. 22 it had halted aid to UNITA. Neither
UNITA nor SWAPO is involved in the truce or in the U.S.-mediated
peace plan for southern Africa signed by South Africa, Angola and
Cuba.
   Angola has protested the failure to establish the three remaining
posts, Martinho said, at sessions of the joint monitoring commission
that includes six members each from Angola, Cuba and six South
Africa.
   The commission has met each weekday on the border about a mile
from the Angolan camp. South Africa's camp is just across the
frontier in South-West Africa, or Namibia.
   South Africa captured the territory from Germany in World War I
and has governed it since _ for the past 22 years in defiance of the
United Nations.
   Under the three-way agreement signed Dec. 22, Cuba's 50,000
soldiers are to leave Angola by mid-1991 and Namibia is to become
independent after U.N.-supervised election.
   Under the cease-fire agreement, no significant movement of troops
is permitted on either side of the border.
   Both Martinho and 1st Lt. Nelson Coelho wore the orange armbands
of the joint commission and carried sidearms. They talked with
reporters in the shade of thorn trees in the camp next to the
Ruacana dam on the Cunene River, which forms part of the border.
   Martinho said daily patrols by 22 Angolans and 22 South African
soldiers have not found significant violations of the cease-fire.
   He said the Cubans, who are expected to have withdrawn 3,000
troops from Angola by Sunday, do not take part in truce patrols.
   Few people live in the area. A helicopter flight from the
Cuban-built airstrip at Cahama south to Ruacana Falls revealed
isolated huts, patches of corn and small herds of goats and cattle.
</TEXT>
