<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 2014EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Fauntroy-Probe 1stld-writethru a0736 01-12 0682</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fauntroy-Probe, 1st ld-writethru, a0736,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: To show FBI tried to contact staffer, adds 2 new grafs after
9th graf previous ``It should be noted''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI is investigating whether District of
Columbia Del. Walter Fauntroy broke federal laws by employing the
son of a congressional colleague at a time that records show the son
had sworn he was living in Illinois, a Justice Department offical
said Thursday.
   Fauntroy, Thomas John Savage and Rep. Gus Savage, D-Ill., are
subjects of a preliminary investigation into Fauntroy's employment
of the younger Savage, who said he was living in Chicago _ and
running for the Illinois Legislature _ at the same time he was on
Fauntroy's payroll, the official said.
   Department policy prohibited him from commenting further, said
the official, who spoke only on condition he not be named.
   In a related development, Rep. Julian Dixon, D-Calif., who chairs
the House ethics committee, also has written Fauntroy, who is the
district's non-voting member of Congress, asking for an explanation
of Savage's employment, according to a congressional source.
   Thomas Savage earned $21,398 while on Fauntroy's payroll from
September 1987 through June 1988.
   The Justice Department official said the FBI also is looking into
any connection between Fauntroy's employment of the younger Savage
and Rep. Savage's employment of Lezli Baskerville, a former Fauntroy
aide. A month before Fauntroy hired Savage, Ms. Baskerville was
ousted from a job Savage gave her on the House Public Works and
Transportation Committee.
   After leaving the Public Works panel, Ms. Baskerville returned to
Fauntroy's payroll, where she was directed to do legislative work on
behalf of the National Black Leadership Roundtable, a private group
of black businessmen that Fauntroy chairs, according to a memo
provided by Fauntroy to his staff.
   Fauntroy, in a statement released Thursday, said, ``On the advice
of counsel for the United States House of Representatives, while I
have nothing to hide, I have nothing to say.''
   ``It should be noted that no one on my staff has been subpoenaed
by any law enforcement authorities, nor has anyone on my staff even
talked to any law enforcement authorities,'' he added.
   However, the FBI officials investigating the matter do not have
subpoena powers, according to sources familiar with the probe.
   In addition, congressional sources and others familiar with the
investigation said Johnny Barnes, Fauntroy's staff director, refused
to meet with FBI agents who attempted to question him. Barnes
refused to comment on the matter when telephoned by a reporter.
   The federal investigation began last month after The Associated
Press reported Savage was on Fauntroy's payroll although he had
submitted a sworn affidavit to Illinois elections officials stating
he had met state requirements by living continuously for two years
in the state legislative district he sought to represent. That
period covered the time he was on Fauntroy's payroll.
   Fauntroy and the younger Savage first said that he had worked on
a District of Columbia statehood bill, but Savage later conceded he
rarely worked in Fauntroy's office and did little more than stuff
envelopes while he was there.
   When contacted by telephone in Chicago Thursday, Thomas Savage
said he was unaware of the investigation. He refused further comment.
   Rep. Savage could not be reached for comment.
   Dixon's letter asked Fauntroy to explain how he had come to hire
Savage, what duties Savage performed, and whether Savage had
regularly reported to work, the congressional source reported.
   House rules require that a congressional employee must report
regularly to work.
   Dixon could not be reached for comment on his letter.
   The FBI conducts a ``preliminary investigation'' after an initial
determination that the known facts in a case warrant a more detailed
examination. Ordinarily, a report resulting from a preliminary
investigation is sent to the U.S. attorney's office for review. A
decision then is made whether to present the case to a grand jury.
   In the Fauntroy case, the preliminary investigation will
determine whether Attorney General Dick Thornburgh will seek the
appointment of a special prosecutor, the procedure required when
members of Congress are involved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890112-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 2121EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w StoltenbergSays`BadFeeling'ClearedUp     01-12 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>Stoltenberg Says `Bad Feeling' Cleared Up</SECOND>
<BYLINE>With US-Germany ^By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German Finance Minister Gerhard
Stoltenberg said Thursday that ``bad feeling'' between the United
States and West Germany over alleged Libyan construction of a
chemical weapons plant has been cleared up.
   Stoltenberg noted his government had initially rejected U.S.
allegations that a German company had played a major role in the
construction of the alleged Libyan chemical weapons plant south of
Tripoli.
   ``In recent days there has been some additional information after
the first (West German) investigation proved nothing,'' Stoltenberg
said in a question-and-answer session with reporters and officials.
   ``You can read in the papers that there is now some suspicion
that it is possible that some international trade company with a
subsidiary in Germany, and possibly also a German company with a
subsidiary,'' were involved, he said.
   Stoltenberg said some exports may have left West Germany
supposedly destined for another country, but had wound up in Libya.
   ``This is possible, but we cannot give a final judgment because
we have -- and this will be done very urgently in these days -- to
clear whether exports, if they happened this way, were against the
law,'' he said.
   Stoltenberg said it would have to be determined if the exports
included ``sensitive components which would be used for weapon
production'' or were pure civilian products not subject to embargo.
   He said it remained important for the United States to ``share
your deep concerns fully about the possible buildup of chemical
weapons especially in countries which pursue a very dangerous
international policy.''
   ``We are generally against it and we are very sensitive as you
when we look to third countries,'' Stoltenberg said.
   He noted that Secretary of State George Shultz and West German
Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher had arranged for a team of
German experts to come to Washington this week to review the
evidence which U.S. officials say proves the American case.
   ``I'm glad that by the political discussions some bad feeling
which came up for a few days could be cleared up and that we could
have this discussion now in a good atmosphere of mutual cooperation
(and) mutual responsibility,'' Stoltenber said.
   He said he hoped the cooperation would produce ``reasonable
results in our interests and the interests of the world community.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890112-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 2121EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PublisherNamed     01-12 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Publisher Named,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>Knight-Ridder Names Jinks Publisher Of San Jose Mercury News</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Larry Jinks has been named publisher of the San Jose
Mercury News, succeeding William A. Ott, who will become the
newspaper's chairman, the Knight-Ridder, Inc. announced Thursday.
   Jinks had been senior vice president for news and operations. The
appointment is effective April 1.
   ``His rich experience on both the news and business side and his
deep affection for San Jose make him the perfect choice to lead the
Mercury News into the 1990s,'' said P. Anthony Ridder, president of
the Knight-Ridder newspaper division.
   ``Bill Ott has had a long and distinguished career with
Knight-Ridder,'' said Knight-Ridder President and CEO James K.
Batten. ``He is regarded with the deepest affection and highest
esteem by all of us. We will miss his contributions to our
day-to-day operations.''
   Jinks is a former editor of the Mercury News and executive editor
of The Miami Herald.
   As senior editorial oficer for Knight-Ridder, Jinks works
directly with publishers and editors of ten of the group's larger
papers on news and editorial matters.
</TEXT>
