<DOCNO> AP890112-0205 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 2122EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Peru-USMayor     01-12 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru-US Mayor,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Linked to Death Of Jersey Mayor's Wife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New Jersey mayor's wife who died in a Dec. 1
rail crash in Peru's Andes Mountains was most likely the victim of
sabotage by a leftist guerrillas, the U.S. Embassy said Thursday.
   Anna Cucci was killed and her husband, Jersey City Mayor Anthony
Cucci, was injured Dec. 1 when the rail car they rode crashed near
Cuzco, 355 miles southeast of Lima.
   She is the fourth American known to have been killed as a result
of the Maoist Shining Path's nearly 9-year-old insurgency.
   Peruvian authorities at the time said saboteurs wedged a 10-inch
steel rod into the tracks, which caused the single car to derail and
tumble down a 250-foot sloped ravine.
   They said either guerrillas or workers supporting a Communist-led
general strike caused the accident, which also killed Doris Chacon,
the wife of Cuzco Mayor Carlos Chacon, and severely injured the
mayor.
   The embassy said Thursday that Peruvian investigators since have
reached the opinion that the guerrillas were behind the attack.
   Local officials believe Chacon was the rebels' most likely
target, the embassy said.
   The crash occurred on Cuzco's outskirts as the two couples, along
with Jersey City councilman Jaime Vazquez and five other people,
were en route on a daylong outing to the ancient Inca citadel of
Machu Picchu, 60 miles northwest of Cuzco.
   Cucci, who was in Cuzco to participate in a sister city ceremony,
returned home with his wife's body a few days after the accident. He
signed the Cuzco-Jersey City accord and vowed to help Peru any way
he could.
   More than 12,000 people have died in the Shining Path's fight to
topple Peru's elected government and install Marxist rule.
   Analysts said foreigners generally have not been targeted for
attacks by the rebels, but the foreign death toll has risen recently.
   Eight foreign tourists including two Americans were killed in
1986 when rebels bombed a train carrying passengers to Machu Picchu,
and one American and two French agricultural advisors were killed
last year by highland guerrillas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890112-0206 </DOCNO>
