<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 2124EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TracyChapman     01-12 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tracy Chapman,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Recording Industry's Newest Star Revives Singer-Songwriter Tradition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tracy Chapman seems of another time, a time when
Dylan, Odetta, Seeger and Guthrie celebrated freedom and the spirit
of man, and defied brutality and repression with their songs and
anthems.
   Chapman, whose self-titled debut album has been nominated for six
Grammys, is of this age and her songs take a hard, cold look at
poverty, racism, inequality and human relations. She is
uncompromising, tough and compassionate.
   ``I think people look at the world in many different ways and
choose to see what they like,'' she said in an interview last year
with The Washington Post. ``I think lots of people ignore some of
the harder issues, the more unpleasant things. I don't think I harp
on them.''
   Her LP opens with ``Talkin' Bout a Revolution,'' a song that
tells of ``standing in the welfare lines
   Crying at the doorsteps of those armies of salvation
   Wasting time in the unemployment lines
   Sitting around waiting for a promotion
   Poor people gonna rise up
   And get their share
   Poor people gonna rise up
   And take what's theirs.''
   Until ``Tracy Chapman'' hit record stores last April, the
24-year-old poet-singer-songwriter-folksinger was one of the Boston
area's best kept secrets. As an anthrolopolgy major at Tufts
University in Medford, Mass., she performed in coffee houses and
clubs, and was a local hit.
   The LP, with its range from folk to pop ballad to reggae,
enchanted millions more. It has sold over 4 million copies and has
been nominated for album of the year and best contemporary folk
recording. The single, ``Fast Car,'' has been nominated for best
song and record of the year, and Chapman herself is up for best new
artist and best female pop vocalist.
   ``Fast Car'' was a No. 1 hit and tells of a high school dropout
who works to supports her alcoholic father and who wants to escape
it all with her unemployed boyfriend:
   ``You got a fast car
   And I got a plan to get us out of here
   I been working at the convenience store
   Managed to save just a little bit of money
   We won't have to drive too far
   Just 'cross the border and into the city
   You and I can both get jobs
   And finally see what it means to be living.''
   Chapman's rich contralto with its melancholic underpinnings is an
instrument by itself and highly effective on ``Behind the Wall,'' a
song about a battered woman. She sings a capella of the harsh
realties of the domestic fight: ``Last night I heard the screaming -
Then a silence that chilled my soul'' _ and slams the police for
doing nothing.
   She grew up in Cleveland and has been singing since she was a
child. She was in a Connecticut boarding school when
singer-songwriters had been put out to pasture by synthesizer
philistines. Chapman didn't turn on her radio, but many of her
classmates listened to folk music and played guitar.
   In college, one of her classmates was Brian Koppelman, whose
father, Charles, is a leader in the music publishing business. This
gave her the wedge she needed to gain entry to the recording world.
   Chapman, whose musical roots can be traced to Joan Armatrading,
Carol King and Joni Mitchell, was part of a new wave of
singer-songwriters in the late 1980s, especially women such as Toni
Childs, Marti Jones, Melissa Etheridge and Michelle Shocked.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890112-0208 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 2124EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Grammy-McFerrin     01-12 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grammy-McFerrin,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Don't Worry, Be Happy' Man Earns Five Grammy Nominations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Grammys and AM-Grammys List</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bobby McFerrin, whose feel-good anthem ``Don't
Worry, Be Happy'' brought him three of his five Grammy award
nominations Thursday, is a one-man band without the hardware.
   The a cappella tune offering the advice of putting aside nagging
worries of daily life _ such as paying the rent _ is a multi-track
recording of simple lyrics accompanied by layers of sounds all made
by McFerrin.
   The vocal gymnast's nominations included best song, record and
male pop vocal performance for ``Don't Worry,'' best album for
``Simple Pleasures,'' and best male jazz vocal performance for the
song ``Brothers.''
   ``Don't Worry'' was the first a cappella song to reach No. 1 on
the Billboard charts. And it brought the widest recognition to a
voice heard on jeans commercials, in ``The Bill Cosby Show'' theme
and singing the alphabet on ``Sesame Street.''
   McFerrin, 38, left the orchestra out when he recorded ``Simple
Pleasures,'' using only his voice and other sounds such as
percussion made with his body.
   His live shows are much the same: no band, but a resourceful
entertainer who can turn the audience into part of the show.
   ``What you're hearing is me thinking aloud,'' McFerrin said in a
biography released by his label, EMI-Manhattan. His intent is to get
``a mature audience to be childlike and spontaneous.''
   Nominated six times previously, McFerrin has already taken home
five Grammys, three for best male jazz vocalist. But he finds the
title confining.
   ``To be labeled as a jazz singer is limiting,'' McFerrin said in
his biography. ``I like to think of myself as one who has simply
been infused with a lot of music.''
   McFerrin, born in New York, is the son of classical singers and
began studying music at the age of 6. The family moved to Los
Angeles in 1958.
   McFerrin formed a quartet in high school, studied music at
Sacramento State University and Cerritos College, worked as a
keyboard player with the Ice Follies, in a series of lounge bands
and as a hotel singer and pianist.
   Jazz vocalist Jon Hendricks invited him to join his group in
1979, and McFerrin made his debut album in 1982, following up by
taking part in all-star jazz tours of Europe and the United States.
   He tried his first solo concert in Ashland, Ore., in 1983, toured
solo and recorded his second album, ``The Voice,'' a live a cappella
recording. Numerous TV appearances and collaborations followed. In
1986 he recorded the solo album ``Spontaneous Inventions.''
   McFerrin lives in San Francisco with his wife, Debbie.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890112-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 2129EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     01-12 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Rain, Western Winds Turn To Rain For Southeast Quadrant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Warm, moist air riding atop freezing air near the surface brought
freezing rain, snow, sleet and rain from eastern Pennsylvania to New
England on Thursday, slickening highways and causing numerous
accidents.
   Very strong south winds accompanied the storm system, with 50-to
70-mph wind gusts reported near Grande Isle and St. Albans, Vt.,
blowing down a large radio tower and causing several power outages.
   Showers and thunderstorms developed from southern Ohio across the
Tennessee Valley to central Texas. Freezing rain was mixed with rain
and sleet over north central Texas and south central Oklahoma.
   Rainfall, heavy over the lower Mississippi and Tennessee valleys
in recent days left streams in Tennessee, Kentucky and northern
Alabama flowing near bankful, and flooded some streets in Memphis,
Tenn., during rush hour.
   Snow fell on parts of New Mexico, with a winter storm watch in
effect through Friday for the southern third of the state.
   High winds blew on the east slopes of the Rocky Mountains in
Montana, with winds gusting to near 50 mph at Livingston.
   The strong Santa Ana winds that earlier produced wind gusts as
high as 100 mph in Southern California, destroying a blimp, shutting
down an airport, and cutting power to thousands of utility customers
were subsiding, officials said.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 2
degrees at Jackson, Wyo., and Gunnison, Colo., to 89 degrees at
McAllen, Texas. The low in the nation was 22 degrees below zero at
Gunnison.
   The national weather forecast for Friday called for showers and
some thunderstorms from central and southern Texas across the lower
Mississippi Valley, Gulf Coast, Tennessee Valley and southern
Appalachians to the southern and middle Atlantic Coast. Snow will
fall on parts of southwest Texas, New Mexico and the central
Appalachians. Rain will fall on the Northern Pacific Coast, with
snow inland. Winds will be strong over the Rocky Mountain region.
   High temperatures will be in the teens and 20s for northern Utah,
southwest Wyoming and southeast Idaho; in the 20s from the upper
Mississippi Valley across the northern Great Lakes and much of New
York to northern New England; in the 30s across the Missouri Valley
and the Ohio Valley to southern New England; and in the 30s for
western Texas and Oklahoma, and southern and central Rockies.
   Coastal Southern California as well as the eastern half of the
Gulf Coast region across northwest Florida to the southern Atlantic
Coast will have highs in the 60s. Readings will warm to the 70s and
80s over the Florida Peninsula. The remainder of the nation will
generally have high temperatures in the 40s and 50s.
</TEXT>
