<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Libya 3rdLd-Writethru a0762 01-12 0729</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Libya, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0762,0751</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kohl: We Have Evidence Of German Link To Poison Gas Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 19 grafs to UPDATE with comments from finance minister,
report of chemical spill at plant. Pick up 19th pvs, `Secretary of ...'
Edits to trim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl on Thursday said
authorities seized new documents that may show West German companies
helped Libya build what Washington says is a chemical weapons plant.
   Kohl gave no details about the documents while answering
questions from reporters in a studio appearance late Thursday night
on West Germany's ZDF television network.
   The government previously maintained it had no evidence of a West
German link to the plant at Rabta, south of Tripoli, the Libyan
capital. The stunning reversal embarrassed West German authorities.
   NBC News reported Thursday that Libyan officials contacted West
German companies for clean-up help after a dangerous chemical spill
in August at the facility.
   West Germany's Imhausen-Chemie was one of those the Libyans
called for help, the network reported.
   A group of West Germans was in the United States this week to
examine evidence that Washington says indicates the Libyan plant is
a chemical weapons factory. Libya says the facility is a
pharmaceutical plant.
   ``There are new indications that will be further checked,'' Kohl
said when asked if the government had new evidence of West German
involvement in building the plant.
   ``More documents have been seized and they could give evidence, I
don't know.''
   Kohl said the documents involved chemical equipment that could be
used in many ways, but he did not elaborate. He did not say where
the papers were seized.
   He said the federal intelligence service also was involved in
investigations. Kohl said authorities were looking for evidence that
could stand in court before bringing any charges.
   A ranking official said on condition of anonymity: ``There is no
question that these allegations have caused serious damage to West
Germany's international prestige. The government is in an extremely
embarrassing and difficult position.''
   In Washington, West German Finance Minister Gerhard Stoltenberg
noted his government initially rejected U.S. allegations that a
German company played a major role in the construction of the plant.
   He said there was no more ill will between the Washington and
Bonn.
   ``I'm glad that by the political discussions some bad feeling
which came up for a few days could be cleared up and that we could
have this discussion now in a good atmosphere of mutual cooperation
(and) mutual responsibility,'' Stoltenber said.
   President Reagan has raised the possiblity of military action
against the plant.
   Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher, who told reporters a
week earlier there was no proof of West German complicity, said
Thursday: ``There are a number of indications that evidently point
in this direction.''
   Ali Treiki, Libya's U.N. ambassador, said on CBS News Thursday
that West Germans ``did help us, not only in this plant, in other
plants also.''
   In Belgium, the Justice Ministry said Jozef Gedopt, head of Cross
Link NV of Antwerp, was arrested and charged with forging shipping
documents for goods delivered to Libya.
   A spokesman for the West German Finance Ministry said Gedopt was
arrested on the basis of information provided by West Germany. He
said the information was found by investigators examining seized
records of I.B.I. Engineering, a defunct Frankfurt company linked to
the Libya plant.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz told Kohl in November the
United States had evidence of West German involvement in building
and outfitting the plant.
   U.S. officials revealed the name of one suspect company,
Imhausen-Chemie of Lahr, nearly two weeks ago, prompting the Finance
Ministry to order an investigation.
   Last week, the government said an audit of the firm's records
produced no evidence of illegal exports.
   On Wednesday, government sources confirmed that a criminal
investigation of I.B.I. Engineering's activities was under way and
said authorities had seized company documents.
   A secretary who answered the telephone at Imhausen-Chemie on
Thursday said company officials were not available for comment.
Company manager Juergen Hippenstiel-Imhausen has denied any
connection to the Libyan plant.
   Horst Koerbler, former business manager of I.B.I., declined
comment on the case. The ARD television network quoted Koerbler
earlier as saying ``many German firms'' were involved in the Libyan
project.
   Koerbler told The Associated Press he had been misquoted, but
would not elaborate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890112-0211 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 2132EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CriticBanned 1stLd-Writethru a0726 01-12 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Critic Banned, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0726,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>Theater Owner Bars Community's Only Film Critic</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 11th graf, `That's a ..., to include excerpts
from Ms. Monnett's reviews; picks up 12th graf pvs: `Paul Davis ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLYTHE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A film critic who gets $8 a review and
won't do R-rated movies has been banned from the only theater around
because her negative reviews hurt business, theater officials said.
   Cathy Monnett, a free-lancer who writes for the twice-weekly Palo
Verde Valley Times, was given a refund and asked to leave as she
watched a recent screening of ``Gorillas in the Mist'' at the
600-seat Blythe Cinema.
   ``People were staying away from the theater because of her
reviews,'' said Don Davis, the theater owner's brother and an
attorney for the Blythe Cinema, in Thursday's Los Angeles Times.
   Paul Davis, 37, co-owner of the theater, called it a matter of
economic survival, even though his movies aren't advertised in the
paper.
   But Ms. Monnett, who said most of her reviews are positive, vowed
to continue writing reviews _ even if she has to travel 90 miles to
Yuma, Ariz., to see the pictures.
   ``I'm incensed,'' Ms. Monnett said. ``By driving to Yuma I'm
telling them they can't stop me from writing reviews.''
   Ms. Monnett, 29, gets $8 for each review she submits, she said.
   The standoff has spawned angry editorials in the paper, with a
circulation of 4,500, protests outside the theater and talk of a
legal challenge.
   Ms. Monnett, who wrote similar reviews for some small newspapers
in Utah, claims the ban was unfounded based on her track record in
Blythe, a desert town of 8,400 people about 220 miles east of Los
Angeles.
   ``Of the 28 reviews I have written, 17 have been positive,'' she
said.
   ``That's a pretty good percentage,'' said David Anson, a movie
critic for Newsweek magazine. ``I don't think any of us would
survive in Blythe.''
   Some of Ms. Monet's reviews have been harsh. The movie ``Hot to
Trot, she wrote, ``Has only one thing to recommend it. It will
restore your faith in TV. Nothing on the tube is this stupid,
unimaginative, tedious and irritating.''
   Yet on the fantasy-adventure ``Willow,'' she wrote: ``It offers
sympathetic characters, a powerful conflict between good and evil,
fantastic action sequences ... and that most elusive of movie
attributes: a happy ending.''
   Of ``Police Academy V,'' she wrote: ``The comedy is sophomoric
but rarely offensive, and you'll even get a few big laughs for your
money.''
   ``Moonstruck,'' which won Cher an Oscar for Best Actress Oscar,
was ``basically a very old-fashioned movie with old-fashioned ideas
about love; but if it doesn't make a believer out of you, maybe you
should have your cynicism level checked.''
   Paul Davis considers Ms. Monnett a dilettante lacking the
credentials to review films.
   In a letter to the editor, published by the newspaper, he wrote:
``Were her distorted, negative and unfair criticism harmless, we
could perhaps ignore her, and chuck it off to a small-town mind that
dabbles in writing newspaper articles.''
   The newspaper has published several editorials denouncing the
theater's action, and urged supporters to picket the movie house.
About a dozen people recently showed up with picket signs. One read:
``Big Screen, Small Mind.''
   Meanwhile, Palo Verde Valley Times Publisher Glen Sparlin said
that since Ms. Monnett will not review R-rated movies, he is
considering using another critic to complement his family film
reviewer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890112-0212 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 2207EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hirohito-Suicide     01-12 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hirohito-Suicide,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Confirm Ritual Suicide Over Hirohito's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police confirmed on Friday that a 38-year-old man
committed ritual suicide by disembowelment, or hara-kiri, this week
after saying he wanted to follow Emperor Hirohito in death.
   A police official said previous police statements were not true
in denying that the suicide was linked to Hirohito's death.
   ``We must have received different information since then,'' he
said.
   Tadao Tanaka, 38, a chef in Fukuoka on Kyushu Island, committed
suicide in the cemetery at Junsei Temple and left a letter for his
wife saying, ``Since his majesty has departed, I cannot live any
longer,'' said an official of the Fukuoka Police Department.
   The incident was reported in the Tokyo Shimbun.
   It was the third known suicide linked to Hirohito's death at the
age of 87 last Saturday of intestinal cancer. On Saturday and
Sunday, two old soldiers hanged themselves in provincial areas,
saying in suicide notes they wanted to follow the emperor in death.
   Following the ancient tradition of the samurai warrior class,
Tanaka placed a white cloth on the ground, knelt, and slit his
abdomen with a long kitchen knife, the official reported.
   He said Tanaka's body was found Tuesday by monks at the temple.
   Ritual suicides, also known here as seppuku, are traditionally
viewed as an act of honor and are rare.
   All the police officials spoke on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
