<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina-Rebel     01-12 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina-Rebel,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Insurgent Leader Enjoys Prison Perks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of last month's
military revolt managed to keep his credit current even behind bars,
renewing an American Express card in prison so he could cover his
wife's vacation, a newspaper said Thursday.
   Col. Mohamed Ali Seineldin is enjoying more privileges than most
prison inmates _ and many Argentines in general, other sources said
on condition of anonymity.
   He has his own telephone and a private secretary to coordinate
his steady stream of visitors, and he even was allowed to spend
Christmas Eve at another prison so he could toast his fellow
insurgents, the sources said.
   Seineldin led a four-day rebellion by more than 800 soldiers that
included a siege at a military school outside Buenos Aires. The
insurgents surrendered on Dec. 5.
   On Tuesday, Seineldin telephoned the American Express office in
Buenos Aires and asked for a renewal on his credit card so he could
cover his wife's vacation to Chile, the newspaper Pagina 12 reported
Thursday.
   A company representative drove to the suburban Buenos Aires
military base where Seineldin is being held and waited while the
colonel completed the paperwork, the paper reported.
   Several hours later, approval was granted and Mrs. Seineldin
picked up the card, the paper said. Such speedy approvals are
reserved ``only for VIP clients,'' it said, noting that prisoners
usually have difficulty getting credit, let alone credit cards.
   Contacted by The Associated Press, American Express issued a
statement that said: ``We believe that the relationship between
American Express and those individuals who possess the American
Express card is confidential.
   ``This policy of privacy is applied in an equal manner with each
one of our 30 million members.''
   A spokeswoman for the army said: ``That (Seineldin) report came
from journalists. We have no comment on that.''
   Seineldin apparently hasn't been confined to a cell since his
surrender. Dozens of soldiers, officers, politicians and a few
reporters have passed by for visits.
   The visits are arranged in advance by a private secretary,
military sources say, and Seineldin has a private telephone.
   On Christmas Eve, Seineldin was flown by helicopter to the
Magdalena military prison, 62 miles south of Buenos Aires, to toast
the holiday with officers jailed there, the sources said.
   Critics of President Raul Alfonsin say the government made a deal
with rebels to end the insurrection rather than force their
unconditional surrender.
   Many loyal commanders said afterward they agreed with demands
made by rebels for an end to the prosecutions of officers for human
rights abuses during the military dictatorships of the 1970s; some
sort of public affirmation that the brutal crackdown in which at
least 8,900 Argentines were executed was legitimite; and a bigger
military budget.
</TEXT>
