<FIRST>r a AM-WindHavoc 2ndLd-Writethru a0662 01-12 0690</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wind Havoc, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0662,0705</SECOND>
<HEAD>Santa Ana Winds Destroy Nation's Largest Blimp, Overturn Trucks and
Fan Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES 6th graf ``The airport ..., to include 45 incoming flights
halted; INSERTS 4 grafs after 6th graf to UPDATE with school closing and
new quote on power outages; INSERTS 1 graf after 9th graf pvs, `At a ...,
to UPDATE with truckers beginning to move out. Picks up 10th graf prvs,
``The National...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE MANNING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Santa Ana winds gusting to 100 mph destroyed a
blimp, shut down an airport, toppled trucks, fanned a brush fire and
cut power to thousands of customers in Southern California,
officials said Thursday.
   The Airships Inc. blimp, used by the Pepsi Cola Co. to promote a
soft drink, was moored at Ontario International Airport when the
desert winds struck Wednesday night, reducing it to tatters and
leaving little more than its nose cone attached to an anchor pole.
   Its gondola lay on its side about 30 yards away and the
surrounding tarmac was littered with debris.
   The 14,617-pound airship was the nation's largest, said Pepsi
spokesman Todd McKenzie. Its last appearance was at the Jan. 2 Rose
Bowl in Pasadena.
   ``It was torn to shreds,'' said Beatrice Martinez, public
relations secretary at the Ontario airport, about 40 miles east of
Los Angeles.
   The airport closed all runways because of blowing debris
Wednesday evening, but the terminal reopened Thursday with limited
operations. Airport manager Michael DiGirolamo said many airlines
chose not to take off or land in the high winds.
   Passengers at the terminal were ``resigned to the fact they
aren't going anywhere right away,'' he said. The 10-hour closing
halted 45 incoming flights.
   Power outages disrupted lives throughout the region.
   ``Weather like this is awful for restaurants,'' said Lou Ray,
owner of the Smokehouse cafe in Fontana.
   ``When there's power outages we lose the coffee maker _
everything,'' she said. ``Everyone is sitting here with each other
and the flashlights.''
   Officials of the Mountain Empire Unified School District in San
Diego County canceled classes Thursday, saying wind made travel
hazardous for school buses.
   The Santa Ana winds _ also called ``devil winds'' _ are spun off
by high pressure over the interior of the country, picking up speed
as they move from Southern California's deserts through mountain
passes and roar down on adjacent communities.
   At a large truck stop east of the airport, some 2,000 truck
drivers and campers waited for the winds to die down, said Lance
Davis, general manager of Truck Stops of America in Ontario. He said
at midmorning that at least 700 trucks were parked outside the truck
stop's three restaurants.
   By afternoon the winds ebbed and truckers and campers were on
their way, said Bob Berenyi, another truck stop manager.
   The National Weather Service said the winds were expected to fade
Friday.
   Elsewhere, a downed power line was blamed for a brush fire that
charred 200 acres in Orange County, said county Fire Department
Capt. Hugh Madlock.
   The fire in Trabuco Canyon, about 45 miles southeast of Los
Angeles, briefly threatened expensive homes before being surrounded
by midnight. Madlock said the high winds aggravated the 220
firefighters' efforts.
   Residents of about 50 homes were evacuated until flames were
doused. Several horses set loose during the height of the blaze had
to be corralled, Madlock said.
   In San Diego County, a 50-acre fire fanned by 60 mph winds burned
out of control Thursday afternoon near the city of Ramona, the
California Department of Forestry reported.
   Other power lines brought down by high winds caused outages that
affected about 6,000 homes and businesses served by Southern
California Edison in Los Angeles and Orange counties, said Edison
spokesman Kevin Kelly.
   The winds also overturned trucks on Interstates 10 and 15, which
remained open with traffic moving about 5 mph, said California
Highway Patrol Officer James O'Brien. Blowing dust reduced
visibility to almost zero, he said.
   In San Bernardino County, winds ripped off part of the roof of
the sheriff's station in Rancho Cucamonga and damaged several
private cars, said Deputy Denise Garland.
</TEXT>
