<FIRST>r a AM-Maxwell'sPlum     01-12 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Maxwell's Plum,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trump Buys Window From Maxwell's Plum</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maxwell's Plum, the prototype Sixties ``singles
bar'' and pre-Yuppy hot spot that catered to the young and upwardly
mobile, put its art deco, art nouveau, funhouse decor on the auction
block Thursday.
   The cafe closed July 10 after 22 years in business.
   Deal maker Donald Trump bought a leaded glass window for $26,800.
The stained glass window, featuring two peacocks against a blue
background, was designed from Tiffany Favrile glass by the
restaurant's owner, Warner LeRoy.
   Another buyer, an unidentified New York art dealer, paid the
highest price of the day: $38,500 for a 12-foot-long, leaded glass
window, depicting a cornucopia by artist John LaFarge.
   ``He (LaFarge) was the one who supposedly taught Tiffany how to
make the Favrile glass,'' said auctioneer William Doyle, who
operates an auction house in Manhattan.
   Trump plans to display the window in the Taj Mahal, a hotel he's
building in Atlantic City, according to Patti Fox, who bid on
Trump's behalf after he made a brief appearance at the auction.
   An 18-by-28 foot ceiling, also designed by LeRoy from Tiffany
glass, was withdrawn from the auction after it failed to make the
lowest acceptable bid, which LeRoy put at $1 million.
   Sources at the auction house and the Trump organization indicated
the millionaire still was interested in the ceiling and would
negotiate for it privately.
   Maxwell's Plum, once a hot spot among trendy New Yorkers in the
1960s, saw its fortunes fail in the highly competitive Manhattan
restaurant market of the 1980s.
   Legend has it that the expression ``singles bar'' was coined
there. An estimated 3,000 people stood in line on the night it
opened for business with a decor that was an odd concoction of art
nouveau, art deco and carnival motifs.
   Among the items sold Thursday was the funhouse mirror, which went
for $550, and a carousel horse that brought $3,575. Another big
attraction, a red Harley Davidson motorcycle that LeRoy bought from
Arnold Schwarzenegger to display at the restaurant, went for $16,500.
   ``They're all my favorites! I'm having so much fun, I may try
this with Tavern on the Green,'' said LeRoy, an avid collector who
also owns that famed New York restaurant.
   The auction brought in a total of $766,965. About $56,000 of that
came from Trump, who also bought a chandelier and a bronze elephant
head, according to Maryalice Adams, a spokeswoman for the auctioneer.
</TEXT>
