<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica     01-12 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Kill Two</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police shot and killed two
blacks who were among a group that fired on a military patrol,
authorities said Thursday.
   Police also said a 23-year-old black man was stabbed to death in
Willow Fountain, also in Natal province, where more than 1,000
blacks have died in unrest during the past 18 months. No further
details were given.
   A police report said officers fired birdshot Wednesday at a group
of blacks, some of whom were firing at a police patrol, in Molweni
township near Durban. Two of the men were killed and one injured,
the report said. Eleven were arrested.
   In another development, police said three mines exploded
overnight in and around Ciskei, a tribal homeland for the Xhosas.
The South African government considers the area to be an independent
republic, but it is not recognized by other countries.
   An officer sustained a burst eardrum when bomb experts were
trying to detonate one mine in King William's Town in the eastern
Cape province, police said.
   Other explosions occurred in Wilsonia near East London and at a
railway station on the outskirts of the nearby Ciskei capital,
Mdantsane. Police gave no motives for the explosions and did not
comment on whether they were linked.
   A weekly black newspaper, The New Nation, said there had been at
least two cases of clashes between authorities and members of the
black communities in the area in the past week.
   The paper, which the South African government closed down for
three months this year, reported that Ciskei police and soldiers
last week assaulted residents of a village who are opposing their
incorporation into the homeland. Many blacks do not want to live in
the homelands because their rights to live and work in South Africa
are curtailed.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
