<SECOND>AM-Bus Wreck, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0764,0606</SECOND>
<HEAD>School Bus and Coal Truck Collide, More Than 40 Injured, Two Critically</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with more than 40 injured, sted 30;
bus driver charged; color from injured teen; identifies two critical teens
and truck's driver, background on bus driver's record. No pick up.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE EMBRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coal dump truck slammed into the side of a
school bus filled with students Thursday, injuring more than 40
children and both drivers, authorities said.
   At least seven people were hospitalized, two in critical
condition.
   ``It was just a tremendous amount of chaos,'' said Laurel County
Sherrif's Capt. Gene Hollon, who arrived at the scene minutes after
the accident.
   ``Several people had stopped on the highway to try to render aid.
... It was a terrible looking scene. ... There were children sitting
everywhere. Children were still pinned in the wreckage,'' he said.
   The bus driver, Enoch Ray Smith, 33, was charged with driving
with a suspended license, police said, but added that they could not
immediately determine who was at fault.
   The accident occurred at 3:10 p.m. at the entrance of North
Laurel Junior High, Hollon said. Most of the students on the bus
were believed to be have attended the school.
   The truck, headed north, slammed into the bus' midsection, Hollon
said, adding that it was not immediately clear what led up to the
accident.
   Rescue units used machines to cut through the crumpled metal to
free some victims.
   ``There was a tremendous amount of screaming and crying,'' said
Hollon. ``Some of the students were pinned in together. I saw one
instance where one of the students was trying to help the other,
even though they both were pinned in.''
   ``It happened all of a sudden,'' said Jackie McFadden, a
14-year-old who suffered a sprained right arm in the accident. ``It
sounded like a stick of dynamite.''
   Two 13-year-old boys were in critical condition at the University
of Kentucky Medical Center in Lexington, said hospital spokeswoman
Mary Margaret Colliver.
   The boys were identified as Robert Watts and John Detherage,
hometowns unknown. Watts had abdominal injuries and other injuries
and underwent surgery late Thursday. Detherage, with head injuries
and multiple lacerations, was in the pediatric intensive care unit.
   At least five others were admitted to Marymount Hospital, said
Lowell Jones, hospital administrator. Thirty-five students, the
drivers of the vehicles and an adult school aide were treated and
released, the hospital said. Injuries ranged from bruises to massive
internal trauma, he said.
   Authorities had not determined how many students were on the bus,
but Jones said all were in their teens.
   The coal truck driver, John B. Massey, 28, suffered cuts and
bruises on his face and Massey's 4-year-old son, who was in the
truck with him, was under observation, said patrolman Paul
Shackelford.
   Smith, the bus driver, completed state-required training more
than a year ago, said Gordon Nichols, spokesman for the state
Department of Education.
   The charge filed against him Thursday involved a speeding ticket
issued on Aug. 25, Shackelford said. Smith paid the fine but failed
to report to traffic school, resulting in the suspension, the
patrolman said.
   About 150 to 175 parents and others converged on Marymount
Hospital after the accident to learn the extent of the students'
injuries, Jones said.
   Students who suffered minor injuries, such as glass cuts, were
treated in the hospital's hallways while the emergency room and the
trauma unit were used to treat the more seriously injured, Hollon
said.
</TEXT>
