<FIRST>r a AM-KMartRuling     01-12 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-K Mart Ruling,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>K Mart Ruled Liable In Sale Of Weapon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NIAGARA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury found K mart Inc., the nation's
second-largest retailer, liable for $2.4 million damages for selling
a shotgun to an intoxicated man who later shot and paralyzed another
man with it.
   The state Supreme Court jury in Niagara County made the award
Tuesday to the estate of Thomas Viscomi and his widow, Norma
Viscomi, of Niagara Falls.
   Viscomi was shot in the back in 1979 by John Hoopsick, who held a
longtime grudge against him, and who hours earlier purchased the
shotgun and ammunition at a K mart store in Niagara Falls.
   Terry Smith, a lawyer for the widow, said the store's sales clerk
should have known not to sell the weapon to Hoopsick, who was
described as obviously drunk and agitated at the time.
   Smith said the award was the first in New York state where a jury
has held a store liable for selling a weapon to a drunken person.
   Although federal firearms regulations prohibit the sale of guns
to minors, illegal aliens, people with drug dependencies and mental
deficiencies, there is no prohibition against sales to people who
are drunk, he said.
   Smith said there have been a number of successful civil cases
against gun retailers in other states, including a recent judgment
against K mart in a similar case in St. Claire Shores, Mich.
   Leslie Kota, a spokeswoman for K mart based in Troy, Mich., said
the company would appeal the ruling.
   K mart's lawyers had argued that Hoopsick was not visibly
intoxicated and that the sales clerk couldn't have known what
Hoopsick planned to do with the weapon.
   K mart has 15 days to file a posttrial motion in the trial-level
State Supreme Court.
   On Dec. 4, 1979, Viscomi, then 59, was shot with a 12-gauge
shotgun after returning home from work. One of the pellets from the
shotgun blast damaged Viscomi's spinal cord and he was left
paralyzed from the waist, Smith said.
   Hoopsick was sentenced to five years' probation after pleading
guilty to charges in March 1981. Viscomi died of a heart attack on
June 28, 1986, according to Smith.
   The case was originally tried in November 1986 and K mart was
found negligent in the selling the shotgun. The jury award the
Viscomis $500,000.
   K mart was unsuccessful in getting a state appellate court to
overturn the finding the next year.
   The one-week trial that ended Tuesday was limited to damages only.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
