<FIRST>u i AM-Mexico-Union 3rdLd-Writethru   01-12 0861</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Union, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0782,0889</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Workers Leader Arraigned</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS five grafs after 17th pvs, `The authentic ...' to UPDATE
with government choice for union spot; picks up 18th pvs: `The Oil...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of Mexico's powerful Oil Workers
Union was arraigned Thursday on homicide and arms charges as forces
in the governing party began moving to install leaders more
sympathetic to President Carlos Salinas de Gortari.
   A bomb threat and rumors of more arrests forced union local
chiefs to evacuate the union's national headquarters before they
could vote to confirm the choice of a new secretary-general.
Judicial police searched the building.
   Joaquin Hernandez Galicia and 50 other union leaders and
associates were arrested Tuesday and Wednesday. Thousands of oil
workers demonstrated in protest Thursday night in Mexico City's
Zocalo Plaza.
   A source in the Attorney General's Office said former Reynosa
Mayor Jose Cruz Contreras was suspected of smuggling arms shipments
for Hernandez Galicia from the United States and officials were
looking for him.
   The source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Mexican and
U.S. law enforcement officials met Thursday to try to determine the
origin of a weapons cache found in Hernandez Galicia's home.
   The source said Mexican officials suspected that drugs may have
been used to pay for the weapons.
   He said Hernandez Galicia faces up to 40 years in prison if
convicted.
   In a Mexico City prison Thursday, Hernandez Galicia told
reporters: ``They told me my family was kidnapped and if I didn't
give a statement that pleased the Federal Attorney General, I
wouldn't see them again.''
   He called his detention ``a dirty, prefabricated infamy.'' Still,
he urged oil workers to stay on the job.
   On Wednesday, Sen. Ricardo Camero Cardiel was named union
secretary-general for 30 days. He replaces Salvador Barragan
Camacho, who turned himself in after Hernandez Galicia was arrested
and Barragan Camacho's house was searched.
   Barragan Camacho, who has a history of heart trouble, is under
arrest in a hospital.
   The daily newspaper La Jornada said Camero Cardiel, ``with more
than 30 years of union activity, is a recognized member of
(Hernandez Galicia's) group.''
   Camero Cardiel pledged to use ``all legal means to win the
freedom of Hernandez, Barragan and other arrested leaders,'' the
newspaper said.
   Government sources said union rules were not followed in the
selection of Camero Cardiel and indicated it was likely he would not
remain in the post.
   ``The authentic workers, and there are thousands of them, will be
able to work better with the company and strengthen'' Pemex, the
state oil monopoly, under a new leadership, a government source said
on condition of anonymity.
   Labor Secretary Arsenio Farell Cubillas objected to the election
of Cardiel, saying that union bylaws require that the union's
interior secretary, Jose Melendez Maranto, should replace Barragan
Camacho.
   The government feels Melendez would be more sympathetic to
President Carlos Salinas de Gortari, who has long feuded with the
union's powerful innner circle.
   But union spokesman Fernando Arreola said that Farell Cubillas
``obviously does not know the union's bylaws.''
   Arreola said an extraordinary session of more than 90 percent of
local representatives chose Cardiel for the remainder of Barragan
Camacho's five-year term.
   He said Melendez could have been selected under union bylaws but
that ``because it was not known how long Barragan Camacho would be
away, they picked Cardiel.''
   The Oil Workers Union, like most of the labor movement, is
closely tied to the government. But Hernandez Galicia, known by his
nickname La Quina, has a longstanding dispute with Salinas.
   The arrest of La Quina, and 50 others in a violent raid continued
to draw criticism Thursday, even from government-linked unions and
their leaders.
   The Labor Congress issued a statement Wednesday saying it
``strongly protests the violence used'' and called for the freedom
of those arrested.
   Soldiers blew down the door of Hernandez Galicia's home and a
federal agent was killed in the ensuing gunbattle.
   Leaders of the Mexican Labor Federation, the country's largest
labor federation, and the Labor Congress, a government-aligned
organization of nearly all the country's unions, met Thursday with
Salinas.
   A statement from the presidency said the meetings were
traditional New Year's calls, and did not mention the arrests.
Veteran Labor Federation leader Fidel Velazquez did not speak with
reporters after the meeting.
   In a second statement, Salinas expressed solidarity with
Velazquez and the labor movement.
   Hernandez Galicia, who held only a minor union office but has
been its unofficial boss for years, was charged with homicide,
possession of large quantitites of weapons, importing prohibited
weapons and resisting authority, said Fernando Arias Perez, an
attorney general's office spokesman.
   Authorities have said more than 200 Uzi submachine guns were
found in Hernandez Galicia's home when he was arrested Tuesday in
Ciudad Madero, about 220 miles northeast of Mexico City on the Gulf
of Mexico.
   He told investigators Uzis and about 30,000 cartridges were
secretly delivered to him on Dec. 10 and were ``to defend his union
members, given the existing situation in the country,'' the attorney
general's office said.
   Arias Perez said 50 other people arrested face charges of fraud,
weapons and tax evasion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
