<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 0657EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-PersonalFile-Jefferies Adv13   01-12 1093</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Personal File-Jefferies, Adv 13,1123</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday, Jan. 13, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Boyd Jefferies: Chainsmoking Workaholic, Admitted Felon, Key Fraud
Witness</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY350 of Jan. 11</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boyd L. Jefferies used to thrive on four hours of
sleep a night, arriving for work at 1:30 a.m. and staying until
evening to command the aggressive stock-trading desk of the
brokerage that bears his name.
   Now the 58-year-old ex-broker spends much of his time with
defense lawyers and federal investigators, chainsmoking cigarettes,
answering questions and wondering when he will get back to his
passion on the 33rd floor of a downtown Los Angeles skyscraper,
buying and selling big blocks of stock.
   A criminal courtroom has replaced his sprawling trading desk; the
tension of interrogation has replaced the thrill of stock
speculation; the priority of avoiding jail time has replaced the
obsession with serving clients.
   Once spectacularly successful, widely admired and courted by
almost every big takeover strategist, Jefferies has been transformed
over the last two years into what gangsters might call the biggest
canary in his business.
   He is the leading prosecution witness in at least three major
fraud cases that arose indirectly from the man who squealed on him,
Ivan F. Boesky, the stock speculator and inside trader now serving a
three-year prison term.
   In exchange for lenient treatment, Jefferies agreed with federal
prosecutors in March 1987 to plead guilty to two violations of
securities laws, cooperate in other investigations, resign from his
brokerage, Jefferies &amp; Co., and stay out of the securities business
for at least five years.
   ``Yes, I miss it,'' Jefferies said, standing outside a Manhattan
federal courtroom on a break in his recent witness-stand debut in
the stock-manipulation case against GAF Corp. and a top company
officer.
   He declined to elaborate and spent much of the break in a witness
waiting room, puffing Benson &amp; Hedges 100s, chewing gum and slowly
pacing the floor. He looked tan and fit in a dark-blue business
suit, but his blue eyes were slightly bloodshot and he seldom smiled.
   ``Here's a guy who used to get up at 1:30 in the morning to go
work,'' said James P. Linn, Jefferies' lawyer. ``It's not easy for a
man who's worked like that to stand around in a federal courthouse.''
   Nevertheless, life isn't that bad for Jefferies. He remains
fabulously wealthy and owns expensive homes in Indian Wells, Calif.,
and Aspen, Colo., which he shares with his wife. He spends much of
his time on the telephone to keep abreast of the market, though he
generally refrains from calling his colleagues at the company, Linn
said.
   ``I suppose he's allowed to call, but the company doesn't like
for him to, so he doesn't,'' the lawyer said in an interview.
   A good golfer, Jefferies has started a scholarship program in
Aspen for aspiring young golf amateurs. Although defense lawyers
have tried to claim this generosity is meant to impress the judge
who ultimately will sentence him, Linn denied that.
   ``The fact is, Boyd Jefferies had a son killed in an accident. He
is passionately involved with young people, having lost his son,''
Linn said. ``He has no ulterior motive in doing his golf deal.''
   Jefferies' punishment remains unclear, but is expected to be far
less than the maximum sentence of 10 years' imprisonment and
$500,000 in fines he faces for pleading guilty to one count of
violating stock-margin requirements and one count of aiding and
abetting to keep false books.
   He even suggested on the witness stand, in cross-examination by
defense attorneys in the GAF trial, that he doesn't expect to serve
any prison time.
   To a large extent, the severity of the sentence will depend on
the fruits of his cooperation, which were bruised this past week
when a federal judge decreed a mistrial in the GAF case because the
prosecution mishandled a key piece of evidence.
   Aside from his involvement in GAF, Jefferies is a leading witness
in securities fraud prosecutions against Paul Bilzerian, a
Florida-based takeover speculator, and Salim B. Lewis, a New
York-based securities professional. Both are former Jefferies'
clients.
   Linn and other associates of Jefferies have tried to portray him
as a man so driven to serve his customers that he crossed the bounds
of legality on their behalf, not out of personal avarice.
   Many big investors have expressed faith in him, such as Texas
oilman T. Boone Pickens and Minneapolis takeover strategist Irwin
Jacobs. But Jefferies' lawyer conceded that other clients might feel
betrayed by a trusted broker who later turned state's evidence in a
major criminal investigation.
   ``Yes, I suppose there would be some of those people,'' Linn
said. ``But Boyd still has a very loyal and large following. He did
a lot of things for a lot of people.''
   Jefferies' rapid rise, generosity and crashing downfall are part
of the folklore of the 1980s takeover boom. A UCLA graduate and
former ranch hand, he started in the securities business by landing
an entry-level job at a small brokerage, quit six years later and
founded his own firm with two employees.
   By early this decade, Jefferies &amp; Co. had swelled to more than
400 employees, with a large trading center in Los Angeles, five
other offices nationwide and one in London.
   It became known as the leading firm where investors could trade
big blocks of stock quickly and discreetly, without going through
conventional stock exchanges.
   Jefferies was said to delight in making markets for high-profile
stocks, and the positions he took in well-known targets sometimes
determined the outcome of takeover battles.
   In late 1986, for example, Jefferies helped Toronto-based Campeau
Corp. acquire Allied Stores Corp. by selling the Canadian developer
a large block of its Allied holdings for more than $1.7 billion.
   Part of the attraction for takeover investors was Jefferies'
policy of absolute confidentiality and extraordinary accommodation
in doing business at their convenience, no matter when.
   Jacobs once said he could call the company as early as 3 a.m. and
Jefferies would answer the telephone, having arrived early to trade
European stocks.
   ``There were no such things as hours for Boyd,'' Jacobs said.
``You could find Boyd seven days a week, 24 hours a day.''
   Despite predictions that his brokerage would falter following his
plea agreement, Jefferies &amp; Co. continues to be an aggressive trader
and he intends to return there when his legal ordeal finally ends,
Linn said.
   ``He's lost without that business. That business literally was
his life,'' the lawyer said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Friday Jan. 13</NOTE>
