<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 2156EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a AM-ReformingSchools Adv16   01-12 1203</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reforming Schools, Adv 16,1241</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release AMs Monday Jan. 16, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>City Schools: What Does It Take To Reform Them?</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hint of revolution is in the air in at least
some big-city school systems: an apparent readiness, at long last,
to stop bickering and start reforming.
   The nation's largest system, New York City, continues to generate
shocking headlines about violence, drugs and widespread neighborhood
school board corruption. Within the last month, an elementary school
principal and three teachers were picked up on drug charges. And
last week, a kindergartner was found with a .25-caliber pistol.
   But the picture has begun to brighten elsewhere.
   In Pittsburgh, Dade County, Fla., and Rochester, N.Y., teacher
unions and school administrators have beaten their swords into
reform-minded contracts that boost teacher pay and power while
making them directly accountable for their students' performance.
   In Detroit, where the dropout rate is at least 40 percent, fed up
voters elected a reform school board slate in November. They also
refused to approve new school taxes and bonds aimed at paying off an
estimated $158 million deficit.
   There are even hopeful signs in Chicago's schools, branded 14
months ago as the nation's worst by U.S. Secretary of Education
William J. Bennett. Illinois Gov. James Thompson signed legislation
last month scrapping Chicago's central school board next July, to be
replaced by parent-run councils empowered to set budgets and hire
and fire principals.
   That hardly means such cities have solved their school problems,
officials are quick to admit.
   Chicago's new governing structure may lead to unprecedented
parent power, but the basic problems still fester: a 45 percent
dropout rate and below-average standardized test scores.
   As Rochester teacher union leader Adam Urbanski put it: ``We have
set the table; we have not served the meal yet.''
   Hopeful signs are scarce in the 960,000-student New York City
system.
   It's true that New York's state legislature recently passed
long-sought bills clearing the way for desperately needed school
construction and making new rules to curb school board patronage.
   But Schools Chancellor Richard Green, whose much-heralded arrival
as an outsider from Minneapolis last March raised hopes for new
approaches, has instead found himself tangled in investigations of
local school board corruption.
   To some, New York remains a system adrift.
   ``At this point, there are a lot of people putting out ideas, and
a lot of people wringing their hands. We have to have the
administration put out a specific plan so that people can get behind
it,'' said Robin Willner, deputy executive director of Interface, a
watchdog group that issues frequent reports on city school issues.
   All of which raises the question: What does it take to put the
nation's largest school systems on the road to reform?
   Relative size and the power of the purse are certainly key
factors, says Samuel L. Husk, executive director of the Council of
Great City Schools. Pittsburgh, for example, has only 40,000
students, and its school board has taxing authority.
   New York City has 25 times more students, and its school board
has no authority to tax. Its size and tangled politics foster a
feeling of hopelessness. Some now openly wonder how many
drug-addicted principals and teachers it will take to finally jolt
the system.
   ``I think that you need a catalyst. I hate to say it has to be
horrible. Unfortunately in a school system this size, it may have to
be,'' said Willner.
   New Orleans' 80,000-student public schools have an additional
disadvantage: they must compete with a popular, 35,000-student
parochial school system that siphons off political support.
   But all cities have obstacles to overcome. Whether they succeed
in reform, or even attempt it, usually depends on someone in
authority willing to lead the charge.
   ``You need leadership at the top. Those at the top and those in
the private sector have to see it as an absolute emergency. It's a
political problem,'' said Ernest L. Boyer, a national spokesman for
reform and president of the Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement
of Teaching, which has produced several reports on urban school
problems.
   In Rochester and Pittsburgh, new superintendents have made a
difference.
   Rochester's Peter McWalters, named in 1986, signaled willingness
to form a working partnership with teachers. Under a contract that
took effect this year, each teacher is directly responsible for 20
students, holding daily meetings and home visits where necessary. In
return, top teacher salaries will rise to $70,000 and school-based
planning teams consisting of teachers, parents, students and
principals will set goals for each school.
   ``When McWalters came in, he shared my sense of urgency, and he
was devoid of the baggage and inhibitions that management often
has,'' said Urbanski. ``His passion proved infectious. After our
collective bargaining agreement, we had left little choice for the
political and business structure but to follow suit to help us make
it work.''
   Pittsburgh's superintendent, Richard C. Wallace, who arrived in
1980 as an outsider to a city enmeshed in a bitter dispute over
school desegregation, helped move the school system beyond that
dispute and establish it as a national model of reform. He promptly
began biweekly meetings with the teacher union, established a center
to enhance teacher skills, and attracted millions in corporate funds
to support innovative programs.
   Likewise in Miami's Dade County, the teacher union and
superintendent have stopped fighting and started cooperating to
devise a reform plan.
   But the key factor was leadership, said Husk. ``The thing to
remember is Florida had an education governor, Bob Graham, and he
made a substantial investment in schools long before other states
were even thinking about reform.''
   Some feel New York is still waiting for such leadership.
   ``We don't have any one elective official who has made education
their primary issue,'' said Willner. ``In terms of using the bully
pulpit, having an education mayor or governor, that hasn't happened
in New York.''
   In New Orleans, meanwhile, the bad times keep rolling for a
school system perennially starved of leadership and tax dollars.
Still, many are encouraged by the election last year of Louisiana's
reform-minded governor, Buddy Roemer, a property tax increase last
April, and a new, expanded school board.
   That may not be enough. A state report showed that 370 of New
Orleans' 4,800-teacher staff were either uncertified or had
temporary certificates, and despite recent increases, salaries still
average just $26,800, about $2,000 below the national average.
   ``The New Orleans public schools remain a factory for the
expansion of the underclass,'' said Lee Gary, a private education
consultant.
   Boyer sees four elements necessary to move big systems toward
reform: clearly stated goals, smaller schools structured so that
students no longer feel anonymous, more school-based authority where
officials are regularly accountable for results, and above all,
partnerships between parents, civic, corporate and educational
officials.
   ``If you pull these reform efforts apart, these cities are making
progress on governance, and partnerships,'' said Boyer. ``What I
don't see is much attention to school climate, student alienation,
and the question of educational goals and outcomes.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Lee Mitgang has covered education for the AP
since 1981.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs Jan. 16</NOTE>
