<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, Two Takes,0544</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. and former Sen.
Howard Baker have scrapped negotiations about a possible management
role for him at the troubled Wall Street giant, which recently
agreed to a record $650 million plea bargain on securities fraud
charges.
   By mutual consent, Drexel and Baker said Wednesday, ``The talks
ended, and the senator will not be taking a position with the
investment baking firm.''
   Steven Anreder, a Drexel spokesman, would not elaborate beyond
the statement, and there was no answer at the Tennessee office of
Baker's spokesman Thomas Griscom late Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rapid rise in oil prices since OPEC agreed to
slash production six weeks ago has exceeded most people's
expections, but energy analysts aren't ready to declare the cartel's
accord a success.
   Prices of Middle East oil remain well below OPEC's target of $18
a barrel, and some recent gains may be lost if the excess oil
produced by the cartel late last year ever hits the market, analysts
said Wednesday.
   Since Nov. 28, when the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries announced it would curtail production, Middle Eastern
crude oil has risen more than $3 a barrel _ from approximately $11
to about $15.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal aviation officials ordered inspections
of 300 Boeing 737s for possible cross-wiring of engine warning
systems, which is one possibility being investigated as contributing
to the British Midland crash.
   The Federal Aviation Administration order on Wednesday came after
the British Civil Aviation Authority ordered similar checks, along
with stepped-up inspections of engines on three types of aircraft
using the same engines as the British Midland Airways Boeing 737-400
that crashed Sunday, killing 44 people.
   The ``air worthiness directive'' issued by FAA Administrator
Allan McArtor did not cover engine inspections and would not ground
any U.S. aircraft.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Only one U.S. worker in 100 was tested for drug
use last year, the government said in new study that sharply reduced
previous estimates of how many employers conduct such tests.
   The Labor Department survey, conducted last summer and released
Wednesday, found that only 3 percent of all employers employing
about 20 percent of American workers had drug-testing programs.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PROSPECT HEIGHTS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Household International Inc. plans
to dissolve its $1 billion manufacturing empire, narrowing the
company's operations to financial services after four years of
restructuring.
   The company said Wednesday it would spin off three of its
manufacturing units to its shareholders, creating three independent
companies, and sell the other six, which include Thermos Co.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warner Communications Inc. has closed its
long-delayed, $1.2 billion merger with Lorimar Telepictures Corp. in
a deal that solidifies its position as the leader in entertainment
programming.
   The two entertainment concerns had agreed to a merger last May,
but the completion of the deal on Wednesday was delayed because of
legal complications arising from Lorimar's ownership of several
television stations, which it sold.
   The merger includes a swap of stock valued at about $635 million
and Warner's assumption of about $600 million in Lorimar debt.
</TEXT>
