<FIRST>r f PM-OilPrices     01-12 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Prices,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crude Prices Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six weeks after OPEC announced it would reduce
production, U.S. crude prices have risen by more than $3 a barrel.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange Wednesday, the February
contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S.
crude, continued to climb, picking up 45 cents to close at $18.14 a
barrel. Other contract months also rose.
   Analysts said a number of factors contributed to the day's gains,
including a sharp drop in crude oil supplies and signs that OPEC is
holding to its agreement to cut back production.
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries agreed last
November to reduce output by 3 million barrels to 18.5 million
barrels a day. WTI prices have since climbed from the $15 range and
analysts expect strong demand to push prices even higher.
   The accord took effect Jan. 1 and continues for six months.
   Richard Redoglia, a broker with Merrill Lynch Energy Futures,
said higher prices have ``encouraged more people to come in and
buy.''
   Analysts said Wednesday's crude market also got a boost from
American Petroleum Institute statistics released Tuesday showing oil
stocks declined 5.5 million barrels last week to 328.86 million
barrels. The API report said gasoline supplies increased by 531,000
barrels to 229.1 million and heating oil stocks were up 726,000 to
127.5 million barrels.
   On the mercantile exchange, unleaded gasoline futures prices were
mostly higher Wednesday, influenced by a partial shutdown of
refinery operations in Mexico by striking union workers. The
February contract for gasoline closed 0.79 cent higher at 48.70 a
gallon.
   Heating oil futures ended the day mixed, with the February
contract down 0.17 cent at 53.69 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
