<FIRST>r f PM-OilRebound Bjt   01-12 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Rebound, Bjt,0614</SECOND>
<HEAD>Analysts Assessing Price Increase Six Weeks After OPEC Pact</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World crude prices have climbed by more than $3 a
barrel in the six weeks since OPEC agreed to cut its production, but
analysts remain skeptical that the accord will last.
   Prices of Middle East oil are still below OPEC's targeted price
of $18 a barrel, and some of the recent gains may still be lost if
the excess oil produced by the cartel late last year reaches the
market.
   Since Nov. 28, when the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries announced it would curtail production, Middle Eastern
crude oil has risen more than $3 a barrel _ from approximately $11
to about $15.
   West Texas Intermediate, the U.S. benchmark grade of crude oil,
has shot up to more than $18 a barrel from $15.03 the day the accord
was finalized.
   Most market observers had expected prices to rise but they had
forecast a more gradual increase with the excess oil keeping prices
soft for some time. Despite the recent increases, experts remain
doubtful about the future.
   ``I don't see $18 in the year for OPEC basket prices, at least
not for any sustained period. There is an overproduction that we
will still see the consequences of down the road, '' said John
Lichtblau, president of the Petroleum Industry Research Foundation.
   At the time of the OPEC agreement in November, the 13-member
cartel was producing approximately 22.5 million barrels of oil a
day. In December, that figure rose to about 23 million.
   For January, OPEC's production will be about 19 million barrels,
slightly above its new quota of 18.5 million. OPEC's accord took
effect Jan. 1 and extends for six months.
   Since it takes four to five weeks for most Middle East oil to
reach markets in the United States, analysts believed shiploads of
crude pumped late last year would be arriving on U.S. shores any day
now, driving prices lower. But they haven't, and the question many
are asking is: Where is it?
   ``I suppose some production could be in transit, but we were
hearing about surplus production as early as October and it hasn't
shown up in the statistics,'' said Gordon Pye, an economist with
Irving Trust Co. ``It calls into question the accuracy of the OPEC
figures we read about. ... Either that or it's being consumed more
rapidly than anyone thinks.''
   Nauman Barakat, vice president of energy investments for
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc., believes a lot of the excess oil
is sitting in storage tanks somewhere in the Middle East.
   ``There was an intentional decision by the cartel to keep as much
of that crude as possible off the market so as not to flood the
market and force prices lower,'' Barakat said.
   Demand for OPEC oil in major oil-consuming countries like the
United States and Japan has been stronger than projected. A report
Wednesday from the International Energy Agency showed industrialized
countries consumed 38.4 million barrels a day of oil in the fourth
quarter, 1 million barrels or 4 percent more than previously
forecast. The report said U.S. consumption was up 4.5 percent while
Japanese consumption rose 6 percent.
   Nevertheless, many analysts believe high demand won't be enough
to boost or sustain prices for Middle East oil at the $18 level for
the length of the agreement. One OPEC country, the United Arab
Emirates, has already acknowledged it is producing above its quota.
   ``The question still is `Will OPEC stick to its quota beyond the
first quarter?''' said Lichtblau.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
