<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 0610EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Warner-Lorimar Bjt   01-12 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Warner-Lorimar, Bjt,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warner Completes Merger with Lorimar</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warner Communications Inc. solidified its
position as the leader in entertainment programming and beefed up
its role in television by completing its $1.2 billion merger with
Lorimar Telepictures Corp.
   The merger, which involves a stock swap valued at about $635
million and Warner's assumption of about $600 million in Lorimar
debt, was concluded Wednesday, the two entertainment concerns said.
   The companies had agreed to a merger last May, but the completion
of the deal was delayed because of legal complications arising from
Lorimar's ownership of several television stations.
   Lorimar subsequently disposed of its television stations,
completing the sale of the last of them, WPGH in Pittsburgh, on
Tuesday.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Warner rose 37{ cents
a share to close at $37.50.
   Under terms of the merger agreement, Warner said Lorimar has
become a wholly-owned subsidiary of Warner and each share of Lorimar
stock has been converted into the right to receive .3675 of a share
on Warner stock.
   With about 46 million shares of common stock outstanding, the
Lorimar stock could be converted into about 17 million shares of
Warner stock, worth about $635 million at current prices.
   In addition, Warner would assume Lorimar's debt of about $600
million, boosting the value of the transaction to about $1.2 billion.
   Warner also reaffirmed its plans to elect Merv Adelson, chairman
and chief executive of Lorimar, as vice chairman and a member of
Warner's board. The election will probably come at the next Warner
board meeting in February.
   Lorimar, based in Culver City, Calif., is a leading producer and
distributor of television programming.
   A spokeswoman for Lorimar, Barbara Brogliatti, said Lorimar
currently supplies nine shows and seven hours a week of programming
carried on the major television networks, including ``Dallas,''
``Knots Landing'' and Alf.''
   She said it supplies an additional 13 shows and 25 hours a week
of first-run syndicated programming to local stations, including
``People's Court,'' ``Love Connection'' and ``Freddy's Nightmares.''
   Warner currently has six shows on network television, including
``Night Court'' and ``Growing Pains,'' and spokesman Geoffrey Holmes
said the combined total of 15 network shows outdistances production
by any other studio.
   Holmes said Warner already was the leader in entertainment
programming, which he defined as movies, television shows and
recorded music and publishing.
   He said the merger will boost its revenue from such programming
by $600 million a year to $4 billion, or about $1 billion more than
the second biggest entertainment programmer, Walt Disney Co.
   Lorimar has lost more than $380 million in the last 2{ years, but
Warner executives have said they expect Lorimar's performance will
improve as some of its more popular first-run shows are sold in
syndication.
   Warner, based in New York, is a leading producer and distributor
of movies, television shows and recorded music and has interests in
cable operations.
   For the first nine months of 1988, Warner earned $322 million, or
$2.02 a share, on revenue of $3.01 billion.
   The stumbling block that had held up completion of the merger
stemmed from a 1984 agreement that Warner and its biggest
stockholder, Chris-Craft Industries Inc., reached when they bought
stakes in one another.
   As Chris-Craft bought its stake in Warner, Warner bought a 42.5
percent interest in Chris-Craft's BHC Inc. broadcasting unit.
   Chris-Craft sued to block the Lorimar deal last summer, saying
the 1984 agreement prohibited Warner from owning television stations
as long as it owned 25 percent or more of BHC.
   A state court judge in New York blocked the planned merger in
late September. Lorimar subsequently agreed to sell its television
stations, completing the sale of its interest in two stations in
Puerto Rico in late December and the sale of the Pittsburgh station
late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
