<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 0611EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-HouseholdInternational Bjt   01-12 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Household International, Bjt,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>Household's Investors Big Winners As Firm Exits Manufacturing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROSPECT HEIGHTS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Household International Inc.'s exit
from the manufacturing arena is a boon to the firm's shareholders,
who will receive stock in three new companies free of charge while
retaining their shares in the streamlined company.
   Household International said Wednesday it was dissolving its $1
billion manufacturing group, ending four years of restructuring
efforts, and would concentrate solely on financial services.
   The company said it would spin off three manufacturing units to
shareholders and sell six other businesses, including Thermos Co.
   ``It's a pleasant surprise to see a company doing something
right,'' said Rudolph Martin, an analyst who follows Household for
Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Martin called Household's announcement ``an illustration of their
integrity.''
   ``They realize they can increase shareholder value by spinning
off these operations,'' he said.
   Analysts said the value of Household's stock may decline
slightly, but the value of shareholders' new stock should more than
make up the difference.
   The three independent companies to be created are Eljer
Industries Inc., a building products company with anticipated 1988
sales of more than $400 million; Schwitzer Inc., a maker of engine
parts with anticipated 1988 sales of $140 million; and Scotsman
Industries Inc., a manufacturer of commercial refrigeration products
with anticipated 1988 sales of $175 million.
   The firm will be left with four financial-services operations:
Household Finance Corp., the Household Bank; Household Commercial
Finance and the Alexander Hamilton Life Insurance Co.
   Household's stock price surged $5.25 Wednesday on the New York
Stock Exchange in reaction to the announcement, closing at $62.37{.
   Martin estimated the combined potential value of the surviving
company and the three spinoffs at $72 a share _ $58 for Household's
financial-services operations and $14 for the spinoffs.
   Household said it was considering a tax-free distribution of one
new share in each of the three spinoffs for every five shares of
Household's common stock on or about April 15.
   Household said it would use the proceeds from the transactions to
reduce its $500 million debt by about $255 million and pump about
$95 million into its financial services businesses.
   ``The actions represent a logical next step to several years of
restructuring in a continuing effort to maximize shareholder
value,'' Chairman Donald C. Clark said in a statement.
   The units to be sold are: Thermos, the well-known maker of
insulated products for storing and serving food; GC-Thorsen, a
marketer of entertainment accessories and hand tools; Albion
Industries, a leading manufacturer of heavy duty casters;
King-Sealey, a major supplier of cooking-appliance controls; Omni
Products International, a furniture maker; and WaterTest Corp., a
provider of water-testing services for consumer and commercial
markets.
   Household, which is based in Prospect Heights northwest of
Chicago, said it expected to receive ``well in excess'' of $120
million for the six units.
   Analysts said Household's departure from manufacturing was not
surprising, considering the company's sale of its Household
Merchandising subsidiary in 1985 and of National Car Rental a year
later.
   Frederick Wightman, vice president of research with Duff &amp; Phelps
Inc. in Chicago, said investors perceived manufacturing as having a
``cyclical influence'' on Household's stock price. He said the
company may be able to attract more investors by focusing on
financial services, which are considered to be more stable.
   Household said it expected 1988 sales from its manufacturing
division to exceed $1 billion.
   The company reported overall 1987 profit of $221.5 million on
sales of $3.4 billion.
   Household said it could not provide an overall figure for 1988
sales and profits, but that it expected a 20 percent increase in
per-share earnings for the year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
