<FIRST>r f PM-Pemex-At-A-Glance     01-12 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pemex-At-A-Glance,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexico's Government Petroleum Monopoly At A Glance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Mexico-Union ^By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a look at Mexico's government petroleum monopoly
Petroleos Mexicanos S.A., better known as Pemex, and the Oil Workers
Union:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE COMPANY: Pemex is one of the biggest oil companies in the
world, accounts for nearly half the government's revenues and is
intimately identified with the governing Institutional Revolutionary
Party.
   It was created in 1938 after President Lazaro Cardenas
nationalized foreign oil firms on March 18 of that year.
   It is not a member of the oil cartel OPEC but tends to follow the
pricing policies of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ASSETS: By law, Pemex has a complete monopoly over the
exploration and production of all hydrocarbons in Mexico, as well as
refining and the production of 36 ``basic'' petrochemicals. It
controls every aspect of the petroleum industry except for service
stations, which are private.
   Pemex claims assets of $31 billion, including nine refineries and
a score of petrochemical plants, as well as oil tankers, offshore
drilling rigs, one of the tallest buildings in the country and over
32,000 miles of pipelines.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   PRODUCTION: Pemex is the world's sixth-largest producer of oil
and the fifth-largest producer of petrochemicals.
   Crude oil production is about 2.8 million barrels per day. Mexico
is exporting about 1.36 million barrels a day, or about 40 percent
of its oil, to 50 nations around the world. About half of the
exports go to the United States.
   Pemex supplies 90 percent of Mexico's energy needs.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE UNION: The Oil Workers Union controls more than half the
lucrative drilling contracts let by Pemex and 95 percent of its
jobs. Pemex has about 180,000 employees and is considered
overstaffed by industry experts.
   Pemex workers are some of the highest paid in Mexico and enjoy
some of the best fringe benefits. Jobs can be inherited and are
sometimes sold under the table.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
