<FIRST>r f PM-Procter&amp;Gamble     01-12 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Procter &amp; Gamble,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Procter &amp; Gamble Announces New Stock Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Procter &amp; Gamble Co. will have a tougher shield
against hostile takeovers under a new employee stock ownership plan
that goes into effect this summer, analysts say.
   ``They see what's happening around them. They'd rather be safe
than sorry,'' Jerome Ballan, an analyst with Fahnestock &amp; Co, said,
referring to a recent spate of large takeovers.
   ``It's no more than a sign of the times.''
   While the stock plan will provide new insulation against possible
takeovers by giving employees a larger stake in the company, Proctor
&amp; Gamble officials said they had other intentions.
   The company said Wednesday that the ESOP is intended to enhance
the value of its stock and provide greater retirement security to
employees by improving profit sharing plans.
   A trust created for the new plan will borrow up to $1 billion for
a period of 15 years, with Procter &amp; Gamble guaranteeing the loan.
The loan's proceeds will be used to buy a new issue of convertible
preferred stock from the company, officials said.
   Pricing, terms and conditions on the preferred stock are to be
announced later, officials said.
   The ESOP goes into effect July 1, the company said.
   The company said its board of directors authorized Procter &amp;
Gamble to use proceeds from issuance of the convertible preferred
stock to repurchase up to 12 million shares of its common stock.
   This adds 2 million shares to the company's previously announced
10 million-share repurchase program adopted in October 1987.
   About 1 million shares have been repurchased to date, the company
said.
</TEXT>
