<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet10am     01-12 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0294</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was little changed today,
pausing to test the winds at its highest levels since the 1987 crash.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials slipped .36 to 2,206.07
in the first half hour of trading.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 7 to 5 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 509 up, 356 down and
541 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 23.10 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts said traders were encouraged by the market's drive
Wednesday past the 2,200 level in the Dow after a week-long
struggle. But they said traders were still faced with some
unanswered questions.
   The market's steady advance since last fall has come without any
support from interest rates, which have been rising.
   The Federal Reserve has continued to tighten credit, and many
Wall Streeters still believe the Fed might soon raise its discount
rate.
   Among actively traded blue chips, Merck rose { to 59|;
International Business Machines added [ to 122]; Exxon gained [ to
44|, and American Telephone &amp; Telegraph was unchanged at 28~.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.09 to 158.74. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .50 at 314.36.
   On Wednesday the Dow Jones industrial average climbed 13.22 to
2,206.43, its highest close since it stood at 2,246.74 on Oct. 16,
1987.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 4 to 3 on the
NYSE, with 802 up, 603 down and 534 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 148.95 million shares, against 140.42
million in the previous session.
</TEXT>
