<FIRST>u f PM-AlleghenyInternational     01-12 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Allegheny International,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Board Rejects Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The troubled small-appliance maker Allegheny
International Inc. said today it asked the federal bankruptcy court
to void a previously announced buyout plan by former ally Donaldson,
Lufkin &amp; Jenrette.
   The company, which has been operating under Chapter 11 federal
bankruptcy protection for nearly a year, advised the court that
instead it will submit its own reorganization plan.
   Allegheny International's board of directors voted to take such
action late Wednesday, citing the securities firm's deal with other
investors to carve up the consumer products company.
   The board's move, though, angered many of its creditors, who had
backed the Donaldson Lufkin plan.
   ``We're amazed and disappointed that the board, having postponed
a decision from November to December and then from December to
January has now rejected the sale route altogether,'' said Wilbur
Ross of Rothschild Inc., adviser to a committee of unsecured
creditors.
   Peter A. Joseph, a partner in the Paul S. Levy merchant banking
group in New York, which would have participated in the Donaldson
Lufkin takeover plan, also expressed disappointment.
   ``We were surprised, we're disappointed and we're examining our
options,'' he said.
   In a privately negotiated deal, the total value of which has not
been disclosed, the Levy group would have bought Allegheny
International's profitable lawn furniture and gas grill business for
about $250 million, according to published reports.
   The two groups were once competing bidders.
   The New York Times reported today that besides being taken back
by the new alignment, Allegheny International directors were upset
by a decision by Donaldson Lufkin to put $30 million less common
equity into the deal than it had earlier proposed.
   The board had announced a tentative merger agreement with
Donaldson Lufkin at the end of last year.
</TEXT>
