<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices pushed ahead today, extending the
early-1989 rally that has carried the market to its highest levels
since the 1987 crash.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 13.21 to 2,219.64
by 11 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 8 to 5 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 741 up, 438 down and
532 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 58.06 million shares at
midmorning.
   Analysts said traders were encouraged by the market's drive
Wednesday past the 2,200 level in the Dow after a week-long struggle.
   In addition, they cited a developing ``bandwagon'' effect as
investors who had been bearish on the outlook for months felt
increasing pressure to join in the rally.
   The market's steady advance since last fall has come without any
support from interest rates, which have been rising. The Federal
Reserve has continued to tighten credit, and many Wall Streeters
still believe the Fed might soon raise its discount rate.
   Among actively traded blue chips, Merck rose } to 59~;
International Business Machines ] to 122|; General Electric { to
44~; American Telephone &amp; Telegraph \ to 29[, and Ford Motor { to
53[.
   Ford lived up to traders' hopes, raising its quarterly dividend
from 60 to 75 cents a share.
   Greater New York Savings Bank jumped 2 to 11| in the
over-the-counter market. The company said Emigrant Savings Bank
proposed to acquire it for $16 a share.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.68 to 159.33. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up 1.13 at 314.99.
