<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   01-12 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Slide In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly lower
in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade in quiet
activity ahead of Friday's crop report from the Agriculture
Department.
   The report will contain final 1988 crop production totals, with
slight increases over the government's previous estimates expected
for both corn and soybeans.
   The report, which is due out after the close of trading on
Friday, also will contain new estimates of the nation's grain and
soybean stockpiles, an actual tally of 1988-89 winter wheat seedings
and estimates for 1989 corn and soybean acreage.
   In addition to bearish expectations for the report, analysts said
some of this morning's selling was prompted by indications of strong
farmer sales of grains and soybeans to commercial dealers during
December.
   ``Especially considering the good movement after the first of the
year, the commercials don't have to reach for anything in here at
all,'' said Dale Gustafson, an analyst in Chicago with Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc.
   In early trading, wheat was 4 cents to 5 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.39{ a bushel; corn was \ cent
to 2 cents lower with March at $2.84} a bushel; oats were } cent to
1{ cents lower with March at $2.35{ a bushel; soybeans were 2\ cents
lower to { cent higher with January at $7.96 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .08 cent to .25 cent higher with February at 74
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .08 cent to .10 cent higher with
January at 85 cents a pound; live hogs were .07 cent lower to .10
cent higher with February at 45.50 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were unchanged to .23 cent higher with February at 42.02
cents a pound.
   Cattle futures closed mixed on Wednesday while pork futures were
lower.
</TEXT>
