<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 1219EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     01-12 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Noon,0304</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices gained more ground today, extending
the early-1989 rally that has carried the market to its highest
levels since the 1987 crash.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 15.36 to 2,221.79
by noontime on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by nearly 9 to 5 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 807 up, 465 down and
533 unchanged.
   Analysts said traders were encouraged by the market's drive
Wednesday past the 2,200 level in the Dow after a week-long struggle.
   In addition, they cited a developing ``bandwagon'' effect as
investors who had been bearish on the outlook for months felt
increasing pressure to join in the rally.
   The market's steady advance since last fall has come without any
support from interest rates, which have been rising. The Federal
Reserve has continued to tighten credit, and many Wall Streeters
still believe the Fed might soon raise its discount rate.
   Among actively traded blue chips, Merck rose } to 59~;
International Business Machines 1\ to 123{; General Electric { to
44~; American Telephone &amp; Telegraph \ to 29[, and Ford Motor { to
53[.
   Ford lived up to traders' hopes, raising its quarterly dividend
from 60 to 75 cents a share.
   Greater New York Savings Bank jumped 1~ to 11{ in the
over-the-counter market. The company said Emigrant Savings Bank
proposed to acquire it for $16 a share.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.79 to 159.44. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up 1.34 at 315.20.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 90.14 million shares at noontime,
up from 67.23 million at the same point Wednesday.
