<FIRST>u f PM-Mexico-Union 1stLd-Writethru f0023 01-12 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Union, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0023,0655</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Boss Says Guns Found After Shootout Were Smuggled From U.S.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with arraignment. Pickup 3rd graf
pvs, At least ...; Also moved on general newswires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA SNOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief of Mexico's powerful oil workers
union was arraigned today on charges of illegal weapons possession,
homicide, gun smuggling and resisting arrest.
   The arrest Tuesday of Joaquin Hernandez Galicia prompted strikes
by union members that crippled the country's nationalized oil
industry for a day but ended Wednesday at a behest of a union
official.
   Hernandez Galicia was charged today before penal judge Jose Luis
Garcia Vasco, who has 72 hours to decide whether the accused should
be released on bail.
   On Wednesday night, Hernanadez Galicia claimed the 200 Uzi
machine guns seized in an assault on his home were smuggled from the
United States and needed by union leaders for self-defense,
officials said.
   At least 50 associates of the union boss arrested with him
Tuesday face charges of fraud, weapons and tax evasion, said
Fernando Arias Perez, a spokesman for the attorney general's office.
   A source in the office, who spoke on condition of anonymity, also
said that two of Hernandez Galicia's bodyguards on Wednesday accused
their boss of ordering the 1983 slaying of a mayor who headed a
union local.
   Tensions have long run high between Hernandez Galicia and newly
inaugurated President Carlos Salinas de Gortari, who has pledged to
sell or close unprofitable or non-strategic state industries.
   Hernandez Galicia's allegedly corrupt Mexican Oil Workers Union
controls more than half the lucrative drilling contracts issued by
the state oil monopoly, Pemex.
   Pemex Director Francisco Rojas told a news conference Wednesday
that the production of crude oil, gasoline and petrochemicals had
returned to normal.
   ``We are fulfilling all our exportation commitments to other
countries,'' he said. Mexico is the world's sixth-largest crude oil
producer, and production from the country's nine refineries amounts
to 1.4 million barrels a day.
   Victor de Leon, acting coordinator of the union, said the
back-to-work appeal had come from Salvador Barragan Camacho, the
union's secretary-general until Wednesday.
   The government news agency Notimex reported later that leaders of
the union's locals had designated Ricardo Camero Cardiel, a local
leader and senator from the northeastern city of Ciudad Madero, the
union's new secretary-general. Weapons were found at Barragan
Camacho's home and he was under arrest, officials said.
   Hernandez Galicia told investigators the Uzis and about 30,000
cartridges were secretly delivered to him on Dec. 10 by former
Reynosa Mayor Jose Cruz Contreras, the attorney general's office
said in a statement.
   Hernandez Galicia said the arms were ``to defend his union
members, given the existing situation in the country,'' the
statement said.
   The government has not said what it thinks Hernandez Galicia
planned to do with the weapons.
   Last week, the union chief threatened to paralyze the oil
industry if the government carried out a threat to sell Pemex
operations to private investors.
   Hernandez Galicia was arrested when soldiers blew down his door
with a bazooka in a raid on his Ciudad Madero home. A federal agent
was shot to death in the attack.
   A spokesman for the attorney general's office, Felipe Flores,
said a paraffin test performed on Hernandez Galicia showed he had
fired a gun. Flores did not elaborate.
   In his statement to investigators, Hernandez Galicia argued that
security forces had no right to force their way into his home.
   He said he had planned to distribute some of the Uzis to other
oil union leaders and said Cruz Contreras, whom he described as a
``good friend,'' did not charge him for the weapons and ammunition,
the attorney general's office said. It did not say where in the
United States the arms were bought.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
