<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 1252EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-InternationalPaper     01-12 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-International Paper,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>International Paper Posts Record Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PURCHASE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Paper Co., which posted a
record 85 percent increase in 1988 profit, announced Thursday it
plans to launch a takeover bid for Europe's largest paper maker.
   Details of the ``friendly'' tender offer for Aussedat-Rey SA,
Europe's leading manufacturer of photocopy paper, were not
disclosed. But Paris stock analysts estimated the bid at 650 to 700
French francs per share _ the equivalent of $104 to $113 based on
Thursday's exchange rates.
   Officials of the Paris-based company declined to comment on
whether the company would accept the offer.
   International Paper spokeswoman Ann Silvernail said that under
French law the company was barred from releasing details pending
government approval.
   International Paper is the world's largest manufacturer of paper
and paper products, with primary production facilities in Maine and
throughout the South and packaging plants in Europe, Asia and South
America. In addition to all types of business paper, the company
makes milk cartons, bottle labels and corrugated boxes. It does not
make newsprint.
   International Paper announced earlier this week that preliminary
figures show its earnings soared last year, due to strong demand and
high operating capacity.
   For the 12 months ended last Dec. 31, International Paper said
its net income totaled $754 million, or $6.57 a share, up from $407
million, or $3.68 a share, in 1987. The company's annual revenue
rose 22 percent to $9.5 billion from $7.8 billion in 1987.
   The company reported that its fourth-quarter net earnings jumped
65 percent to $206 million, or $1.81 a share, on sales of $2.5
billion. In the year-earlier quarter the company reported earnings
of $125 million, or $1.14 a share, on sales of $2 billion.
   ``Our white paper, market pulp and packaging businesses turned in
particularly impressive results in 1988,'' said John A. Georges,
International Paper's chairman and chief executive officer.
   Georges said that for the second year in a row, the company's
paper and paperboard mills operated at or near capacity.
   ``This strong level of demand led to higher prices on most of our
major product lines and we compounded the benefits by continuing to
emphasize cost reduction, customer service and quality,'' he said.
   Georges said the company planned to invest $900 million in 1989
to further modernize its facilities and would continue to search for
new investment opportunities.
</TEXT>
