<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 1548EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-InternationalLoans     01-12 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-International Loans,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>Banks Ask For Loan Guarantees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major commercial banks say they should receive
loan guarantees from governments or agencies like the World Bank
before they lend out any more money to debt-ridden Third World
countries.
   ``Creditor countries risk that some of these debtor countries
will default on their debt,'' explained Horst Schulmann, the West
German managing director of the Institute of International Finance.
``If this happens ... the banks of the creditor countries will
suffer heavy losses.''
   The institute, which represents 186 leading banks and other
private lenders around the world, issued a position paper on
Wednesday apparently aimed at influencing the Bush administration's
views on Third World debt.
   The paper said, ``There is a case for creditor governments and
the international financial institutions to provide assistance
possibly through guarantees of principal and interest.''
   Former Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III, the choice of
President-elect Bush to become secretary of state, has strongly
opposed official guarantees because they transfer to taxpayers the
risks taken by private lenders.
   The World Bank, which is owned by 151 governments, estimates that
Third World countries now owe $1.3 trillion, more than $540 billion
of it to private lenders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890112-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 1516EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-Banks     01-12 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Banks,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chemical Reports Jump In 4th Qtr Profit, Record Annual Income</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Chemical Banking Corp., one of the nation's largest banking
companies, on Thursday reported a 26 percent jump in its
fourth-quarter profit and record earnings for 1988.
   The company attributed those gains partly to a decrease in its
provision for future loan losses from Third World countries and
past-due interest payments from Brazil.
   Net income for the three months ended Dec. 31 totaled $288.5
million, or $4.66 a share, up from $229.6 million, or $3.83 a share,
the same time a year earlier.
   The 1987 quarterly earnings included a $126.4 million pre-tax
gain on a pension settlement and $25.6 million from the sale of
Chemical's factoring business.
   For the year, Chemical's profit totaled a record $753.6 million,
or $12.02 a share, compared with a year-earlier loss of $853.7
million.
   The 1988 figures included pre-tax gains of $53.8 million on the
settlement of a portion of its pension obligations and $41.3 million
on the sale or closure of non-strategic businesses and the receipt
of about $161 million in past-due interest from Brazil from Feb. 20,
1987 to Sept. 30, 1988.
   The 1987 earnings reflected the company's decision to add nearly
$1.5 billion to its loan-loss provision at the peak of the Third
World debt crisis. During that year Brazil had placed a moratorium
on interest payments to commercial banks.
   In 1988, Chemical added around $364 million to its loan-loss
provision, including $81 million in the final quarter. The 1987
fourth-quarter provision was $108 million.
   Chemical said fourth-quarter operating earnings reflected
increases in corporate finance fees, earnings from equity affiliates
and declines in non-interest expense, as well as the smaller
loan-loss provision.
   It said a drop in net interest income, bond trading and
foreign-exchange profits helped partially offset those gains.
   The huge profit for 1988 was largely attributed to an increase in
net interest income, corporate finance fees, profits from bond
trading and the lower loan-loss provision.
   The 1988 results also included full-year earnings from Texas
Commerce Bancshares Inc., which merged with Chemical in May 1987.
Texas Commerce earned $2.1 million last year, compared with a $120.3
million loss in 1987, Chemical said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
