<DOCNO> AP890112-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 0658EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-SpyCameraWoes Adv14-15   01-12 0655</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Spy Camera Woes, Adv 14-15,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 14</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions Jan. 14-15 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Maker of World Famous Miniature Cameras Fights to Stay Afloat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GIESSEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The maker of Minox miniature
cameras, the ``spy cameras'' made famous in an early James Bond
movie, has racked up big losses, sought bankruptcy-court protection
and cut its workforce by 50 percent in a struggle to stay in the
Japanese-dominated market.
   Minox's woes are just part of the restructuring of West Germany's
proud camera industry, which has seen the only other two all-German
companies, Leica and Rollei, drop out of the amateur automatic focus
camera market to concentrate on producing high-priced professional
gear.
   Minox, which continues to pursue the amateur photographer market
in tough competition with Japan's producers, is based in the central
West German town of Heuchelheim near Giessen, about 40 miles north
of Frankfurt.
   The so-called ``spy camera'' used in the 1963 James Bond movie
``From Russia With Love'' can be concealed in the palm or easily
slipped into a normal pocket. A newer version, the Minox EC, is even
smaller, about as long and thick as a normal index finger, and not
more that two-fingers wide.
   Ludwig Rinn, who died in 1942, invented the tiny camera in 1938
in Riga, Latvia, in what is now the Soviet Union. His descendants
founded the Minox company in Heuchelheim on Jan. 3, 1949.
   Exactly 40 years later, Minox filed for bankruptcy-court
protection and a court-appointed executive entrusted with running
the company cut 220 of its 564 employees. The reduction followed a
cut of 186 employees last April.
   ``This is really hurting Heuchelheim,'' the town's mayor Willi
Marx told The Associated Press in an interview at his office earlier
this month.
   ``Not only the jobs, but also the taxes. We may have to reduce
some town services,'' the mayor said. The town has a population of
7,500.
   Loss of the jobs also means small businesses in Heuchelheim will
lose the customers who used to go shopping there after work, Marx
said.
   ``But I guess the worst part is the months of uncertainty that
the families have gone through for the past months. Some have spent
their whole lives at Minox, others had grandfathers and fathers who
also worked there,'' he said.
   Minox has not shown a profit since 1981, and on April 1, 1988,
Robert C. Corduwener, a Netherlands businessman bought a 51 percent
share of the company to take control from the Rinn family.
   Corduwener immediately cut the workforce to streamline the
operation, but even with $40 million in sales in 1988, the company
lost $3.4 million for the year. Its debts swelled to $25.7 million.
   Despite forecasts that business was rebounding with three months
of orders to fill on its new 35 GT-E and 35 AF (Automatic Focus)
cameras, the company's applications for short-term bank loans were
rejected.
   Employees took out private loans to tide them over during
November and December because Minox had no money for salaries. They
worked extra shifts to fill contract obligations and keep the firm
in operation, mayor Marx said.
   Many had hoped their loyality would convince the banks, primarily
the Frankfurt-based Commerzbank and Giessen's Bezirksparkasse bank,
to continue to help Minox, but the hope backfired on those who were
layed off, he said.
   While Minox is struggling, the Leica company in nearby Wetzlar,
and Rollei in Braunschweig, report business has been good over the
past year.
   Leica spokesman Hans Guenther von Zydowitz told the AP company
officals estimate last year's sales at about $60.6 million, but he
declined to estimate profits.
   Spokesman Dietmar Kanzer of the smaller Rollei company, which
employs about 270 people, told the AP the firm had great success
with its new Roliflex 6008 camera in 1988. He estimated 1988 sales
at $20 million but also declined to estimate profits.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Jan. 14-15</NOTE>
</DOC>
