<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   01-12 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Finish Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices finished mixed
Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade as traders adjusted their
positions ahead of Friday's crop report from the Agriculture
Department.
   Wheat futures finished mostly lower for the third consecutive
session amid jitters about an expected increase over last year in
winter wheat plantings. The figure is the most eagerly awaited
statistic in the USDA report, and analysts' estimates have varied
widely.
   ``It could be something that could break the back of the
market,'' said Ted Mao, an analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
in New York.
   ``Everbody expects an increase; the question is what the
magnitude of the increase is,'' Mao said. ``It could be a lot higher
than people expect.''
   The crop report, due out after Friday's close of trading, also
will contain the USDA's final 1988 crop production totals, new
estimates of the nation's grain and soybean stockpiles and estimates
for 1989 corn and soybean acreage.
   At the close, wheat was 3{ cents lower to 1 cent higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.41 a bushel; corn was } cent
lower to 1\ cents higher with March at $2.86 a bushel; oats were {
cent lower to 1} cents higher with March at $2.37} a bushel;
soybeans were 2{ cents lower to 1\ cents higher with January at
$7.98 a bushel.
</TEXT>
