<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 0647EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d f BC-Poland-Coal     01-12 0108</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Poland-Coal,0113</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poland Seeks To End Coal Exports By Year 2000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government expects to virtually end
coal exports by the year 2000 because of rising domestic demand and
increasing costs of extraction, Industry Minister Mieczyslaw Wilczek
said Wednesday.
   Poland, now the world's fifth-largest coal exporter, will instead
try to increase exports of other products, Wilczek said.
   He said Poland has been struggling to keep production as high as
190 million tons of coal annually and it is not economically
feasible to increase extraction. Meanwhile, he said, demand for
energy is increasing in Poland and the country has few other
significant energy resources.
</TEXT>
