<FIRST>d f BC-PhoneRefund     01-12 0155</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Phone Refund,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pacific Bell Pays Out $94.5 Million In Penalties, Refunds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Because of improper phone service charges,
uncovered in a secret PUC probe, Pacific Bell has paid out $94.5
million in penalties and refunds to 491,000 customers, the utility
says.
   Company officials said Tuesday $63 million in charges billed to
customers for services they did not order or need were refunded
between September 1986 and November 1988.
   The utility spent another $15 million to notify 8.5 million
customers about the refunds, and yet another $16.5 million in
penalties levied by the Public Utilities Commission.
   The PUC reported that an undercover staff investigation disclosed
that Pacific Bell representatives, among other things, often added
optional features such as call-waiting and call-forwarding to bills
although they hadn't been ordered.
   The phone company said it will continue to offer the refunds to
customers who received unwanted services between January 1985 and
October 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
