<DOCNO> AP890112-0265 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 1643EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Britain-GEC Bjt   01-12 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-GEC, Bjt,0632</SECOND>
<HEAD>GEC, Siemens Temporarily Blocked From Plessey Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British government on Thursday temporarily
barred General Electric Co. PLC and Siemens AG from proceeding with
their hostile, $3.6 billion takeover bid for British defense
contractor Plessey Co.
   Trade Secretary Lord Young said he referred the bid to the
Monopolies and Mergers Commission to determine its effects on
competition, particularly in defense electronics and air traffic
control equipment.
   Young asked the commission to make its recommendation within
three months. During that time the bidders cannot proceed with their
offer and are limited to a Plessey holding of under 15 percent.
   Following the ruling, the British and German partners raised
their stake in Plessey to about 14.9 percent from about 3 percent.
   Meanwhile, in Brussels, Belgium, the European Commission said it
would investigate the joint bid, which might break Common Market
competition rules.
   The commission was requesting information from the companies
involved and hoped to complete the inquiry ``as soon as possible,''
said a spokesman for Leon Brittan, a Briton who is the new European
commissioner for competition policy.
   The developments came amid expectations that a newly formed
international consortium, expected to include Plessey, would make a
bid for GEC, a British electronics giant that is unrelated to the
similarly named U.S. company.
   The potential bid for GEC was expected to be worth between $11.6
billion and $14.3 billion, which would make it the largest takeover
ever on London's Stock Exchange.
   Such a counterbid would be what Wall Street calls a ``Pac Man''
defense because of its similarity to the eat-or-be-eaten video game.
   After the British government's announcement, GEC and Siemens paid
$4.39 a share in a midmorning raid that increased their joint stake
in GEC to the maximum allowed, said Barclays de Zoete Wedd Ltd.,
broker to the companies.
   By paying $4.39 a share for Plessey stock, the bidders are forced
by British takeover rules to raise their offer to at least that
price if they get clearance to proceed.
   A bid at that price would value the whole of Plessey at about
$3.3 billion.
   The previous offer of $4.03 a share, which automatically lapsed,
valued Plessey at $3 billion.
   GEC and Siemens, a West German electronics maker, said they would
cooperate with the British inquiry ``in the belief that the proposed
merger will be allowed to proceed in due course.''
   Plessey shares finished 13 cents higher at $4.17 on London's
Stock Exchange. GEC shares ended up 4 cents at $3.85.
   The GEC-Siemens bid has come under heavy political pressure in
Britain and a referral to the mergers commission had been considered
likely. The government blocked a solo bid from GEC for Plessey in
1986, saying it would harm competition in the British defense
electronics market.
   But many analysts expect the government to allow it to proceed
this time.
   Plessey, meanwhile, said it would not relax its attempts to fight
the GEC-Siemens bid.
   John Clark, Plessey's chairman and chief executive officer, said
his company would explore various means to maximize shareholder
benefits. The statement was believed to be a reference to Plessey's
expected role in the efforts to build a consortium bid for GEC.
   Metsun Ltd., a shell company set up to lead any bid for GEC, said
talks on a possible offer were continuing. The offer would lead to
the breakup of GEC and the sale some of its businesses.
   Analysts said the investigations could hinder the negotiations,
which are being conducted by Plessey's adviser, Lazard Brothers and
Co., because the referral indicated that any further bid in the
industry also would be referred to the commission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
