<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 1649EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-GAF     01-12 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GAF,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Declines to Block Second Trial in Stock Manipulation
Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court rejected defense
arguments Thursday to prevent a second trial in the
stock-manipulation case against GAF Corp. and a key company officer,
two days after a mistrial was declared.
   The ruling by the 2nd Circuit Court of Appeals after a brief
hearing means jury selection for a new trial will commence next
Tuesday in U.S. District Judge Mary Johnson Lowe's court, lawyers
involved in the case said.
   Lowe decreed a mistrial Tuesday in the first major case arising
from the Wall Street insider trading scandal to reach the trial
phase. She based the ruling on a prosecutorial blunder in handling a
key piece of evidence.
   The judge ordered a new trial, but lawyers for the chemical
company and vice chairman James Sherwin appealed on grounds of
double jeopardy, the legal principle that protects defendants from
two trials for the same offense.
   Defense lawyers routinely object to new trials when mistrials are
declared, but the strategy's success depends on the circumstances of
the case.
   In instances of prosecutorial misconduct, the defense generally
has to prove that prosecutors deliberately provoked a mistrial
because they feared they would lose and wanted a second chance.
   But Judge Lowe said she believed the prosecution's mistake in the
GAF case was unintentional, which weighed heavily in the appeals
court's support of her decision to proceed with a new trial.
   GAF and Sherwin were indicted in July for an alleged scheme to
manipulate up the price of Union Carbide Corp. stock in order to
maximize GAF's gain from the sale of Carbide shares it wished to
sell after a failed takeover attempt.
   The prosecution has based its case largely on the testimony of
ex-broker Boyd L. Jefferies, whose Los Angeles-based securities firm
conducted the alleged manipulation on GAF's behalf. Jefferies
himself was implicated in wrongdoing by inside trader Ivan F.
Boesky, who is now imprisoned.
</TEXT>
