<FIRST>u f AM-MoneyFunds     01-12 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Funds,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rose $4.36 Billion in Latest Week to Record High</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report
are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 453 money market mutual
funds rose $4.36 billion in the latest week to an all-time high of
$282.4 billion, the Investment Company Institute said Thursday.
   The rise in the seven-day period ended Wednesday followed a
$449.5 million drop in fund assets the previous week, the
Washington-based mutual fund trade group said.
   ``In a sharp reversal of the end-of-the-year decline, assets of
money market funds staged an impressive advance to reach an all-time
high record,'' said Jacob Dreyer, vice president and chief economist
of the group.
   The new record eclipses the previous all-time high of $281.89
billion reported in the week ended Nov. 23.
   The biggest weekly rise in the funds' assets _ $9.64 billion in
the week ended Oct. 21, 1987 _ came during the stock market collapse
as investors sought safe havens for their money.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 225 general purpose funds rose $239.5 million to $90.17
billion, assets of 91 broker-dealer funds rose $3.61 billion to
$119.28 billion, and assets of 137 institutional funds rose $519.2
million to $72.94 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds fell in
the week ended Tuesday to 8.28 percent from 8.39 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield rose to 8.22 percent from 8.14 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was 30
days, up from 29 days, Donoghue's said.
   The newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of 100 leading
commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and savings banks in
the nation's 10 largest markets showed the effective annual yield
available on money market accounts rose to 6.24 percent as of
Wednesday from 6.22 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super NOW
accounts, rose to 5.14 percent from 5.13 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 8.26
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 8.21 the
previous week. Yields were 8.51 percent on 1-year CDs, up from 8.48
percent; 8.63 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 8.58 percent; and 8.75
percent on 5-year CDs, up from 8.71 percent.
</TEXT>
