<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rolled up their sixth gain in the
past seven sessions Thursday, extending the early-1989 rally that
has carried the market to its highest levels since the 1987 crash.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 15.89 points to
2,222.32 _ less than 25 points shy of its close of 2,246.74 on Oct.
16, 1987, just before it took a 508-point drop on Black Monday.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by more than 3 to 2 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
907 up, 586 down and 496 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 183 million shares,
up from 148.95 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in those
stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market,
totaled 215.92 million shares.
   Analysts said traders were encouraged by the market's drive
Wednesday past the 2,200 level in the Dow after a week-long struggle.
   In addition, they cited a developing ``bandwagon'' effect as
investors who had been bearish on the outlook for months felt
increasing pressure to join in the rally.
   The market's steady advance since last fall has come without any
support from interest rates, which have been rising. The Federal
Reserve has continued to tighten credit, and many Wall Streeters
still believe the Fed might soon raise its discount rate.
   Among actively traded blue chips, Merck rose } to 59~;
International Business Machines ~ to 123[; General Electric | to 45;
American Telephone &amp; Telegraph \ to 29[, and Ford Motor \ to 52~.
   Ford lived up to traders' hopes, raising its quarterly dividend
from 60 to 75 cents a share.
   Elsewhere, Kollmorgen gained 2] to 24. The company asked its
holders to take no action on Vernitron Corp.'s offer of $23 a share
until Kollmorgen directors study the bid and make a recommendation
on whether the accept or reject it.
   Dexter Corp., the subject of rumors about a possible takeover or
restructuring, picked up 2\ to 25}. The company said it had no news
pending to account for the activity.
   Novo Industri rose 3 to 42{. The company plans to merge with
Nordisk Gentofte, another Danish concern.
   Greater New York Savings Bank jumped 2\ to 11~ in the
over-the-counter market. The company said Emigrant Savings Bank
proposed to acquire it for $16 a share.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $10.20 billion, or 0.37
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks added
.61 to 159.26.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose 1.70 to 327.99, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index was up 1.16 at 283.17.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market gained
1.70 to 387.01. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 315.00, up 1.14.
