<HEAD>London Shares End Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity, closing index;
No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices finished broadly higher in brisk
trading Thursday on the London Stock Exchange, with the market's
advances led by heavy activity in electrical stocks as well as by an
early rally on Wall Street.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed 16.8
points, or 0.9 percent, higher at 1,850.9, its best level for the
day. At its minimum, the index was up just 0.5 point shortly after
the start of trading.
   The market has shown persistent strength in recent sessions, with
the 100-share index gaining nearly 70 points since Tuesday of last
week.
   ``The market just doesn't want to go down,'' one dealer said.
   The Financial Times 30-share index rose 13.1 points to 1,511.9 at
the close. The Financial Times 500-share index rose 8.92 points to
close at 1,041.79.
   Volume was heavy, expanding to 791.3 million shares from
Wednesday's 581.3 million.
   A large portion of Thursday's turnover was in Plessey Co., whose
shares were snatched up in a midmorning raid.
   A joint venture of Britain's General Electric Co. PLC and West
Germany's Siemens AG bought about 89 million Plessey shares shortly
after Trade Secretary Lord Young referred their bid for Plessey to
the Monopolies and Mergers Commission for a study of its impact on
competition.
   Market excitement faded shortly after midday once the GEC-Siemens
buying spree ended, as the companies approached the limit of 14.9
percent of Plessey shares that British authorities imposed.
   But the market picked up again as Wall Street pushed ahead in
early trading. As London trading finished, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 16.43 points at 2,222.86.
</TEXT>
