<FIRST>u f AM-AlleghenyInternational Bjt   01-12 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Allegheny International, Bjt,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plans to End Merger Pact, Sell Oster-Sunbeam to Black &amp; Decker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegheny International Inc. announced plans
Thursday to cancel a merger agreement with a New York securities
firm in favor of a deal to sell its core Oster-Sunbeam division to
Black &amp; Decker Corp. for $260 million.
   The proposed sale is the centerpiece of an independent plan of
reorganization that management intends to present in bankruptcy
court, where creditors had backed the proposal from the securities
firm Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Inc.
   The company also said it entered a letter of intent with Spear,
Leeds &amp; Kellog, head of a shareholders' committee that had
previously battled management, to finance management's plan.
   The Oster-Sunbeam division makes a range of small household
appliances, including shavers, mixers and other kitchen appliances.
   Black &amp; Decker, based in Towson, Md., manufactures and sells
power tools, accessories, household appliances and lawn care
equipment.
   Under management's plan, Allegheny International would be left
with businesses that include lawn furniture, gas grills, electric
blankets, scales and clocks, among other things.
   ``The consensus is they just abdicated,'' unsecured creditors'
counsel Robert Sable said after the board confirmed published
reports that it voted down the Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette plan on
Wednesday.
   ``It's time the creditors take control of the case,'' he said.
   In voting to cancel its earlier tentative merger agreement with
Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette, the board cited the securities firm's
subsequent arrangement with a rival bidder, the Paul S. Levy
merchant banker group, to carve up the company between them.
   Allegheny International said it would ask U.S. Bankruptcy Court
for sanctions against Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette and against the
Levy group.
   In its latest version, the Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette plan
would have sold Allegheny International's lawn furniture and gas
grill business to the Levy group for about $250 million, according
to the Wall Street Journal.
   Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette would have retained the
Oster-Sunbeam division.
   In another late change, Donaldson Lufkin &amp; Jenrette would have
put $30 million less common equity into the deal than it had earlier
proposed, according to the New York Times.
   Allegheny International said Thursday it had asked the bankruptcy
court to void the agreement with Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette.
   ``We were surprised, we're disappointed and we're examining our
options,'' said Peter A. Joseph, a partner in the Levy group.
   ``We're amazed and disappointed that the board, having postponed
a decision from November to December and then from December to
January has now rejected the sale route altogether,'' said Wilbur
Ross of Rothschild Inc., an adviser to the unsecured creditors.
   The board announced a tentative merger agreement with Donaldson,
Lufkin &amp; Jenrette last November after the major creditor groups shot
down an earlier reorganization plan from management and forced the
board to offer the company for sale.
   Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette and Levy both made independent
buyout proposals. The board twice endorsed the securities firm's
offer, only to withdraw support when Levy sweetened its bid.
   Both plans would have repaid creditors nearly in full. Donaldson,
Lufkin &amp; Jenrette would have given stockholders 40 percent of the
reorganized company, which would have closely resembled the current
Allegheny International.
   The Levy group would have given shareholders 49 percent equity in
what was left after selling the Oster-Sunbeam unit to reduce debt.
</TEXT>
