<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Rise</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against most major currencies
Thursday but its increase was modest, a sign of the success of
central banks' efforts to halt its recent ascent. Gold prices rose.
   Foreign-exchange dealers said trading was cautious in the
aftermath of Wednesday's concerted dollar-selling by the Federal
Reserve and at least eight other central banks.
   ``They (central banks) have in fact capped the dollar,'' said
Marc Cohen, a vice president of Republic National Bank of New York.
But Cohen said there was strong support for the dollar at current
levels, meaning the currency is ``trapped'' for now in a narrow
trading range.
   ``The market just seemed to be settling in ranges,'' said Robert
Ryan, corporate foreign-exchange manager for Irving Trust Co.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7880 late Thursday, more
expensive for buyers that Wednesday's late $1.7815. Later in New
York, the pound weakened against the dollar and was quoted at
$1.7850, down from $1.7866 late Wednesday.
   The dollar closed at 126.12 Japanese yen in Tokyo, down from
126.95 yen Wednesday. Later in London the dollar was trading
slightly higher at 126.15 yen. In New York, the dollar rose to
126.38 yen from 125.82 yen late Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Wednesday's
late rates, included: 1.8268 West German marks, up from 1.8255;
1.5559 Swiss francs, up from 1.5529; 1.1972 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.2013; 6.2280 French francs, up from 6.2240; and 1,344 Italian
lire, up from 1,341.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe, compared with
Wednesday's late rates, included: 1.8355 West German marks, up from
1.8280; 1.5510 Swiss francs, down from 1.5550; 6.2150 French francs,
down from 6.2270; 2.0590 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0595; 1,339.50
Italian lire, up from 1,337.50; and 1.1957 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.2003.
   Gold bullion prices were up by around $1 a troy ounce but traders
said the market lacked sparkle and Middle East customers stayed away
after buying earlier in the week.
   Gold closed in Hong Kong at $406.36 a troy ounce bid, up from
$404.48 an ounce.
   The closing price in London, the major market, was $404.50 bid a
troy ounce, up from $403.50. The closing price in Zurich,
Switzerland, was $404.20 an ounce bid, up from $403.30.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery rose to $404.50 a troy ounce from $403.40 Wednesday. Later,
Republic National Bank of New York said gold was bid at $404.20 an
ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, up from $403.65 late Wednesday.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $5.95 an ounce bid a troy
ounce, up from $5.94 late Wednesday. On New York's Comex, silver
bullion for current delivery fell to $5.916 an ounce from $5.921.
