<FIRST>r f AM-BearStearns     01-12 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bear Stearns,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bear Stearns Posts Highest Quarterly Profit; Announces Stock Buyback</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At a time when many securities firms have
suffered an earnings slump, Bear Stearns Cos. Inc. announced the
best quarterly earnings in its history Thursday, more than a
125-fold gain over the year earlier period.
   Bear Stearns also said it would repurchase up to 4.8 percent of
its stock in the next four weeks, which analysts called a reflection
of self-confidence in an era largely colored by post-crash
uncertainty.
   The company said earnings for the second quarter ended Dec. 31
increased to $63.3 million from $500,000 in the comparable period of
1987. Per-share earnings totaled 73 cents, vs. none a year earlier
because of special payments to preferred shareholders.
   Revenue for the quarter totaled $624.6 million, up 41 percent
from the $442 million for the same period a year earlier.
   For the six months ended Dec. 31, Bear Stearns reported earnings
of $83.8 million or 94 cents a share, up 206 percent from $27.4
million or 26 cents a share a year earlier.
   Revenue for the six-month period totaled $1.1 billion, up from
$906.6 million for the same period a year earlier.
   Many Wall Street firms involved primarily in retail brokerage
posted lackluster results last year, reflecting a flight from stocks
following the October 1987 crash. However, firms involved primarily
in investment banking, such as financing corporate takeovers, fared
better.
   Bear Stearns said results for the latest quarter reflected strong
performance in ``principal transaction'' business _ management of
its own money _ and its investment banking activities.
   The firm would not provide figures for the retail business, one
of Bear Stearns' six areas of operation, but analysts said it was
doing poorly.
   ``Some of the decisions made in October 1987 (not to retrench
after the crash) are starting to have a very positive impact on our
bottom line,'' said Alan C. Greenberg, the chairman and chief
executive officer.
   ``We are particularly proud that our head count is approximately
the same as it was before October 1987 and we have not eliminated
any lines of business,'' he said, alluding to layoffs and cutbacks
at competitors.
   Bear Stearns has about 6,000 employees in 13 offices worldwide.
   Under the stock repurchase plan, Bear Stearns said it will buy
back up to 4 million of its shares by Feb. 10, approximately 4.8
percent of the total amount outstanding, at a cost of between $12.25
to $14 a share.
   Bear Stearns stock closed at $13.25 a share Thursday on the New
York Stock Exchange, down 50 cents from Wednesday.
   The company said it considered the stock buyback an attractive
investment and an appropriate use of available cash.
   Bear Stearns was a partnership before it went public in October
1985, and about half its stock is owned by current and former
employees, said Brenda Davis McCoy, a stock analyst at PaineWebber
Inc. She called the stock buyback ``a vote of confidence'' in the
company.
   Bear Stearns also announced it had increased its quarterly
dividend on common stock to 14 cents a share from 12{ cents, payable
March 15.
</TEXT>
