<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 1800EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MoneySupply     01-12 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Supply,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Supply Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two broadest measures of the nation's money
supply rose in the week ended Jan. 2, the Federal Reserve Board
reported Thursday. The growth in money supply in 1988 was within the
Fed's target range.
   The Fed said the measure known as M2 rose $3.1 billion to a
seasonally adjusted $3,068.7 billion from $3,065.6 billion the
previous week.
   An even broader measure, M3, increased $4.7 billion to a
seasonally adjusted $3,905.0 billion from $3,900.3 billion.
   M2 grew 5.4 percent and M3 grew 6.3 percent in 1988, according to
a comparison of the last 13 weeks of 1988 with the last 13 weeks of
1987. The Fed had aimed at growth of 4 percent to 8 percent in the
two money supply measures in the year.
   The narrowest measure of the money supply, M1, rose $6.7 billion
to a seasonally adjusted $793.1 billion from $786.4 billion. Its
growth in 1988 was 4.3 percent.
   M1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts
and non-bank travelers checks. M2 is M1 plus accounts like savings
deposits and money-market mutual funds. M3 is M2 plus less-liquid
accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations
of $100,000.
   In judging its monetary policy, the Fed has indicated it is
monitoring the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the
difference between short- and long-term interest rates. It also has
shifted its attention from M1 to the two broader money supply
measures.
   The Fed said in mid-1988 that it reaffirmed its target for annual
growth in M2 and M3 at between 4 percent and 8 percent, which is
slightly lower than the 1987 target of 5.5 percent to 8.5 percent.
The Fed has not set a specific target range for M1 since early 1987.
   The Fed has tentatively set a target of M2 growth of 3 percent to
7 percent and M3 growth of 3.5 to 7.5 percent in 1989. There again
is no target for M1 growth.
   For the latest 13 weeks, M2 averaged $3,053.6 billion, a 3.0
percent seasonally adjusted annual rate of gain from the previous 13
weeks. M3 averaged $3,888.1 billion, up 4.2 percent, while M1 rose
1.2 percent to an average of $785.2 billion.
   In other reports:
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of New York reported commercial and
industrial loans at major New York City banks rose $663 million in
the week ended Jan. 4, compared with a gain of $173 million a week
earlier.
   _The Federal Reserve said bank borrowings from the Federal
Reserve System at the discount window, excluding extended credit,
averaged $309 million a day in the week ended Wednesday, down from
$1.372 billion in the previous week.
   _The Federal Reserve said net free reserves totaled $151 million
in the two-week period ended Jan. 11, down from a revised $741
million in the previous two-week period.
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis reported that the monetary
base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank reserves held at
Federal Reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and in circulation,
was $287.9 billion in the two-week period ended Wednesday, up from
$285.0 billion two weeks earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
