<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     01-12 0778</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0806</SECOND>
<HEAD>Copper Futures Surge On Renewed Supply Fears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices surged Thursday on New York's Commodity
Exchange amid signs of tightening supplies and production problems
against a backdrop of steady demand.
   On other markets, precious metals finished mixed; coffee futures
ended higher; grains and soybeans were mixed; energy futures were
mostly higher; cattle futures were higher; pork futures were mixed;
and stock-index futures advanced.
   Copper settled 0.30 cent to 4.35 cents higher with the spot price
at $1.489 a pound and the most active futures contract, for delivery
in March, at $1.379 a pound.
   The advance followed five straight days of declines in both the
spot price and the March contract.
   Analysts said buying interest was piqued by the Commodity
Exchange's report of a 500-ton decline Wednesday in inventories of
copper for delivery against futures contracts. The decline, which
brought the exchange's warehouse stocks to 12,459 tons, indicated
strong demand for immediate delivery of copper, they said.
   Further buying was linked to rumors that the Chilean copper
company Codelco was considering shutting down its smelter at
Chuquicamata, the world's largest copper mine, due to persistent
mechanical problems, said Fred Demler, metals economist with Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York.
   Chile, the world's top copper producer in 1987, fell short of its
1988 production goal by 85 tons due to production problems, Demler
said.
   He said labor problems had resurfaced in Peru, the world's
sixth-largest copper producer, where a 57-day miners' strike late
last year contributed to a 100,000-ton drop in annual copper
production.
   And copper production in Zambia and Zaire, the fourth- and
fifth-largest producers, fell by 135,000 metric tons last year due
to mechanical and transportation difficulties, he said.
   Meanwhile, copper consumption is at its seasonal peak, and
projections for continued economic expansion in the United States,
Japan and Western Europe suggest that strong demand for the metal
will continue, analysts said.
   ``It's a very tight market,'' Demler said.
   Analyst Scott Hinton of Elders Futures Inc. said the copper
market seemed unsinkable, even though prices have fallen from the
record highs reached in early December.
   Gold advanced marginally while silver futures fell for the fourth
straight day on the Commodity Exchange.
   Gold settled 50 cents to 60 cents higher with February at $405.80
a troy ounce; silver was 0.5 cent to 1.5 cents lower with March at
$5.985 a troy ounce.
   Coffee futures ended higher in a day of volatile trading on New
York's Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange following a dramatic plunge on
Wednesday.
   Coffee settled 0.5 cent to 3.3 cents higher with March at $1.4211
a pound.
   Grain and soybean futures finished mixed on the Chicago Board of
Trade as traders adjusted their positions ahead of Friday's crop
report from the Agriculture Department.
   Wheat futures finished mostly lower for the third consecutive
session amid jitters about an expected increase over last year in
winter wheat plantings. The figure is the most eagerly awaited
statistic in the USDA report, and analysts' estimates have varied
widely.
   The crop report, due out after Friday's close of trading, also
will contain the USDA's final 1988 crop production totals, new
estimates of the nation's grain and soybean stockpiles and estimates
for 1989 corn and soybean acreage.
   Wheat settled 3\ cents lower to { cent higher with March at
$4.41\ a bushel; corn was } cent lower to 1{ cents higher with March
at $2.86 a bushel; oats were { cent lower to 1} cents higher with
March at $2.37} a bushel; soybeans were 2{ cents lower to 1\ cents
higher with January at $7.98{ a bushel.
   Most energy futures prices finished moderately higher on the New
York Mercantile Exchange after falling earlier in the day.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 3 cents to 18 cents
higher with February at $18.17 a barrel; heating oil was .85 cent
lower to .30 cent higher with February at 52.84 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .50 cent to .74 cent higher with February at
49.27 cents a gallon.
   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, live cattle settled .10 cent
to .22 cent higher with February at 74.02 cents a pound; feeder
cattle were unchanged to .40 cent higher with January at 85.05 cents
a pound; live hogs were .20 cent lower to .30 cent higher with
February at 45.57 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .47 cent
to .87 cent higher with February at 42.70 cents a pound.
   Stock-index futures advanced modestly on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for March delivery of the Standard &amp;
Poor's 500 index settled .85 point higher at 285.25. Each point is
worth $500.
</TEXT>
