<FIRST>u f AM-Chris-Craft     01-12 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chris-Craft,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Offer To Buy Boat Maker Receives Tentative Approval</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRADENTON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Murray Industries Inc., the parent of
Murray Chris-Craft Boat Cos., announced Thursday it had given
tentative approval to an offer from Genmar Industries Inc. to buy a
substantial part of the assets of the financially troubled boat
maker.
   The offer was accepted subject to receipt of court and regulatory
approval and any higher or better offer, said Chris-Craft
spokeswoman Mary Glass. Terms of the offer were not disclosed.
   Murray Industries Inc. and its affiliates filed for protection
from creditors Dec. 9 under Chapter 11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code.
   Murray expects to seek approval from a bankruptcy judge for the
transaction Friday and anticipates court consideration in early
February, said Ms. Glass.
   Early approval would permit Genmar to produce the 1989 model line
of Chris-Craft boats, she said.
   Chris-Craft, the nation's oldest pleasure boat maker, makes
recreational powerboats ranging from 17-foot ski boats to 50-foot
yachts. It is not connected with Chris Craft Industries Inc., the
New York-based media company.
   Genmar, a division of Minstar Inc. of Minneapolis, is a
diversified manufacturer of recreational powerboats that sell under
the trademarks Wellcraft, Hatteras, Larson, Glastron, Lund,
Crestliner and Cajun.
</TEXT>
