<FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 2007EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Newspapers-Sale 1stLd-Writethru   01-12 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Newspapers-Sale, 1st Ld-Writethru,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Knight-Ridder Plans To Sell Two Daily Newspapers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after the 2nd graf with no comment on asking
price.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Knight-Ridder Inc. on Thursday announced plans to
sell two of its daily newspapers _ the Star-News in Pasadena,
Calif., and the Post-Tribune in Gary, Ind.
   The company has owned the Star-News since 1956. The Post-Tribune
was purchased in 1966. Knight-Ridder will be represented in the sale
of the two newspapers by Goldman-Sachs.
   Knight-Ridder declined to reveal any asking price for the papers.
   ``The decision to sell these two newspapers was not an easy
one,'' said James K. Batten, Knight-Ridder president and chief
executive officer. ``Both papers have excellent leadership teams and
fine editors, writers and executives throughout their organizations.
But it is important to our shareholders and the future of our
organization that its individual components fit the overall
strategic and growth needs of Knight-Ridder.''
   Batten said an analysis of the company's holdings led management
to conclude that Knight-Ridder would benefit from selling the two
newspapers.
   ``Proceeds will be used to reduce the company's debt, repurchase
the company's stock or make strategic acquisitions,'' Batten said.
   ``We will be most inclined to consider offers from American
publishers who recognize the full value of these newspapers and
whose track records suggest that they would take seriously the
newspapers' responsibility to readers, advertisers and the
communities to be served,'' Batten said.
   Also on Thursday, Knight-Ridder announced that it has named Larry
Jinks publisher of the San Jose Mercury News, succeeding William A.
Ott, who will be the newspaper's chairman.
   Jinks had been senior vice president for news and operations. The
appointment is effective April 1.
   Last April, Knight-Ridder's board of directors authorized the
repurchase of 5 million shares of the company's stock. At its
December meeting, the board authorized the repurchase of an
additional 5 million shares.
   Knight-Ridder currently has 30 newspapers as well as business
information services and cable television operations. Last October,
the company announced it intends to sell its eight television
stations, but has not yet concluded a sale.
</TEXT>
